<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Pensions     05-03 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Pensions,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>States Denied Chance To Tax Income From Federal Securities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than two weeks after creating a potential
new source of federal tax money, the Supreme Court is denying a
similar opportunity for state treasuries.
   The justices on Monday refused to let states tax pension fund
income from investments in federal government securities.
   On April 20, the court had ruled that the federal government may
tax the interest earned on state and municipal bonds.
   Although congressional leaders say there is no plan to impose
such taxes, the court's ruling last month cleared away a
constitutional hurdle in the event Congress some day changes
federal tax law.
   Justice William J. Brennan, writing for the court on April 20,
said giving the federal government power to tax state and municipal
bonds does not suggest that states should have reciprocal power.
   ``States can never tax the United States directly,'' he said.
``The federal tax immunity has always been greater than the states'
immunity.''
   That opinion was reinforced indirectly Monday as the court
rejected an appeal by Vermont officials seeking to tax income from
such federal obligations as treasury bills and short-term borrowing.
   Vermont officials said they should be allowed to tax the income
after it is distributed to retirees.
   The Vermont Supreme Court last December upheld a ruling by a
state judge who said the pension fund money is tax-exempt.
   Superior Court Judge Matthew I. Katz of Windsor County ruled
that interest on federal obligations is immune from state taxation
even when the income is passed on by a pension fund to a retired
investor.
   ``In practical operation, the tax in question was in fact a
state tax on interest derived from federal obligations,'' Katz
said. The fact that pension money was passed on to someone other
than the fund itself does not eliminate the exemption enjoyed by
investments in federal securities, he said.
   The judge rejected arguments by state officials that interest on
a government security is exempt ``only in the hands of the original
recipient unless there is a specific federal statute to pass
through the tax-exempt character of such income.''
   Katz ruled in favor of Loren D. Keys, who when he retired in
1981 received a lump-sum distribution of $141,000 from a savings
plan in which he had invested.
   The money included $35,000 in interest on federal securities.
   Vermont officials said Keys owed an additional tax of $1,246 on
the income from the government obligations. The court rulings in
Keys' favor meant he received a tax refund of $203 plus interest.
   Vermont officials said a lot more was at stake. They said the
state court rulings could force them to examine the source of
payments from pension and mutual funds, corporate dividends and
even bank deposit interest and then eliminate from the state's tax
base any income traced to investments in federal obligations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
