<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-DISTOFCOLUMBIAAt-A-Glance     05-03 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-DIST OF COLUMBIA At-A-Glance,210</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from the District of Columbia to attend the 1988
Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, May 3
   Presidential filing deadline: Friday, March 4, 1988
   Pledged delegates: 16 Super delegates: 7 TOTAL: 23
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, May 3
   Selection of delegates:Tuesday, May 3 and Thursday, June 9
   
   The District of Columbia picks its delegates to the Democratic
National Convention through a two-step caucus and primary system.
   Delegate candidates are slated according to presidential
preferences at caucuses held on Feb. 6 in two districts in the city.
   Allocation of the 11 district-level and three at-large national
convention delegates will depend on the results of the primary May
3.
   The two party and elected officials delegates will be picked by
the District of Columbia Democratic State Committee on June 9 and
will be allocated in proportion to the results of the primary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Tuesday, May 3
   Presidential filing deadline: Friday, March 4, 1988
   Delegates: 14
   Delegates allocated: Tuesday, May 3
   Selection of delegates: Tuesday, May 3
   
   District of Columbia Republicans will award all 14 of their
national convention delegates to the winner of the presidential
primary on May 3.
   The delegates are elected directly from the primary ballot and
all run at large.
</TEXT>
