<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF-Religious Death,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Christian Science Couple Plead Innocent in Son's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Christian Science couple pleaded innocent to
manslaughter in the death of their 2{-year-old son who died after
they refused to seek medical help for him because of their beliefs.
   David and Ginger Twitchell entered the plea at their arraignment
Monday in Suffolk Superior Court on charges stemming from the April
8, 1986, death of their son Robyn.
   Magistrate Gary Wilson set a pretrial conference for June 1, and
ordered the Twitchells, who have two other sons, released on their
recognizance.
   The Twitchells are the second Christian Science parents to be
prosecuted in Massachusetts and the first since 1971, when the
state amended the child abuse and neglect law to recognize
spiritual healing as an alternative to modern medicine.
   Followers of Christian Science refuse medicine or other health
care on the belief that true understanding of God acts as a cure.
</TEXT>
