<1ST_LINE>r i PM-LifeAbroad-Kenya     05-03 0792</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Life Abroad-Kenya,0818</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: Kenya _ Where Women Can Marry Women</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report. Spelling of Ochieng' with
apostrophe correct 23rd graf and thereafter.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents on the way of life in other
countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE FAUL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ancient custom permits one woman in Kenya
to take another as a ``wife,'' but a divorce case involving two
such women has thrown up a challenge to Kenya's Western-style legal
system.
   The case involves Wanjiru Gutu, a barren widow, who 10 years ago
took Mary Njeri Macharia as a ``wife'' to bear her the children she
desperately wanted.
   The relationship went sour and the women have asked a
Western-style divorce court to sort out their broken marriage,
including the question of alimony, child support and property
settlement.
   ``We don't have a precedent for this case,'' said Paul Mberi,
Ms. Macharia's lawyer.
   ``The problem we have is that our legal system as practiced in
the courts is changing to the Western legal system. But at the same
time, in the village we are living with people whose arrangements
are based on customary law concepts.''
   Marriage between women is not uncommon in Kenya and neither is
divorce.
   But this case is unique because the couple has turned to Western
laws, instead of adhering to custom and letting tribal elders
decide the issue.
   Barren women, such as Ms. Gutu, often take one or more fertile
women as ``wives'' to bear children, which the female ``husband''
then claims as her own. Even married women make such arrangements,
with the husband of the barren woman fathering children by his
spouse's wife.
   Barren women often are ostracized in Africa, where wealth and
prestige still are measured by the number of children a couple has.
   Since both Ms. Macharia and Ms. Gutu were single, Ms. Macharia
was entitled to choose the man to father the children.
   For the surrogate mother, such an arrangement offers the
security of a home and income.
   Ms. Macharia, in her late 20s, was a single mother of two
children, aged 12 and 10, when she married Ms. Gutu and took her
surname. She brought them to Ms. Gutu's home and had two more
children, now 7 and 5.
   After a fierce quarrel in January 1986, Ms. Gutu chased her
``wife'' from their matrimonial home in the western Kenyan town of
Nakuru, according to court records.
   Before turning to the Western-style courts, Ms. Macharia twice
went to a court of tribal elders, asking for alimony and child
support or a share of Ms. Gutu's property, including a small
grocery store.
   Ms. Gutu, about 60, complained that Ms. Macharia beat her,
threatened her life and stole from the business.
   Both times the elders ruled that Ms. Macharia could keep the
children but should receive nothing else.
   ``This was not a hardship in the past, as the woman would go
back to her father and his community, which jointly owned and
shared land and resources,'' explained Gibson Kamau Kuria, a
Nairobi lawyer who specializes in family law.
   Ms. Macharia did return to her father, a peasant farmer near
Nakuru. But when she felt that she and the children were a burden,
she sued her former ``husband'' for divorce in the district
magistrate's court, again demanding alimony and child support or a
share of Ms. Gutu's property.
   She filed suit in August 1986, but the case has been delayed by
a backlog and is expected to be heard soon.
   Ms. Gutu had told the tribal courts Ms. Macharia had no money or
property when they married, and that the relationsip gave her
status and a comfortable lifestyle.
   Odhiambo Ochieng', Ms. Gutu's lawyer, argues in an affidavit
that because the marriage is recognized only by customary law, only
a traditional solution is possible: for Ms. Macharia to return to
her father's family with nothing.
   Kenya's very diversity is at the root of the now-budding legal
problems.
   The East African nation's 22 million people are divided among
dozens of ethnic groups who abide by Islamic, Hindu and various
tribal customary laws in addition to the statutory Western laws
inherited from British colonizers at independence 25 years ago.
   A case last year pitted the widow of a prominent lawyer, S.M.
Otieno, against his Luo clansmen in a tussle over whether the widow
or the tribe should bury him. The High Court ruled that in the
absence of written law, customary law prevails.
   Otieno's widow lost.
   ``These problems are going to have to be tackled and will not go
away until Kenya is lived in by an overall younger and more modern
generation,'' Ochieng' said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0059EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis-Budget Bjt   05-03 0724</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis-Budget, Bjt,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Backers May Make Dukakis' Budget-Balancing Struggle A
Campaign Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael S. Dukakis, who has made his
efficiency as a manager one of the key selling points in his
presidential campaign, is struggling to balance his state budgets
for this year and next year.
   Dukakis' budget-balancing efforts are turning into something of
a balancing act, because his status as the Democratic front-runner
puts him under intense scrutiny.
   Supporters of Republican rival George Bush are hoping the
situation will provide them with ammunition they can use against
the governor.
   Dukakis boasts that he has given Massachusetts nine balanced
budgets as governor, including the current one for fiscal 1988, and
that he will do the same for the coming fiscal year.
   But he'll have to find some way to make up a $77 million revenue
shortfall this year, and already has proposed $233 million in
additional cuts to offset supplementary spending.
   ``We will make the necessary adjustments which will make it
possible for us to live within our income,'' Dukakis said last week.
   He said there are ``a number of ways to do that,'' but hasn't
said exactly which way he favors.
   Bush backers were rubbing their hands in anticipation.
   ``I think it raises a credibility issue for the governor,'' said
Sen. Paul Cellucci, George Bush's state campaign chairman. ``He has
talked about balancing a federal budget, yet it appears he is going
to have difficulty with a fiscal 1989 state budget.''
   Dukakis said he will work matters out with the legislature. But
some lawmakers are grumbling that that hasn't happened yet.
   ``You are telling us you are going to work with us, and you
haven't worked with us,'' Rep. Christopher Hodgkins, a Democrat on
the budget-writing House Ways and Means Committee, told Dukakis'
budget chief, Frank Keefe, during an appearance before the
committee last week.
   No one doubts that the budgets ultimately will be balanced,
because they must be under the state constitution. But how Dukakis
does it could become a campaign issue.
   ``He is either going to have to raise taxes or cut human
services spending, neither of which he wants to do. So it's
something we (Republicans) are obviously going to watch very
carefully,'' said Cellucci.
   Advocacy groups fighting to keep funding for their programs are
mindful of Dukakis' status as a presidential candidate.
   ``I think the governor running for president has created a
situation where the advocates feel that they can leverage his
cooperation more _ that they can make him look bad if they don't
get what they want,'' said Barbara Salisbury, the state budget
director.
   Dukakis and his aides have consistently said he will not cut
existing services to balance this year's budget, but will instead
clamp down on program expansions, primarily in human services. But
even that tactic is bringing complaints.
   ``People were promised ... they were going to get this service
and they still haven't gotten it yet,'' said Deborah Weinstein,
executive director of the Massachusetts Human Services Coalition.
``That is suffering and you can't take that away.''
   The Dukakis administration had projected 6.6 percent revenue
growth, but this week reduced its estimate to 5.7 percent. Even so,
House Ways and Means Chairman Richard Voke says the
administration's revenue estimates are too optimistic.
   A large part of the shortfall is blamed on smaller-than-expected
corporate tax collections due to a state law allowing state
companies to use losses on out-of-state subsidiaries to reduce
their Massachusetts tax bill.
   Dukakis has proposed changing this measure. Meanwhile, the state
has an appeal pending with the Massachusetts Supreme Court.
   The governor has proposed a $700 million package of savings and
revenue increases to balance his fiscal 1989 budget. Some of the
controversial features include:
   _Recouping $70 million in unclaimed bottle deposits from
beverage wholesalers. That issue is also before the courts.
   _Spending $22 million for more tax collectors _ some of the
nearly 1,600 new jobs contained in the budget _ to raise $190
million in new revenue.
   _Raising $55 million by requiring applicants for Medicaid
nursing home coverage to agree to a state lien on their homes for
reimbursement after they die. The administration has modified the
proposal to say Medicaid eligibility will be delayed after
applicants transfer assets to others, depending on the size of the
transfers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
