<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush     05-03 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Hits Dukakis Anew On Foreign Policy</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Bush leaves for West Virginia at 11 a.m. EDT; top prospects
uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush says Michael
Dukakis is displaying his lack of experience on foreign affairs
with ``macho'' talk about how to oust Panama's dictator.
   Bush was headed to Morgantown, W.Va., today to visit research
facilities at West Virginia University before returning home for a
belated victory party this evening to celebrate his clinching the
number of delegates needed to win the GOP presidential nomination.
   West Virginia's primary is a week from today.
   On a primary-eve campaign swing to Ohio and Indiana on Monday,
Bush ridiculed both Dukakis and Jesse Jackson for what the vice
president said was naivete about how Panaman's strongman, Manuel
Antonio Noriega, should be dealt with.
   ``You'd think it's a cinch listening to these guys: `Throw out
Noriega! Do this! Do that!''' Bush said.
   Noriega is under a U.S. drug indictment. In pressuring him to
step down, Bush said the United States must avoid moves that hurt
the Panamanian people or seem like some ``great bullying,
gringos-of-the-North kind of overstatement of power.''
   Bush told high school students in Vandalia, Ohio, that ``we're
still living down'' past military intervention in Central America.
   ``Ninety percent are now living under democracy in this
hemisphere. We don't want to set that back by some kind of macho
statement out of Harvard,'' Bush said. Dukakis was a lecturer at
Harvard's John F. Kennedy School of Government.
   Even with the nomination all but in hand, Bush was continuing to
campaign in primary states. On Wednesday, he heads to California,
which votes June 7.
   Bush's celebration tonight comes a week after he actually
obtained his mathematical lock on the nomination. He secured the
last few delegates he needed in the Pennsylvania primary on April
26.
   Aides had thought it would take today's round of contests _ in
Ohio, Indiana and the District of Columbia _ to put him over the
top.
   Bush told 1,200 supporters at the Canton Civic Center Monday
evening, ``They say, `What in God's name are you doing in Canton,
Ohio, when you got this Republican nomination wrapped up?' I will
not project in overconfidence. I will not project in arrogance.''
   ``I will work right down to the Republican convention and, with
your help, in the fall will be the next president of the United
States,'' he said. He predicted ``a classical confrontation'' in
the general election with a liberal Democrat nominee.
   Stephen Hart, a Bush spokesman, said President Reagan is not
expected at tonight's ``Over The Top'' celebration at a posh
Washington hotel. There had been speculation that Reagan, who has
stayed neutral during the GOP primaries, would use the occasion to
formally endorse Bush.
   Bush said in Mishawaka, Ind., on Monday, ``I had the feeling the
president did endorse me at lunch the other day.''
   That was a reference to a private White House meeting with the
president, at which Reagan congratulated him for his Pennsylvania
win and the White House indicated a formal endorsement would come
soon.
   Bush seemed exasperated when the question was raised again by
local reporters in Canton.
   ``Do you think there's any doubt in any credible person's mind
about who he's for? So what's the big deal?'' he said. ``You'll see
an endorsement soon, so stay tuned.''
</TEXT>
