<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Election     05-03 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Election,0761</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>View From The Provinces: It Doesn't Really Matter Who Wins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FOIX, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political joustings, coded language and
sophistictated election arguments of Paris fade long before they
reach this French provincial capital.
   To the residents of Foix, President Francois Mitterrand and
challenger Jacques Chirac are just about the same.
   ``Do you know what `bof' means?'' asks 80-year-old Roger Boy, a
retired draftsman, as he sipped his morning coffee on the main
square of this lovely town nestled in the foothills of the Pyrenees.
   Bof is a French expression that amounts to a verbal shrug. And
that's exactly how Boy and many other inhabitants of Foix view
Sunday's election runoff between the Socialist president and the
conservative premier.
   ``Whether its one or the other, things will continue just the
same,'' said Boy. ``It's `le bof' in general.
   Foix, a town of about 10,000 residents 500 miles from Paris, is
the capital of the Ariege Department, one of the least populated
districts of the country. It is dominated by the 11th century
chateau of the Counts of Foix perched on a massive rock overlooking
the town.
   The area has a long Socialist tradition, and because of this
Mitterrand is favored, but with more resignation than enthusiasm.
   On April 24, in the first round of voting, the Ariege gave
Mitterrand 41 percent of its vote, seven points above the
president's national score, and 18 percent to Chirac, two points
under his overall showing.
   Mitterrand no doubt will win again here Sunday, but it will be a
gut vote more than a carefully reasoned choice.
   Jacques Doumenc, who for the past 25 years has been the local
correspondent for the Toulouse newspaper 50 miles away, put it best
when he said the things people here really care about are
television reception and a proposed tunnel to Spain.
   ``Mitterrand doesn't have a program for after May 8,'' said
Gerard Firon, a local homebuilder. ``Really, there is no
fundamental difference between the two. And they both need the Le
Pen vote.''
   Jean-Marie Le Pen, leader of the extreme right National Front,
won 14.4 percent in the first round, stunning many political
observers. Le Pen campaigned hard on a platform of ridding France
of its immigrants and cracking down on law and order.
   In the Ariege, despite its leftist tradition, Le Pen won 10.3
percent. It's hard to find somebody who will own up to voting for
the extreme right and many Fuxiens, as local residents are called,
were looking suspiciously at their neighbors last week.
   Bernard Rouch lounged on a bench in Foix's packed criminal
court, wearing the traditional black bailiff's robe. A crowd waited
for the jury to return its verdict in a sensational local murder
case.
   ``The Ariege is a place where we live well,'' he said. ``There
is no pollution, no racism. There is unemployment, yes ... but we
live well. I don't know about Le Pen. It's a rejection phenomenon.''
   Despite the lack of enthusiasm for Mitterrand, polls after the
first round show him winning the runoff by scores ranging from
53-47 percent to 57-43 percent.
   Mitterrand ``still represents a popular image that no other
political group can match,'' said defense attorney Yves Saez, just
before the jury convicted his client and sentenced her to 12 years
in prison for bludgeoning her husband to death.
   In the Cafe de la Mairie on the night of the great debate
between Mitterrand and Chirac, most of the clientele sat in the
back room drinking and socializing. Up front, where the debate was
on the television, only a few folks paid attention.
   Lined up on a bench were four working-class men in their 30s and
40s, stonefaced, arms crossed. After the two-hour debate, they got
up as a unit and left. One of them, in another typical French
mannerism, expressed his opinion by filling his cheeks with air and
letting it out with a soft puff.
   ``They're all the same.''
   The next morning at the farmers' market, a peasant selling her
cheese declared herself for Mitterrand, but was hard put to explain
why.
   ``We live on agricultural subsidies,'' she said. ``For peasants
it's an absolute necessity.''
   Has Chirac threatened to cut subsidies?
   ``Well, you have the feeling that you are listened to under the
left. Under the right, decisions are made without consultation, and
that's it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AtomicVeterans     05-03 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Atomic Veterans,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Aides Recommend Veto of Benefits for `Atomic Veterans'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's advisers are recommending
that he veto a bill which would grant some new benefits to ``atomic
veterans,'' the American servicemen exposed to radiation in the
1945 occupation of Japan or during post-World War II tests of
nuclear weapons.
   The bill was sent to Reagan after the House approved it Monday
on a 326-2 vote, which would be far above the two-thirds majority
needed to override any veto.
   However, the Senate margin last week was just 48-30, indicating
that a veto could be sustained there.
   The Veterans Administration opposes the bill and says there is
no direct evidence proving that the veterans' exposure is causing
current health problems.
   The bill was part of a larger measure authorizing benefits for
some 2.7 million veterans. But it was stripped out after
administration officials said they would recommend a veto of the
overall bill because of the ``atomic veterans'' provision.
   The measure would cover an estimated 250,000 U.S. military
personnel who were in Hiroshima or Nagasaki after U.S. atomic bombs
were dropped on those Japanese cities in August 1945, or who took
part in open-air tests of U.S. nuclear weapons in the southern
Pacific Ocean or in Nevada after the war.
   Many have health problems which they say are related to their
radiation exposure. But the Veterans Administration says they can't
get disability benefits unless they can show a direct link to their
service duty.
   The bill establishes a presumptive link and sets out 13 types of
cancers for which the veterans could receive disability payments.
   According to Rep. J. Roy Rowland, D-Ga., the VA has only allowed
44 of the 6,000 claims filed by atomic veterans.
   The chairman of the House Veterans Affairs Committee, Rep. G.V.
Montgomery, D-Miss., said the VA's standard can't be met because
``the level of exposure cannot be verified.''
   He said that during the tests, some personnel didn't wear
radiation-monitoring badges, other servicemen lost their badges and
some badges were found to be ineffective.
   Rep. Bob McEwen, R-Ohio, called the bill ``a reasonable and
modest approach'' to the problem. ``If we err in our approach, and
I think we do not, then we err on the side of compassion,'' he said.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearCooperation     05-03 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Cooperation,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Soviet Delegations Discuss Building New Nuclear Power Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of a Soviet delegation says
prospects are good for collaboration with a U.S. company to develop
new nuclear power reactors.
   The company, GA Technologies of San Diego, Calif., built the
only working commercial gas-cooled reactor in the United States,
the Fort St. Vrain plant of Colorado Public Service Co. near Denver.
   A joint U.S.-Soviet committee on peaceful uses of atomic energy
last week visited GA Technologies for talks on development of
so-called modular high-temperature gas-cooled reactors.
   In a ceremony at the State Department on Monday in which the
heads of both delegations signed a document recommending renewal of
the cooperation agreement, the Soviet chairman, Alexandor N.
Protsenko, said, ``We think the prospects are very good for
collaboration with (GA Technologies) in this area, as well as with
other companies.''
   The agreement was begun by President Nixon and Soviet leader
Leonid Brezhnev in 1973. It was renewed in 1983 and 1985.
   Asked just what form cooperation with GA Technologies might
take, Protsenko, who is chairman of the state committee for the
utilization of atomic energy, said through an interpreter the
Soviet and United States delegations were discussing ``a possible
collaborative program with (the company) in the context of the
general agreement.''
   But, he added, ``We don't exclude the possibility that our
cooperation will lead to a time where we might have a separate
agreement'' with GA Technologies.
   Gas-cooled reactors have been widely used in Europe, but neither
the Soviet Union nor the United States has favored them for
civilian power.
   They do offer certain safety advantages, such as slow reaction
to disturbances. Modular designs, which could be built efficiently
in small sizes so utilities could add generating capacity only as
needed, have attracted increasing attention both in the United
States and the Soviet Union, and the Soviets plan to complete
construction of two in 1995.
   The modular high-temperature gas-cooled reactor is ``a good
example of a safe, economically feasible new generation of
reactor,'' Protsenko said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
