<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HospitalCruise     05-03 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hospital Cruise,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Team Helps Chronically Ill Enjoy Cruise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audrey Deetz thought her traveling days were
over when she was diagnosed as having emphysema. But this week
she's packing for her third Caribbean cruise, accompanied by a
hospital medical team.
   For the third year, University Hospitals of Cleveland is sending
a doctor, nurses and therapists on a week-long cruise with a group
of people with chronic lung diseases. The trip begins Sunday from
Fort Lauderdale with ports of call including Jamaica and Grand
Cayman.
   ``You might say we're all in the same boat,'' said the
73-year-old Ms. Deetz. ``We all have something in common. We
understand each other's problems.''
   Dr. Michael Nochomovitz, medical director of the hospital's
Pulmonary Treatment Center, said many people with breathing
problems are afraid to travel because of their unstable health.
   ``They live for years with the anxiety of something happening
suddenly,'' said Nochomovitz, who went on the first two trips.
``Cruise lines are not equipped to handle complex medical illnesses
and you can't expect them to be.''
   He said the hospital-sponsored cruise developed after a patient
brought up the problem of traveling. Besides the patient's fear,
there's the problem of carrying oxygen supplies and other medical
equipment along, he said.
   Some airlines and cruise lines won't allow the equipment, a
situation that Nochomovitz wants changed.
   ``Somehow we've got to set up a system to accommodate these
people so they can live as near as normal lives as possible,'' he
said.
   University Hospitals plans the cruise with a supplier of home
medical equipment that publicizes the trip among its customers. The
first cruise drew about 25 people, including 17 patients. Last
year, the group swelled to 80 people, about half patients, from
more than a dozen states.
   The cost of the cruise ranges from $1,600 to $2,000.
   Nochomovitz said this year's trip was almost canceled because of
Coast Guard restrictions on portable oxygen tanks on cruise ships.
But Nochomovitz said an exemption was obtained to allow about three
dozen to make the trip.
   Some past participants hadn't traveled for years because of
their health problems, said Nochomovitz. ``For many of the
patients, this is a goal,'' he said.
   The trip has many side effects as well, he added.
   ``It's humbling to see how this experience improves on the
patient's sense of well being, achievement and independence,''
Nochomovitz said.
   Ms. Deetz said the first hospital-sponsored cruise gave her the
confidence to continue traveling.
   She was found to have emphysema about four years ago, after
returning from a trip to Stockholm. The cruise was her next trip.
   ``I thought (my travels) were over and that's why I jumped at
the first cruise,'' said Ms. Deetz, of suburban Berea.
   Next week's cruise will be her fifth in three years, and she's
planning a trip to Europe this summer with one of her three sons.
She takes along a breathing machine for daily treatment.
   ``I enjoy the cruises. They're really wonderful for people like
me,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
