<DOCNO> AP880503-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WritingCure     05-03 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writing Cure,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Through Writing, Ex-Mental Patient Finds A Cure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN GEORGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some people write as a hobby,
scribbling in journals or dashing off verse and short stories for
nothing more than their own pleasure.
   Others, be they authors of flashy ad campaigns, creators of TV
sitcoms or this year's Hemingway, are blessed with enough talent
and good fortune to do it for money.
   But Van Garner, a mental patient-turned-poet and songwriter,
uses his typewriter to exorcise the demons that led him to two
nervous breakdowns and a bout with alcoholism.
   ``It's been the real savior for me, writing,'' he says,
``because it gave me a chance to bring out my inner feelings.''
   Garner, 55, of Chattanooga, is the author of ``Deep Within,'' a
recently published collection of poetry, and a gospel music album,
``Polished by the Master,'' to be released this month.
   His voice deliberate and thoughtful, his eyes lively, there's
little in Garner's demeanor to suggest his rocky past. But his work
is the culmination of a journey that began 28 years ago at Warner
Robins Air Force Base in Georgia.
   That's where Garner was stationed when he suffered his first
nervous breakdown. Although granted an honorable discharge after
observation by military officials, he soon checked into a Veterans
Administration mental hospital in Murfreesboro.
   The doctors diagnosed him as a paranoid schizophrenic: He
suffered from feelings of persecution marked by flights of fantasy,
illogical thinking and hallucinations.
   ``I would be depressed one moment, then I'd go to another
extreme and be as high as a kite,'' he said.
   He spent three months in locked confinement. Then another
patient suggested he enter a Hospitalized Veterans Writing Project
contest. Reluctantly, he submitted an article.
   Then another, and some short stories and poetry. Nearly all
focused on his illness. One poem, ``The Apple,'' read in part:
   ``Take an apple from a tree;
   Pretend that apple is me;
   Now cut the apple in half,
   Hear one part cry, one part laugh!''
   He won some prizes, but that wasn't the important thing. Putting
the words down seemed to release something within him.
   ``The more I wrote, the better I felt,'' Garner said.
   In 1965, after five years of hospitalization, he was discharged.
``I literally wrote myself out of the hospital,'' he said.
   Two years later, he met and married Helen, his wife of 21 years.
He suffered another nervous breakdown and was hospitalized for
three months in 1972, but he hasn't been back in the hospital.
   Garner's work has appeared in numerous poetry anthologies, and
he has published two collections of short stories.
   Dick Green, whose G&G Publishers of Nashville published ``Deep
Within,'' remembered his first impression of Garner's poetry.
   ``He was almost like an inner soul crying out,'' Green said.
``There was something there that really sort of got to me.''
   Garner doesn't expect his efforts to make him rich. But he
figures he's already done pretty well.
   ``I want to tell people what I went through so it may help
someone else who may say, `Well, this is the end. I had a nervous
breakdown, and this is the end of the world,''' he said.
   ``But it isn't the end. It's just the beginning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0025 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-747 3rdLd-Writethru a0818 05-03 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-747, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0818,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Probe Opened Into Apparent Engine Failure On United Jet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with investigation Tuesday,
quotes from passengers. Pickup 8th graf pvs, ``Passengers
cheered...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese authorities on Tuesday investigated the
apparent engine failures that caused a United Airlines jumbo jet
with 258 people aboard to make an emergency landing with only one
of its four engines working.
   The plane landed safely Monday after two of the engines stopped
over the Pacific and the third stopped just before the landing, an
airline official said.
   Kyodo News Service, quoting airport and airline officials it did
not identify, said the pilot shut off the engines after noticing
problems with fuel gauges. It was not known if that meant the plane
was running out of fuel.
   United spokesman Katsuro Isa said emergency vehicles stood by at
the New Tokyo International Airport in Narita, 40 miles northeast
of Tokyo, but the Boeing 747 taxied to the terminal under its own
power.
   None of the 239 passengers and 19 crew members on the Los
Angeles-Tokyo flight was injured, he said.
   UAL Flight 97 was 39,000 feet above the Pacific and about 125
miles from Narita when the first engine stopped, Kyodo reported.
   Isa said that half an hour later, 45 minutes before landing, the
second engine stopped and the pilot radioed the Narita control
tower for an ``expedited approach.'' The third engine stopped
shortly before the plane landed at 3:17 p.m.
   Passenger Shinobu Murota, 21, said flight attendants ordered
people to put on life jackets as the plane approached Japan and
said they might have to make an emergency landing.
   ``A few minutes later the sound of the engine suddenly stopped,
and I felt as if the plane was floating in the air like a hang
glider,'' Ms. Murota told The Associated Press.
   Passengers cheered and applauded when the Boeing 747-100 settled
on the runway, Kyodo said.
   ``I expected death at any moment,'' it quoted Kazuko Kato as
saying. Mrs. Kato, who was returning from her honeymoon, shouted at
her husband when the plane landed: ``Thank goodness we didn't die!''
   Boeing spokesman David Jimenez in Seattle, Wash., said the safe
landing did not surprise him.
   ``Almost any aircraft we have is capable of operating on one
engine,'' he said. Jimenez said he did not know of another 747
losing power in three engines.
   A Tokyo newspaper, the Yomiuri Shimbun, said in its Tuesday
editions that while the jumbo jet was some 120 miles from Narita
control tower authorities at the airport received the following
message from the pilot: ``Out of the four main engines, the
condition of No. 1 and No. 4 engines at both ends is bad and I want
to make an emergency landing.''
   The newspaper account added, ``According to the Transport
Ministry, the Narita airport office and the airline, during the
flight the gauge that indicates how much fuel is feeding into the
engine from the fuel tank showed there was almost no fuel going
into engines number 1 and 4 and that the No. 3 engine was also
malfunctioning.
   ``For this reason, the pilot turned off the number 1 and 4
engines at about 2:00 p.m. and 2:40 p.m. (Tuesday local time)
consecutively. After requesting emergency landing permission from
control authorities, he turned off engine 3 just before beginning
to glide in for a landing.''
   A statement released by United Airlines in Chicago said in part
that about one hour and 15 minutes before the jetliner landed ``it
lost power in one of the four engines. About 30 minutes later they
lost power to a second engine. And just before landing they lost
power to a third engine. The plane landed safely and taxied to the
terminal under its own power where the passengers deplaned in a
normal fashion. The cause of the incident is still under
investigtion.''
   The mishap occurred several hours after the government urged
Japanese airlines to ground and do maintenance checks on Boeing 737
jets of the model that lost part of its fuselage last week on an
inter-island flight in Hawaii.
   An official of the Transport Ministry's engineering deparment
said the 21 Boeing 737s in Japan are operated by All Nippon
Airways, Air Nippon and the airline Nansei Koku.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0238EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-ConventionProtests     05-03 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Convention Protests,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say They'll Try To Work With Protest Groups At Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DICK PETTYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police say they'll try to work with groups
planning demonstrations during this summer's Democratic National
Convention but warn that space is limited and that protests will
have to be scheduled.
   Only five groups have applied so far for demonstration permits
during the July convention, but many more are expected.
   ``We assume we'll have a lot of diverse groups here and, to the
extent we can accommodate them, we plan to,'' said Deputy Chief
W.J. Taylor. ``We don't want anyone to feel they are not welcome.''
   However, the American Civil Liberties Union charged last week
that was exactly what was happening, and threatened legal action
unless the city clarified the procedures it intends to follow for
handling protest groups.
   The ACLU's key complaint is that the city has not adopted rules
and procedures for permitting demonstrations, Margaret L. Dudney, a
staff attorney for the organization's Georgia chapter, said Monday.
   She also contended that the city has not said whether it intends
to adhere to existing rules requiring seven days' notice for street
marches and 30 days' notice to hold political gatherings in parks.
   In addition, some city officials have indicated that downtown
parks will not be available for demonstrations, she said.
   Taylor said those problems are being addressed.
   ``The problem is, there's not that much available space,'' he
said.
   Taylor said the city is trying to secure two parking lots
directly across from The Omni, the convention site, to serve as
staging areas for demonstrations. Some downtown parks also may be
used, he said.
   The advance-notice rules for street demonstrations and park use
will be waived, he said, so long as organized groups have obtained
permits.
   No applications have been processed yet, and none will be acted
on until June, he said.
   Those already seeking permits are the International Society for
Krishna Consciousness; the Lenora Fulani Committee, which supports
Ms. Fulani's New York-based New Alliance Party campaign for the
presidency; a committee supporting legislative equality for
homosexuals; a local group calling itself ``Arts Pluribus Unum'';
and another local group called Alternative 88. The group was formed
by the owners of the Metroplex nightclub in Atlanta.
   Partner James Fleter said the group is designed to serve as ``a
loose coordinating group for different groups that will be raising
First Amendment and alternative issues.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
