<HEAD>Women's Representatives Differ On Robins Reorganization Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Advocates for women who used the Dalkon Shield
are divided on the merits of a reorganization plan involving the
manufacturer of the defective contraceptive devices and
establishing a trust fund for victims.
   One representative of the victims, Atlanta-based attorney Guerry
R. Thornton Jr., said the plan offers the best deal yet for the
more than 196,000 women harmed by the intrauterine device.
   But Karen Hicks, founder of the Dalkon Shield Information
Network, told a news conference Monday: ``After an agonizing
decision-making and education process, we have found that the plan
is unfair, inadequate and contrary to the law.''
   The $3.2 billion reorganization plan _ the sixth plan developed
since Robins filled for Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1985 _ is part of
the Manhattan-based American Home Products Corp.'s agreement to
take over the beleaguered company. The $3.2 billion plan includes
$2.3 billion to be put in a trust fund for the victims.
</TEXT>
