<HEAD>Resolution Condemns Soviet Religious Persecution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has added his signature to a
Senate resolution urging the United States to refrain from
participating in June ceremonies marking the millennium of
Christianity in the Soviet Union if religious persecution there
persists.
   The resolution, signed by the president on Monday, deplores
persecution by the Soviet government of religious believers in the
Ukraine. The document also expresses congressional concern for
Ukrainian religious believers who are persecuted for attempting to
worship.
   The June ceremonies will mark the founding of Christianity in
Kievan Rus', an area now within the Ukraine, 1,000 years ago.
   Last Friday, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev condemned past
anti-religious repression and called for a more tolerate attitude
toward religion.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bone Marrow Cells A Site For AIDS Virus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government scientist says researchers have
found that the bone marrow can become a quiet haven for the deadly
AIDS virus, adding to the types of cells in the body known to be
attacked by the virus.
   Anthony S. Fauci, director of the National Institute of Allergy
and Infectious Diseases, said Monday that the bone marrow, which is
the body's blood-making organ, ``can be a reservoir'' for the virus.
   ``It (the AIDS virus) can reside in the marrow, but not be
detected in the peripheral blood,'' he said.
   The finding demonstrates just how challenging it will be to
develop an antiviral drug or vaccine to defeat the AIDS virus, said
Fauci. In order to effect a cure, some way will have to be found to
seek out and destroy the virus wherever it hides.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>World Bank Lowers Status of Its Loans to Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank has placed its loans to Panama
on ``non-accrual status,'' making the accounting change because the
country has paid nothing for six months on the $502 million it owes.
   The change in status, announced Monday, means the bank no longer
includes on its own statements the interest and other charges due
from Panama until money is actually received.
   ``Placing loans in a non-accrual status is an accounting action
which does not reduce in any way the country's obligation to the
bank or the bank's ability to assist the country in formulating
policies to help redress its economic difficulties,'' the
announcement said.
   The bank, owned by 151 countries, is the biggest single source
of aid money for the Third World. The United States is the largest
shareholder.
</TEXT>
