<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DeathPenalty     05-03 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Death Penalty,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Approves Death Penalty Legislation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state Assembly approved legislation
Monday to restore the death penalty in New York state and sent it
to Gov. Mario Cuomo's desk, where it faces a certain veto.
   It was the 12th straight year the Legislature approved a death
penalty bill. Six times from 1977-82 the measures were vetoed by
former Gov. Hugh Carey and five times since then by fellow Democrat
Cuomo.
   As in years past, the Democratic-controlled Assembly failed
Monday to come up with the 100 votes needed in the 150-member house
to override Cuomo's impending veto. The vote Monday was 92-53.
   The Assembly's chief death penalty advocate, Democrat Vincent
Graber, said it was important that the Legislature ``address this
issue each and every year until someday, somehow we're able to get
to that needed 100 votes. We're only some five or six votes short.
Our day will come for sure.''
</TEXT>
