<HEAD>Gang Film `Colors' No. 1, Squeezing Out `Beetlejuice'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After three weeks in the nation's movie
theaters, the gang film ``Colors'' has moved past ``Beetlejuice''
as the No. 1 box office attraction.
   ``Colors,'' with Sean Penn as a cocky rookie cop teamed with the
savvy veteran Robert Duvall, nearly tripled its coverage last
weekend _ from 480 screens to 1,372 _ and took in $6.5 million in
its third week of release while the comedy ``Beetlejuice'' dropped
to second with a $5 million take.
   After the top two finishers, box office receipts plummeted.
   The teen-oriented film ``Casual Sex?'' was third with $2.4
million and the violent ``Above the Law,'' featuring a Chicago
cop's drug-ring battle, was fourth with $2.3 million.
   Fifth was ``Biloxi Blues,'' starring Matthew Broderick as an
Army boot camp private, with $2.1 million in its sixth week of
release.
   In sixth was the new James Garner-Bruce Willis film ``Sunset,''
which earned $2 million in its debut weekend. ``Bloodsport'' was
seventh at $1.9 million.
   ``Critters II: The Main Course'' made its debut as No. 8.
   ``The Last Emperior,'' the Bernardo Bertolucci epic that won
nine Academy Awards, was ninth with $1.7 million and
``Moonstruck,'' was 10th with $1.5 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release, and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Colors,'' Orion, $6.52 million, 1,372 screens, $4,755 per
screen, $18.7 million, three weeks, $12 million.
   2. ``Beetlejuice,'' Warner Bros., $5.01 million, 1,582 screens,
$3,172 per screen, $46.7 million, five weeks, $20 million.
   3. ``Casual Sex?,'' Universal, $2.43 million, 1,265 screens,
$1,925 per screen, $7.32 million, two weeks, $9 million.
   4. ``Above the Law,'' Warner Bros., $2.39 million, 852 screens,
$2,808 per screen, $11.67 million, four weeks, $14 million.
   5. ``Biloxi Blues,'' Universal, $2.1 million, 1,162 screens,
$1,810 per screen, $34.2 million, six weeks, $16 million.
   6. ``Sunset,'' Tri-Star, $2.03 million, 1,023 screens, $1,986
per screen, $2.03 million, one week, n-a.
   7. ``Bloodsport,'' Cannon, $1.92 million, 784 screens, $2,458
per screen, $6.4 million, 10 weeks, n-a.
   8. ``Critters II: The Main Course,'' New Line, $1.89 million,
1,114 screens, $1,704 per screen, $1.89 million one week, n-a.
   9. ``The Last Emperor,'' Columbia, $1.78 million, 852 screens,
$2,125 per screen, $35.6 million, 23 weeks, $25 million.
   10. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $1.57 million, 897 screens, $1,756
per screen, $69.12 million, 19 weeks, $17 million.
</TEXT>
