<HEAD>Thames Filled With Fanciful Floats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A giant green dragon, a water-spouting whale and a
golden barge propelled by oarsmen in 17th-century garb temporarily
turned the Thames into a very weird waterway.
   Sir Greville Spratt, lord mayor of London, led the fancy
flotilla of floats up the river on Monday as part of a charity
drive to raise $465,000 for the Independent Television children's
charity telethon.
   The waterborne procession was based on a Thames pageant devised
in 1613 by dramatist Thomas Middleton.
   The floats swept up the river from the newly developed Docklands
area, past the Tower of London and under Tower Bridge to Festival
Pier to present a check to the telethon. The amount of the check,
representing contributions from businesses, will be disclosed May
29 when the telethon is broadcast.
