<HEAD>Mayor Accepts Apology From Aide Over Slurs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer on Monday accepted a written
apology to the public from an aide whose religious slurs prompted
aldermen and others to demand his dismissal. But Sawyer said the
apology might not be sufficient.
   ``I humbly apologize to Chicago residents of all races and
religious groups who were offended by remarks made prior to my
ascension to the mayor's office,'' said a letter signed by Steve
Cokely, a $35,000-a-year mayoral aide.
   ``I have, since working in the mayor's office, respected all
those I have had the privilege to serve,'' added the apology,
distributed by the mayor's office.
   ``No one has accused me of abusing the privilege of working for
Mayor Sawyer. Mayor Sawyer has discussed with me, in a firm and
gentlemanly manner, what he expects from all employees of the
mayor's office.''
   Later Monday at a gathering of Jewish business leaders, Sawyer
said: ``This afternoon, a young man issued an apology that might
not be sufficient ... We will not tolerate an individual with views
of this type.
   ``We are reviewing the situation, and we will have something to
say about it in the very near future,'' Sawyer added.
   Alderman Bernard L. Stone called Monday for the immediate ouster
of the 35-year-old aide. Alderman Edwin Eisendrath said the City
Council would take up the matter next week if the mayor fails to
act.
   Cokely, who serves as a liaison to black nationalist groups,
said in four tape-recorded lectures before the Chicago-based Nation
of Islam between August 1985 and November 1987 that Jewish doctors
were guilty of injecting blacks with the AIDS virus and that a
Christian crucifix is a symbol of white supremacy, according to
published reports over the weekend.
</TEXT>
