<HEAD>Bus Strike Ends In Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 400 bus drivers are back on the job
after ending a two-day strike caused by a wage dispute with a
private bus company.
   The drivers in southern Taiwan went back to work on Monday after
accepting an offer from Kaohsiung Bus Co. for a 10 percent wage
increase.
   About 90,000 passengers travel daily on the bus lines.
   Strikes were banned in Taiwan under martial rule, imposed in
1949 when the Nationalists fled to Taiwan after losing a civil war
to the communists on the China mainland. The government lifted
martial law in July 1987.
