<1ST_LINE>r p PM-StatePrimaryRdp     05-03 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-State Primary Rdp,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Candidates for Governor Chosen in Indiana, NC; Ohio Senate Race
Takes Shape</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic voters choose nominees for governor in Indiana and
North Carolina today, and in Ohio they are expected to nominate
Sen. Howard Metzenbaum for a third term, pitting him against
Cleveland's Republican Mayor George Voinovich in November.
   Presidential primaries are being held in Ohio and Indiana, and
in Washington, D.C.
   North Carolina did its presidential primary voting as part of
the Super Tuesday on March 8.
   With Indiana's GOP Gov. Robert Orr forced by law to retire after
two terms, the governor's race is viewed by Democrats as a golden
opportunity to recapture an office they have not held in 20 years.
   Secretary of State Evan Bayh, 32-year-old son of former Sen.
Birch Bayh, is the leading contender, opposed only by former Kokomo
Mayor Stephen J. Daily. Senate Minority Leader Frank L. O'Bannon's
name was put on the Democratic ballot by Bayh's campaign when it
appeared Bayh might be held in violation of the state's five-year
residency requirement. But the state Supreme Court ruled last week
that Bayh could run.
   Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, who is the only Republican candidate, has
pointed to his own experience as a 20-year veteran of the General
Assembly and executive branch and tried to make an issue of Bayh's
age.
   ``We're not talking about electing somebody class president
here,'' said Mutz, 52.
   ``Age is not relevant,'' countered Bayh. ``It's ability. It's
ideas. It's where you hope to lead Indiana.''
   Indiana also has a Senate race this year, with Republican Sen.
Richard G. Lugar unopposed for nomination to a third term. The lone
Democratic contender is Indianapolis attorney Jack Wickes, formerly
with Gary Hart's campaign staff.
   In North Carolina, Gov. Jim Martin is unopposed for renomination
as he tries to become the first Republican in the state to serve
consecutive terms as governor this century.
   Leading a field of five Democrats is Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan, who
has portrayed Martin as doing little of substance and trying to
take credit for Democrats' accomplishments.
   ``North Carolina doesn't need a governor who is content to be a
passenger or a back-seat driver,'' Jordan said in January after
driving an 18-wheel truck from his family lumberyard in Mount
Gilead to Raleigh to dramatize his ``hands-on'' management style.
   Opposing Jordan are Billy Martin, a service-station employee not
related to the governor; Bruce Friedman, an anti-nuclear activist
from Sylva; Carroll W. Crawford of Mount Ulla, who said he quit the
Ku Klux Klan in 1987 but remains sympathetic to some of its causes;
and James T. Lloyd of Salisbury.
   In Ohio's Senate race, the popular Voinovich is unopposed on the
GOP side, while Metzenbaum is heavily favored over Ralph Applegate,
a political newcomer from Columbus who has hardly been heard from
since filing in February.
   The fall campaign promises to be a high-spending one, with
Federal Election Commission reports showing that Metzenbaum had
raised $4.4 million as of March 31. That's the third-highest amount
of any incumbent senator seeking re-election this year.
   Voinovich, who raised $2.9 million by the same date, had
initially criticized his rival for collecting money out of state.
But he recently announced his own fund-raising drive in major
cities around the country.
   Ohio also two congressional races of note. GOP Rep. Delbert
Latta is retiring in rural Northwest Ohio, and the Republican
candidates include his attorney son, Robert, State Senate President
Paul Gillmor, of Port Clinton, and Rex Damschroder, of Fremont.
   And in Cleveland, Rep. Mary Rose Oakar, who seeks her sixth
term, is pitted in a Democratic primary against Dennis Kucinich,
the former Cleveland mayor who has attracted large numbers of
blue-collar votes in the past.
</TEXT>
