<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     05-03 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's finest probably won't win any fashion
contests with a new uniform they're testing, but at least they
won't have to shine their shoes, crease their pants or polish their
gunbelt buckles.
   ``It's quite different, but it doesn't look that different,''
Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said Monday as two
nervous-looking police officers modeled the new threads.
   The new uniform will be worn by 135 officers citywide for the
next year. If it passes final inspection, the duty jacket,
raincoat, shirt, trousers, gunbelt and shoes will become mandatory
for the city's 27,000 police officers.
   The changes reflect New York's busy lifestyle that calls for
minimal upkeep, and includes machine washable shirts; pants with a
permanent crease; shoes that don't need to be shined and a gunbelt
with a non-tarnish buckle.
   The new jacket, a lightweight poly-wool blend, has four
gold-plated buttons to give it the appearance of a dress coat, but
is actually closed by a concealed plastic zipper with a Velcro
closure.
   ``You don't lose the buttons, and yet you have the traditional
appearance of the buttons,'' Ward said approvingly.
   The most visible change is the placement of the Police
Department patch on both sleeves of the duty jacket, raincoat and
shirts. Currently officers wear the patch only on their right
shoulders.
   ``On the old uniform, if you happened to be facing the wrong
way, you wouldn't know whether this was a police officer or a
private security guard in a dark suit,'' Ward said.
   As usual, convenience doesn't come cheap. The new uniform costs
$476, versus the $350 for the current uniform.
   ``This is a great improvement over what I wore,'' Ward said,
recalling that his leather uniform coat ``was heavy and it wasn't
warm.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORANGE BEACH, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technique doesn't count for much when
throwing fish, but kissing may help, says the winner of the fourth
annual Interstate Mullet Toss.
   Steve King of Pensacola, Fla., won the men's division Sunday by
tossing a mullet 111 feet, 7 inches across the state line from
Florida to Alabama.
   ``We bought a couple of mullet last week,'' King said. ``We
tried to make them spiral and be aerodynamic, but it didn't work.
You just gotta grab it and throw it.''
   A day earlier in the preliminaries, King got off a toss of 171
feet, 6 inches, about 30 feet farther than the record set in 1986.
But it won't go into the record books because only final round
throws qualify.
   ``I know what happened,'' King said after his shorter toss into
a strong head wind. ``I didn't kiss (the mullet) today. Yesterday,
I kissed him. That helps.''
   Vickie Andrews of Thomasville won the women's competition with a
toss of 72 feet, 1 inch.
   ``I throw one every day,'' Ms. Andrews said. ``The first thing I
do when I get up is throw a mullet.''
   About 200 people attended the competition as part of the Greater
Gulf Coast Beach Party.
   Mullet are about 8 to 10 inches long and popular for fish fries
along the Florida Panhandle and Alabama coast. Appropriately
enough, mullet are related to flying fish.
</TEXT>
