<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0310EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Arthritis Bjt   05-03 0588</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arthritis, Bjt,0604</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arthritis Gene Identified In Mice; Early Step Toward Human Cure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers seeking to cure crippling
diseases like arthritis and multiple sclerosis in humans say
they've taken an early, important step by isolating the gene that
causes a form of arthritis in mice.
   ``We are on the way to finding the cure for this type of
arthritis in mice,'' Tariq M. Haqqi, a molecular biologist at the
Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., said Monday.
   If the same kinds of arthritis-causing genes _ or inherited
blueprints _ can be identified in humans, ``we are one step closer
to the cure and prevention of human rheumatoid arthritis and other
human auto-immune diseases'' in which the body apparently is
attacked by its own disease-fighting immune system, Haqqi said.
   Discovery of the gene Vb6 that causes mouse arthritis was
outlined by Haqqi during the annual meeting of the Federation of
American Societies for Experimental Biology, which drew 22,000
scientists and exhibitors.
   The discovery is ``very exciting'' because it is the first time
scientists have isolated a gene that causes arthritis, said Dr. C.
Garrison Fathman, an immunologist-rheumatologist at Stanford
University.
   But he said it still will take scientists years to find a cure
for rheumatoid arthritis, which afflicts 7 million Americans, or
any of the other 100 forms of arthritis and related diseases such
as lupus, multiple sclerosis and juvenile or insulin-dependent
diabetes.
   Fathman recently used what are called monoclonal antibodies,
proteins made in the laboratory to target specific types of cells,
to attack T cells _ a type of white blood cell in the immune system
_ that cause diabetes in mice. The mice were cured, he reported
Friday in the journal Science.
   Haqqi is now trying to cure mice of arthritis by using other
tailor-made monoclonal antibodies to attack the T cells responsible
for that disease without harming other white blood cells, which are
needed to defend the body against infection.
   T cells normally help fight infection by recognizing an invading
germ or foreign substance and then triggering production of
antibodies to combat them. But bacterial and viral infections also
can trigger auto-immune diseases.
   Haqqi and his colleagues identified and isolated the gene that
codes for production of a certain receptor on the surface of T
cells in mice.
   Haqqi said this receptor causes the T cells to lose their
ability to distinguish foreign collagen, or connective tissue, from
the collagen naturally found in cartilage, tendon and skin.
   So the T cells attack collagen in cartilage in the mice's
joints, causing the inflammation, swelling and pain known as
arthritis.
   Scientists from the Howard Hughes Medical Institute at
Washington University in St. Louis and from the University of
Tennessee in Memphis also worked on the study, in which mice
developed arthritis when injected with collagen from cows. The
disease is similar to crippling rheumatoid arthritis in humans.
   If researchers can identify the genes for human T cell receptors
that go awry to cause human arthritis and other auto-immune
diseases, ``then we can cure the disease'' and prevent it by
producing monoclonal antibodies to attack the culprit T cells while
leaving other white blood cells unharmed, Haqqi said.
   But, he cautioned, ``the antibody that works in mice may not
work in humans, so we'll have to find the antibody that works in
humans.''
   Fathman agreed, saying different monoclonal antibodies would be
needed not only for every form of arthritis and auto-immune
disease, but possibly for each individual human.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0320EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--Korea-AIDS     05-03 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Korea-AIDS,0162</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korea To Begin Producing Anti-AIDS Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A South Korean pharmaceutical company
was given permission today to begin mass producing and exporting an
anti-AIDS drug at cut-rate prices, officials said.
   The Health and Social Affairs Ministry said Samchully
Pharmaceutical Co. received a permit to manufacture and export
Azidothymidine (AZT).
   But domestic sales of the drug will not be allowed until
clinical tests are completed, the ministry said.
   The drug, first developed in Britain as an anti-cancer drug, can
lengthen the lives of patients suffering from acquired immune
deficiency syndrome by restraining development of the virus that
causes the disease.
   Export plans call for producing the drug at about half the
international price of $155 for 100 milligrams, officials said.
Exports to the United States and Western Europe are expected to
begin as early as next month, they said.
   Plans call for exporting about $10 million worth of AZT annually.
</TEXT>
