<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0349EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MonitorSalvage     05-03 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Monitor Salvage,0585</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Engineer Says Uncertain If Civil War Ship Monitor Should Be
Salvaged</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An engineer studying the sunken Civil War ship
USS Monitor says it could cost $20 million to raise the ironclad
vessel from its 125-year-old grave off North Carolina.
   But James Jenkins, a corrosion and metallurgical engineer with
the Navy Civil Engineering Laboratory in Port Hueneme, Calif., also
said that federal officials are uncertain whether to raise the ship.
   ``Personally, I'd like to make sure anything done there is done
carefully so we don't waste the 120 years that it's been down
there,'' Jenkins said Monday at the Offshore Technology Conference
here. ``We really don't know today what could or should be done.''
   Already, $3 million has been spent on research, and estimates of
costs to raise the ship range from $10 million to $20 million, he
said.
   ``There are major structural components, like the armored deck,
the turret, the guns, the engine and the boilers, that appear to be
relatively intact and probably could be retrieved,'' he said.
   On New Year's Eve 1862, the USS Monitor sank in a storm off Cape
Hatteras.
   Nine months earlier, on March 9, 1862, it battled the
Confederate vessel Merrimack to a draw in the first combat between
two ironclad ships. Neither ship was able to inflict serious damage
on the other in the battle, which occurred at Hampton Roads off
Virginia.
   The Merrimack, renamed the Virginia by the Confederates, was
scuttled two months later when Southern forces abandoned the
Norfolk navy yard. The Merrimack was discovered in 1910, its
armored plates retrieved and sold as souvenirs, Jenkins said.
   ``We don't want that to happen to the Monitor, to have pieces of
it on the end of keychains,'' he said. ``We don't want people going
in and we don't want souvenir hunters, a la the Titanic.''
   The Monitor suffered extensive damage while being depth-charged
during World War II when it mistakenly was believed to be a German
submarine. It was not until 1973 that Duke University researchers
said they believed the wreck was the Monitor. Photographs made two
years later confirmed that.
   Last year, Jenkins coordinated a corrosion survey of the
Monitor, using Norwegian-made electronic probes attached to
remote-controlled underwater gear. The probes normally are used to
test the corrosion of offshore drilling rigs and the investigation
of the Monitor marked one of the first times oilfield technology
was applied to marine archeology, he said.
   The Monitor is in about 230 feet of water, upside down, with its
two-gun turret _ made of foot-thick wrought iron and weighing 120
tons _ supporting about 90 feet of the deck above the sea floor.
   Although corrosion has set in, Jenkins said, it's important to
note that less than one-half inch of material has been lost.
   ``Corrosion rates tend to drop over long periods of time,'' he
said.
   As an engineer, Jenkins said the wreck is significant because it
provides corrosion data over 120 years.
   The wreck in 1975 was designated the first National Marine
Sanctuary.
   Jenkins said technology exists to preserve what it left of the
ship or the debris around the vessel could be retrieved or
officials can take no action at all.
   ``We have a lot more plans than money,'' he said. ``Its value is
as a fingerprint of society and a fingerprint of shipbuilding in
the 1860s.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
