<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AgathaChristie     05-03 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Agatha Christie,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rights to Christie Books Sold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rights to 87 books by the queen of suspense,
Agatha Christie, have been purchased by the Putnam Berkley Group as
part of a package sold by the ailing publishing house Dodd Mead &
Co.
   The price of the purchase, which also included 156 works by
Western writer Max Brand, was not released. But The New York Times
reported today that it was thought to be about $4 million.
   Dodd Mead, a 149-year-old firm, sold the rights in an effort to
retire its debt and survive as an independent publisher. The
purchase also included several titles on sailing and Dodd Mead's
entire juvenile list, which was 44 of its 154 titles last year.
   Jerome H. Grossman, chairman of Dodd Mead, said problems during
the past two years included paying advances that were not justified
by sales, printing more books than necessary and signing up too
many books in light of the firm's debt.
   The company's major assets were the rights to the Brand and
Christie books. It acquired the rights to the Christie books
starting in 1921 and Brand in 1927. Brand was a pen name for
Frederick Schiller Faust, who was killed on the Italian front while
covering World War II for Harper's magazine. Ms. Christie died in
1976.
</TEXT>
