<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0427EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama     05-03 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama,0598</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Of U.S. Deal With Noriega Alarm Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition party leaders said they
were alarmed by reports of a U.S. deal that would force Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega to resign as head of the military but allow him to
remain in Panama.
   In another development, an official of the bilateral commission
that runs the Panama Canal said the waterway continues to do a
thriving business despite the nation's protracted economic and
political crisis.
   The opposition leaders discussed the reported deal Monday at
what they called their first meeting since Panama's crisis began
nearly a year ago.
   ``We met to discuss jointly the grave situation of our country
and what we may do together to find a democratic solution for our
country,'' said Ricardo Arias Calderon, who held the two-hour
meeting at his home.
   The opposition wants Noriega, the power behind the civilian
government, to resign as commander of the 15,000-member Defense
Forces and leave the country.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions on Panama
designed to oust Noriega and has called for him to leave Panama.
Some U.S. political leaders say it would be a mistake if the United
States backed off that stance.
   The sanctions, which have caused an economic crisis in Panama,
were imposed after Noriega was indicted in February on U.S. drug
trafficking charges.
   Following Monday's meeting some of the opposition leaders said
they were alarmed by reports of a deal that would allow Noriega to
remain in Panama.
   The leaders discussed ``everything that has to do with the
serious crisis,'' including the reported arrangement between
Washington and Noriega, said one source at the meeting, who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   U.S. officials in Washington have said Noriega agreed to step
down as commander of the Defense Forces but refused to leave
Panama. Treasury Secretary James A. Baker said on Sunday that U.S.
talks with Noriega continued during the weekend and that ``progress
is being made.'' Noriega denied on Saturday he had reached any
agreement with the United States.
   Sources in the opposition say their leaders are afraid the
United States is bypassing them and ignoring promises to them. They
say if Noriega quits but remains in Panama he will continue to
wield power through the Defense Forces. ``He would continue to be a
focus of controversy,'' Arias Calderon said Monday.
   The Christian Democrats, the second largest opposition party,
called Monday's meeting. Also attending were representatives of the
Authentic Panamanian Party, the Republican Party of ousted
President Eric Arturo Delvalle, the Liberal Republican Nationalist
Movement and factions of the Liberal and Labor parties. The
Authentic Panamanian Party is the largest opposition party followed
by the Christian Democrats.
   Delvalle was deposed Feb. 26, the day after he tried to fire
Noriega.
   Such concerns have not reduced traffic in the Panama Canal.
   ``Business is almost embarrassingly high,'' said Richard A.
Wainio, chief of economic research and market development for the
Panama Canal Commission. He said on Monday that the canal is
running smoothly because neither the United States nor Panama
``wants to jeopardize operation of the canal.''
   Five Americans and five Panamanians make up the commission,
established under 1977 treaties that will turn the canal ove to
Panama at the end of 1999.
   During the first five months of fiscal 1988, toll revenues came
to $143.6 million, $4.6 million higher than anticipated.
   Wainio said he expects income to match expenses the rest of the
year.
</TEXT>
