<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TinyBaby     05-03 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tiny Baby,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tiny Baby Goes Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A premature baby so small she could fit
in her mother's hand when she was born has gone home from the
hospital _ cradled in her mother's arms.
   Elsa Marie Gustafson weighed only 15 ounces and was 10{ inches
long when she was born three months premature on Jan. 11 at Oak
Knoll Naval Hospital. She left the hospital for her home in Vallejo
on Monday, weighing 4-pounds, 10 ounces, and measuring 15 inches.
   ``It is remarkable the way she has caught up in growth,'' said
Cmdr. David R. Field, who delivered Elsa, the smallest surviving
premature baby in the hospital's 46-year history. ``I consider her
a miracle baby.''
   The tiny infant also survived heart and lung surgery.
   ``She was just a slip of a thing in Saran Wrap to keep the
moisture and heat in and I thought `that's my baby,''' said her
mother, Navy Lt. Linda Prince-Gustafson, 39.
   ``The first night was hard,'' she said, ``because every time the
door to my room opened I kept expecting them to tell me that she
had died, but on the contrary, everybody said she was going to be
OK.''
   Elsa's father, Lt. Cmdr. Water A. Gustafson, said their
confidence was boosted after she made it through the first day.
   ``Everything was in the Lord's hands,'' he said.
   Elsa was delivered by Caesarean section after doctors found her
mother had high blood pressure and that her placenta wasn't
functioning properly.
   Doctors first estimated Elsa's survival chances at 10 percent to
15 percent.
   Elsa will remain connected to an oxygen tank for a few more
months.
   Her father said the baby still mostly just eats and sleeps but
there are a few hours a day when she's ``pretty interactive.''
   ``We think she's smiling a lot and surprisingly responsive. We
receive a lot from her and she's a positive influence on our
lives.''
</TEXT>
