<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LehderTrial     05-03 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lehder Trial,0348</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cocaine-Smuggling Case Could Go To Jury Next Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cocaine-smuggling trial of reputed
Colombian drug lord Carlos Lehder Rivas could go to the jury next
week, after his lawyers shocked the courtroom by resting their case
without calling witnesses.
   U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton scheduled closing arguments
to begin next Monday, and attorneys estimated they could last up to
three days.
   The judge also denied a defense motion Monday to sequester the
jury during closing arguments, which defense attorneys complained
will come during ``Just Say No To Drugs Week.''
   Lehder, 38, is accused of smuggling 3.3 tons of cocaine into the
United States from his private island, Norman's Cay in the Bahamas.
   A federal indictment names Lehder as one of the leaders of
Colombia's Medellin cartel, believed to be responsible for 80
percent of the cocaine smuggled into United States _ a bonanza
worth $8 billion each year.
   Defense attorney Edward R. Shohat stunned the courtroom Monday
when he announced the defense would rest without calling any
witnesses to counter the 115 prosecution witnesses who testified
during a 22-week period. He refused to discuss the move with
reporters.
   ``You could honestly say I looked surprised and stunned,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller said later. The jury did not
show any visible reaction.
   Stephen Weinbaum, an attorney for co-defendant Jack Carlton
Reed, also rested without calling any witnesses.
   That tactic is used by defense attorneys ``to keep the
sufficiency of the government's case at issue,'' Weinbaum said.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy; possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute; importation of cocaine; and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise. Reed, 57, of San Pedro, Calif., is
charged with being a member of the smuggling conspiracy.
   If convicted of all 11 counts, Lehder could be sentenced to a
maximum sentence of life plus 165 years. Reed would face a possible
15 year-sentence.
   Lehder also is also charged in separate indictments in Los
Angeles and Miami.
</TEXT>
