<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Collapse     05-03 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Collapse,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three More Bodied Recovered From Indian Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers recovered three more bodies
today from the wreckage of a children's hospital annex that
collapsed in northern India, the United News of India said. The
discovery raised the official death toll to 17.
   UNI quoted hospital authorities as saying as many as 32 people,
including 22 children, were still unaccounted for and that the
death toll could rise.
   Arun Joshi, a reporter for the Kashmir Times, said rescuers were
losing hope of finding anyone alive. ``It is a terrible sight up
here,'' he said. ``No one knows how many children have died or are
dying.''
   Rescue workers pulled 30 people alive from the rubble of the
three-story hospital wing on Monday, UNI said. Twenty-three of
them, mostly children, were being treated at a makeshift emergency
center, state-run All India Radio said.
   Civilians, police and army units with cranes today removed
blocks of concrete and brick at the site. R.S. Chib, the state's
health minister, told UNI he expected rescue operations to be
completed tonight.
   The collapse of several wards in the hospital annex was blamed
on structural defects. The Statesman newspaper said four wards
collapsed in the wing of the hospital, which was built four years
ago.
   The newspaper said each ward had 17 beds and some contained more
than one child. In addition to hospital staff, parents and
relatives were attending some of the children when the accident
occurred, the paper said.
   In Jammu, a city of 500,000 more than 300 miles north of New
Delhi, most stores and businesses closed today in sympathy for the
victims and their families. Stores also were reported closed in
neighboring towns.
   Satish Gupta, a Jammu police department spokesman, said the
collapse apparently was caused by a weak foundation under the
hospital wing. The older wing of the hospital was still standing.
   Joshi said cracks had developed over the weekend in the ground
floor walls. He said one doctor told him the cracks widened Sunday
and he evacuated 35 children. The three civil engineers who oversaw
construction of the hospital wing have been suspended, news reports
said. They did not elaborate.
</TEXT>
