<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FraternityRape     05-03 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fraternity Rape,0385</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida State Fraternity Ordered Disbanded Five Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida State University ordered a
fraternity to disband for five years for a rape of a teen-age
student at the fraternity house and subsequent cover-up, officials
said.
   ``I hope what we're doing sends out a message we do take this
very seriously,'' Dean of Students James Hayes said Monday. ``The
nature of the whole incident was so serious that to be responsible
you have to take action.''
   University officials accepted a recommendation after a four-day
hearing by an administrative hearing panel made up of a student,
faculty member and staff representative.
   Hayes announced the sanctions just 10 days after a strongly
worded grand jury interim report urged university officials to
crack down on Pi Kappa Alpha fraternity, where the woman was
allegedly raped March 5 by two fraternity members.
   The grand jury report issued last month said the 18-year-old
victim was raped by more than one person and left in a
life-threatening condition of intoxication. She suffered several
scratches and abrasions and had crude words and a fraternity symbol
scrawled on her thighs.
   Other fraternity members allegedly tried to block the
university's investigation, which led to the arrest of three men.
   ``The question of not cooperating was a pretty serious one,''
Hayes said.
   The fraternity's president, Brant Byrd of Belleair, denied
claims that the fraternity failed to cooperate.
   ``I know that we cooperated with the FSU police from the
beginning and we'll continue to,'' Byrd said.
   The fraternity, which has about 170 members, has until May 15 to
appeal the sanctions.
   Fraternity members Daniel G. Oltarsh, 23, of Fort Lauderdale and
Byron L. Stewart, 21, of Orlando were charged with sexual battery.
Jason J. McPharlin, 19, of Plantation, a Pi Kappa Alpha member at
Auburn University, was charged with being an accessory to a felony
and failing to report a sexual battery.
   Oltarsh and Stewart were freed on $10,000 bond last week, while
McPharlin was freed on $6,000 bond.
   The Pi Kappa Alpha chapter at Stetson University in Deland,
about 250 miles southeast of Tallahassee, was suspended for one
year by school officials last week following rape allegations. No
criminal charges were filed.
</TEXT>
