<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Press     05-03 0707</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Press,0730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israelis Raid Arab Newspaper, Detain Managing Editor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with raid on Arab newspaper,
editor arrested, comments. Pickup 4th pvs, ``Israel officials...''
EDITS to TRIM</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RONI C. RABIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli security forces raided a Palestinian
newspaper and detained the managing editor, police and newspaper
officials said today.
   Hannah Siniora, editor of the Arab- and English-language Al Fajr
newspaper in east Jerusalem, sharply criticized the Monday night
raid. It followed the closing Monday of the Palestinian weekly, Al
Awdah, and was the latest in a series of measures taken against
journalists.
   ``I feel all these oppressive measures will backlash against the
peace process,'' he told The Associated Press today. ``Journalists
apparently are being singled out for special attention.''
   A police official confirmed that Israeli authorities carried out
the raid, and security sources said managing editor Hatem Abdul
Khader would be jailed for six months without trial under Israeli
emergency regulations. The officials spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Since unrest began in the occupied territories Dec. 8, Israeli
authorities have shut two pro-Palestinian newspapers and a press
agency, arrested 22 reporters, most of them Arabs, and lifted the
credentials of two American correspondents.
   The authorities said they closed Al Awdah, the only
English-language weekly magazine published in east Jerusalem
because it received funding from terrorist organizations. The
magazine's publisher, Ibrahim Kara'een, denied the charge.
   Siniora said it was not clear why Al Fajr's managing editor was
detained.
   ``We are making inquiries with our lawyers today about what
actions to take,'' Siniora said.
   The army also has periodically closed large areas of the
occupied territories to journalists and empowered local commanders
to chase them from the scene of trouble spots.
   Israeli officials have blamed television cameras for stoking the
fires of the uprising and accused the press of maintaining a double
standard, taking Israel to task for actions that are overlooked
elsewhere in the world.
   ``A sort of paranoia has developed about the media,'' said Yariv
Ben-Eliezer, a professor of film and communications at Tel-Aviv
University. ``Soldiers always ask, `Why is the media against us?'
and students ask the same question.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's spokesman, Avi Pazner,
acknowledged Israelis feel resentment toward the media.
   The media ``have given us the short end of the stick _ they
didn't tell the whole of the Israeli side of the story,'' Pazner
said. ``No wonder there is resentment.''
   He stressed, however, that Israel has made no changes in its
policy of freedom of the press.
   ``We scrupulously maintain our principle of safeguarding the
freedom of the press in the country,'' Pazner said. ``There are
very few countries in the world that would allow this kind of
freedom, in the situation we have been in during the last months.''
   Monday's actions followed the six-month closure in March of Al
Awdah's sister organization, the English-language Palestine Press
Service, a key source of information on the occupied territories.
   Israel also shut down a left-wing, pro-Arab Israeli newspaper,
Derech Hanitzotz. The Press Service and Derech Hanitzotz were
charged with maintaining links with terror organizations.
   Since its February closing, four editors of the Israeli
newspaper, including three Israelis, have been arrested and accused
of membership in guerrilla groups.
   At least 18 Palestinian journalists are in jail, many held under
administrative detention orders which allow imprisonment for up to
six months without trial, according to a representative of the Arab
Journalists Association, who asked not to be identified for fear of
reprisals.
   Israel has also periodically barred the distribution of
Arabic-language newspapers in the occupied territories.
   Last month, the government suspended the press credentials of
foreign correspondents Glenn Frankel of the Washington Post and
Martin Fletcher of NBC News after they published details of the
assassination of a PLO leader without submitting them to military
censorship.
   Since the uprising began, the Foreign Press Association, which
represents 200 foreign journalists working in Israel, has received
between 100 and 150 complaints of harassment and physical attacks
by Israeli troops and Jewish settlers, said Robert Slater, the
group's chairman.
   ``There is a feeling among many people that the media should be
taken out of the territories, that if you don't see it, it isn't
there,'' Ben-Eliezer said.
</TEXT>
