<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PasswordFraud     05-03 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Password Fraud,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Game Show Winner Sentenced for Insurance Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was the biggest single-game winner
on the TV game show ``Super Password'' has been sentenced to five
years in prison for an insurance scheme in which he falsely said
his wife was dead.
   U.S. District Court Judge William Byrne on Monday also ordered
Kerry Dee Ketchem to repay $100,000 to an insurance company and
said prosecutors were correct in calling Ketchem a ``con man and a
thief.''
   Ketchem, 36, who had been living in San Bernardino, admitted
fraudulently collecting the $100,000 from an insurance policy by
saying his wife had been killed in an auto accident.
   Ketchem's wife Kelly Ann, who had not been living with her
husband, told FBI agents she was unaware he had collected on the
policy, held by Amex Life Insurance Co. of San Rafael.
   Ketchem admitted obtaining a death certificate and accident
report from a U.S. Air Force Base in England and filling them out
to fake his wife's death.
   Investigators later found Mrs. Ketchem on active duty at
Lackland AFB in Texas, where she had been transferred.
   Ketchem pleaded guilty March 14 to two counts of a six-count
mail-fraud indictment returned by a federal grand jury in San
Francisco.
   Ketchem had used the name Patrick Quinn to appear on the TV
show, which was seen by an Alaskan banker who recognized Ketchem as
the man who allegedly ran up about $25,000 in credit in Alaska by
fraudulently obtaining credit cards.
   Authorities arrested Ketchem when he tried to pick up $58,600 in
winnings from his appearance on ``Super Password.''
   Ketchem told the judge he used the other name to hide his assets
from his wife, whom he was divorcing.
   NBC has announced it will not give Ketchem his winnings because
he lied about his name while on the show, posing as a government
employee. In a move show officials called ``unbelievable,'' Ketchem
sent a Mailgram from his jail cell demanding the cash and saying
the show had received ``priceless free publicity because of me.''
</TEXT>
