<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0802EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Antarctica     05-03 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Antarctica,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks To Set Rules For Mining In Antarctica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives from 37 nations
have opened a monthlong meeting aimed at hammering out
international rules governing the mining of oil, gas and other
minerals in Antarctica.
   The talks were opened Monday by Foreign Minister Russell
Marshall.
   Environmentalists, such as the Greenpeace organization, are
strongly opposed to any mining in Antarctica and say the
mineral-rich continent could one day ignite a military conflict as
the world's natural resources dwindle.
   Greenpeace, which conducts scientitic research in Antarctica, is
campaigning to have the continent a ``world park.''
   But to others, in particular the 19 countries operating
geological programs there, Antarctica is rich in mineral resources
waiting to be extracted.
   The United States, which is represented at the meeting,
estimates there are 48 billion barrels of offshore petroleum
reserves and vast quantities of coal, copper, gold and uranium in
Antarctica.
   Marshall told representatives from the 37 Antarctic Treaty
nations there was no reference to mining in a 1959 Antarctic Treaty
and the meeting would fill that gap. In 1977, the nations agreed to
voluntary mineral restraints.
   Chris Beeby, deputy secretary of foreign affairs, said it had
not been determined whether mining should ever be allowed
Antarctica.
</TEXT>
