<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DysonAide     05-03 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dyson Aide,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman's Aide Wrote of `Ill Winds That Taunt Us' Before
Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top aide to U.S. Rep. Roy Dyson wrote an
eight-line poem that spoke of ``ill winds that taunt us'' shortly
before jumping out a window in his New York City hotel room to his
death, The Sun reported today.
   Tom Pappas, administrative assistant to the Maryland Democrat,
died Sunday after talking with colleagues about a front-page
article that appeared in The Washington Post. The story said
Pappas, 46, recruited young, single men as employees and pressured
them to socialize with him.
   The Sun today quoted an unidentified source close to the police
investigation as saying Pappas' poem read, in part, ``Ill winds
that taunt us through peace and understanding will not cause us to
have a crash-landing.''
   The verse also spoke of the ``dark and ugly world.''
   ``Goodbye'' was neatly printed on the lined notebook paper that
bore no addressee, The New York Times reported. Police called the
death a suicide.
   Meanwhile, Maryland Republican leaders considered asking a GOP
congressional candidate to step aside so a stronger opponent could
challenge Dyson.
   The Post article quoted former Dyson aides as saying the
congressman had ceded control of his office to Pappas. Some staff
members complained about Pappas' unusual demands, including one
that an unidentified employee perform a striptease at a staff
retreat.
   Dyson, Pappas and Todd Skipper, another aide, were in New York
to meet with a lawyer and attend the Broadway musical ``Phantom of
the Opera,'' police there said.
   Republican leaders said Monday they are thinking of asking Wayne
Gilchrest, a political novice who won the party's nomination in the
March primary, to consider stepping aside so a better-known
candidate can challenge Dyson.
   But they said they won't try to force Gilchrest out, and
Gilchrest said he would not withdraw.
   ``I was given the `10 count' the day after the primary,'' he
said. ``I think I'm more electable than anybody has imagined.''
   Gilchrest, a former high school social studies teacher who has
never held public office, works as a counselor at Chesapeake
College. His campaign has no paid staffers and he estimates he so
far has raised only about $1,000.
   Democratic officials Monday predicted Dyson, 39, would win
re-election in November.
</TEXT>
