<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Violinist-Arson     05-03 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Violinist-Arson,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Concert Violinist-Landlord Sentenced to 15 Years to Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge said he was sending ``a warning to
landlords'' when he sentenced a Russian emigre violinist to 15
years to life in prison for hiring arsonists to burn an occupied
apartment house he owned.
   The landlord, Gregory Gelman, 39, who has performed at Carnegie
Hall, insisted at his sentencing Monday that he was innocent.
   ``The truth did not come out at trial. People lied under oath,''
Gelman protested when state Supreme Court Justice Jeffrey Atlas
sentenced him.
   Gelman's lawyer, Irving Cohen, asked the judge for leniency and
said his client had been frustrated and financially hobbled by the
complexities of the city's housing laws. Gelman, who came to this
country 10 years ago, is a graduate of the Juilliard School of
Music.
   Gelman, married and the father of a 2-year-old daughter, was
unable to make an adequate living at his profession, according to
Cohen, so he became a landlord. He owns four buildings.
   Atlas, who heard Gelman's two-month trial without a jury, told
the defendant that he convicted him only after finding him guilty
beyond a reasonable doubt. The judge also said he could not believe
Gelman's assertion that virtually every prosecution witness had
lied.
   The judge said the sentence, imposed under a recently enacted
``arson-for-profit'' law, should be ``a warning to landlords that
their financial problems will not be solved by burning down their
buildings.''
   Atlas convicted Gelman on Oct. 6 of first-degree arson,
second-degree conspiracy and first-degree reckless endangerment for
torching his five-story building in the Chelsea section of
Manhattan on Feb. 24, 1986 while a rent strike was on.
   Assistant District Attorney Suzanne Flamm said Gelman wanted to
burn the 15 tenants out so he could collect $250,000 in insurance
money and then rent to tenants who would not be covered by rent
control or rent stabilization laws.
   Gelman hired four men to torch the building, but two were
seriously burned when the 40 gallons of gasoline they had brought
into the building ignited. The four pleaded guilty to third-degree
arson and are awaiting sentencing.
   The building's occupants escaped the blaze without injuries and
moved back into their apartment after repairs were made.
   Ms. Flamm, observing that the value of Gelman's building
increased after he bought it, said, ``He could have made a handsome
profit without arson but profit was not enough.''
   Gelman blamed the tenants for his troubles. ``The tenants did
not pay for two years,'' he said. ``In New York, being a landlord
you can never win.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
