<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JetBlast     05-03 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jet Blast,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigators Find More Weakened Rivets In Aloha's Boeing 737 Jet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KAHULUI, Hawaii (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two fuselage panels on an Aloha Airlines
jetliner that ripped open at 24,000 feet had several rivets showing
signs of cracking, but officials are not sure if the cracks were
present before the accident.
   More electronic tests of rivets along a key strip of the plane's
structure were scheduled for today as investigators near the end of
their field work, Joseph Nall, a member of the National
Transportation Safety Board, said Monday.
   A 20-foot section of the Boeing 737's upper fuselage ripped off
as it flew across the Hawaiian Islands on Thursday, killing a
flight attendant and injuring 61 of the 89 passengers.
   Tests were done on 760 rivets and 30 were found cracked, he said.
   None of the bad rivets were next to each other and they were
randomly scattered along the length of the aircraft, he said.
   In normal maintenance, rivets usually are checked visually for
cracks resulting from metal fatigue, and a focus of the
investigation will be whether that method is adequate, Nall said.
   The pilot of Aloha's Flight 243, Capt. Robert Schornstheimer,
and co-pilot Mimi Tompkins, returned to Maui from Honolulu on
Monday to look at the crippled plane they managed to land.
   ``They had not seen the floor beams and were just as amazed as
the rest of us. Our investigators have been scratching their heads
that the aircraft held itself together,'' Nall said.
   Nall said he hopes the accident forces the airline industry to
reassess its maintenance methods and take another look at ``high
cycle'' aircraft, meaning older, heavily used planes.
   The Federal Aviation Administration has ordered the oldest
versions of the Boeing 737s not to fly above 23,000 feet.
   Meanwhile, family members, friends and hundreds of fellow
workers at Aloha Airlines gathered in a hangar at Honolulu
International Airport on Monday for a memorial service for missing
flight attendant, Clarabelle ``C.B.'' Lansing, 57, who was swept
out of the plane when it tore open.
   Seven injured passengers remained hositalized in Maui Memorial
Hospital in stable condition, according to a nursing supervisor.
</TEXT>
