<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0840EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NewCaledonia     05-03 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New Caledonia,0322</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Refuses To Allow Officials Transport To Ouvea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL DONNET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government refused to allow
three rightist elected officials to go today to the island of
Ouvea, where Melanesian separatists are holding 23 police officers
hostage in a cave.
   The main pro-independence organization, the Kanak Socialist
National Liberation Front, also rejected the offer.
   Dick Ukeiwe, who represents the French Pacific island territory
in the French Senate, said he and two National Assembly members,
Jacques Lafleur and Maurice Nenou, want to change places with the
hostages.
   Lafleur asked that an airplane be made available for the three
men to go to Ouvea. The request was refused.
   ``Given the present situation and the talks in progress, the
government has decided to not accept this proposition,'' said a
official in the High Commission in Noumea, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Transportation to Ouvea, in the Loyalty Islands group east of
New Caledonia's main island, has been interrupted since separatists
attacked a police station in the village of Fayaoue on April 22,
killing four policemen and taking others hostage.
   New Caledonia, a French possession since 1853, is about 1,000
miles east of Australia and has been the scene of sporadic violence
since 1984.
   About 43 percent of New Caledonia's 145,000 people are native
Melanesians, known as Kanaks, and many of them favor independence.
About 36 percent are Europeans, who generally want to remain part
of France. The rest are mostly Asian or Polynesian.
   Ukeiwe, Lafleur and Nenou are members of the rightist Rally for
the Republic, and are prominent opponents of the separatist
movement.
   The hostages include the head of an anti-terrorism squad and an
assistant prosecutor. The hostages are being held in a cave in a
remote part of Ouvea, which lies off the east coast of New
Caledonia's main island, La Grande Terre.
</TEXT>
