<1ST_LINE>r a BC-History 1stLd-Writethru b0167 05-03 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-History, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0167,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Today in History</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS James Brown's age to 55, sted 60, in next-to-last
graf. Original moved in advance as b0167 on April 25</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Tuesday, May 3, the 124th day of 1988. There are 242
days left in the year.
   Today's Highlight in History:
   On May 3, 1802, Washington, D.C., was incorporated as a city,
with the mayor to be appointed by the president, and the council
elected by property owners.
   On this date:
   In 1654, a bridge in Rowley, Mass., was permitted to charge a
toll for animals, while people crossed for free.
   In 1765, the first U.S. medical school was proposed at the
College of Philadelphia, now the University of Pennsylvania.
   In 1916, Irish nationalist Patrick Pearse and two others were
executed by the British for their roles in the Easter Rising.
   In 1921, West Virginia imposed the first state sales tax.
   In 1933, Nellie Taylor Ross became the first woman director of
the U.S. Mint.
   In 1937, Margaret Mitchell won a Pulitzer Prize for her novel,
``Gone With the Wind.''
   In 1948, Pulitzer Prizes were awarded to playwright Tennessee
Williams for ``A Streetcar Named Desire'' and to novelist James
Michener for ``Tales of the South Pacific.''
   In 1948, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that covenants prohibiting
the sale of real estate to blacks and other minorities were legally
unenforceable.
   In 1971, anti-war protesters, calling themselves the ``Mayday
Tribe,'' began four days of demonstrations in Washington aimed at
shutting down the nation's capital.
   In 1979, Conservative Party leader Margaret Thatcher was elected
Britain's first female prime minister.
   In 1986, in NASA's first post-Challenger launch, an unmanned
Delta rocket, lost power in its main engine shortly after liftoff,
forcing safety officers to destroy it by remote control.
   Ten years ago: ``Sun Day'' fell on a Wednesday as thousands of
people extolling the virtues of solar energy held ceremonies,
demonstrations and other events across the country.
   Five years ago: After two years of debate, U.S. Roman Catholic
bishops overwhelmingly approved a pastoral letter that condemned
the first use of nuclear weapons, virtually ruled out their use for
retaliation and demanded a halt to the growth of superpower
arsenals.
   One year ago: The Miami Herald published a story in its Sunday
editions saying its reporters had observed a young woman spending
``Friday night and most of Saturday'' at a Washington townhouse
belonging to Democratic presidential candidate Gary Hart.
   Today's Birthdays: Broadway librettist Betty Comden is 69. Folk
singer Pete Seeger is 69. Former boxing champion Sugar Ray Robinson
is 68. Singer James Brown is 55. Singer Engelbert Humperdinck is
52. Singer Frankie Valli is 51. Magician Doug Henning is 41.
   Thought for Today: ``Great minds discuss ideas, average minds
discuss events, small minds discuss people.'' _ Adm. Hyman G.
Rickover, ``father'' of America's nuclear navy (1900-1986).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0905EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Soviets-Change     05-03 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviets-Change,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Panelists Propose 2-Party System, Other Sweeping Changes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union could limit terms
of office of high-ranking officials and develop a two-party system
in the near future, a panel of Soviet officials said during a
conference on U.S.-U.S.S.R. relations.
   American participants at Monday's conference appeared skeptical
upon hearing those and other statements from their Russian
counterparts, who outlined plans to revitalize Soviet society after
what they called ``10 years of stagnation.''
   ``We are only in the beginning of the process,'' said Nikolai
Shislin, a member of the Central Committee of the Communist Party,
the Soviet Union's only political party.
   ``In five, seven, 10 years _ I don't know'' how many parties
there might be, he said.
   ``I'd like to see more evidence,'' said George Kessinger,
president of Goodwill Industries of Orange County. He said he'd
like to visit the Soviet Union to see such changes for himself.
   ``If half of what they say is true, there's an amazing thing
going on,'' said Kessinger.
   Sergei Plekhanov, deputy director of the Soviet Institute for
USA and Candada Studies, said a greater separation of power is part
of the goal.
   ``We are talking about introducing the rule of law in the Soviet
Union,'' he said. ``But do we want to turn into a litigious society?
   ``We want ... the judiciary empowered to pass judgment on laws
and a legislature with more independence,'' Plekhanov said. ``But
do we want to create a class of professional politicians?''
   The panel discussion was one of many events at the annual
weeklong conference here, which is now in its 28th year. It brings
together experts on American and Soviet affairs.
   In June, the Central Committee will hold a party conference and
will consider many new laws to promote change and create what
Shislin called a state of citizens' rights.
   One issue will be rules to ``promote rotation in the party,'' he
said, including limiting the general secretariat to two or three
5-year terms.
   Alexander Kislov, a political scientist with the Soviet Academy
of Sciences, said such a system is necessary ``because we have to
get rid of the people who are afraid of change.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
