<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 0939EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LiberaceTrial     05-03 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liberace Trial,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manager: Liberace Knew Radio City His Final Concerts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Liberace knew a November 1986 series of
concerts at Radio City Music Hall would probably be his last, but
still his longtime manager said the late entertainer never told him
he had AIDS.
   Seymour Heller, Liberace's personal manager for 37 years, said
Liberace complained to him the night before he closed in New York.
   ``He said, ```I've been working 43 years and I'm very tired. I
may never work again and I want to quit on top,''' said Heller, but
he said Liberace didn't say why. Heller said the performances were
indeed Liberace's last.
   Heller's testimony came Monday as a hearing on a request by the
late entertainer's longtime manager and four others to remove Joel
Strote as executor of Liberace's estate and head of his trusts
entered its third week in state court.
   Heller said the next month he asked Liberace if he had AIDS and
Liberace denied it, ordering his attorney to sue a newspaper that
reported he had the fatal disease.
   ``He said, `No, I don't have AIDS, Seymour,' '' Heller recalled.
``I'd been with him all those years and I had no idea he had AIDS.''
   Heller said Liberace told him to call his attorney, Strote, and
launch a lawsuit against the Las Vegas Sun.
   ``Lee wanted the Sun sued, but it never went anywhere,'' he
said. ``That's what broke the story about AIDS.''
   Liberace died less than two months later, on Feb. 4, 1987, at
his Palm Springs home from complications of AIDS.
   Heller, who was the executor on all of Liberace's wills except
the final one penned by Strote two weeks before Liberace's death,
had harsh words for Strote, who also served as Heller's attorney.
   ``After Lee died and he became executor, he turned on me like a
snake,'' Heller said of Strote. ``We were very close friends before
that.''
   Heller accused Strote, who he introduced to Liberace in the
mid-1970s, of ordering he be kept from Liberace in the final weeks
of the entertainer's life. He said he wasn't allowed to see
Liberace in a Palm Springs hospital two weeks before he died.
   ``Mr. Strote had put out an edict against me,'' said Heller, who
first served as Liberace's manager in 1950.
   Heller described how he traveled with Liberace and described
their friendship and business relationship as very close.
   ``We had a wonderful performer-personal manager relationship,''
he said. ``We never had any fights over business.''
   Heller said he made some $500,000 a year over the last years of
Liberace's life from his contracts with the pianist. The last year
of his life, he said was a ``slow year'' and he made $450,000.
   ``I deserved it and I'm not ashamed of it,'' he said.
   Heller also said he had life insurance contracts on Liberace
that paid $300,000 upon his death. He said that was normal in the
personal management business.
</TEXT>
