<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Yeltsin     05-03 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Says Soviet Leaders Must Not Disappoint The Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Moscow Communist Party boss Boris N.
Yelstin today said the Soviet leadership cannot afford to
disappoint the nation in the application of its reform campaign.
   ``This hope must not be deceived, or then it will not be easy to
restore faith to the people, to elevate them to great tasks,''
Yeltsin told the daily Stroitelnaya Gazeta (Construction Newspaper)
in an interview.
   Yeltsin, 57, once considered a protege of Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, was fired as Moscow party chief Nov. 11 after
criticizing the slow pace of reform and the party's style of
leadership at a party meeting.
   One week after his ouster, Yeltsin was named first deputy
chairman of the State Construction Committee, a government job that
carries the rank of minister but that is clearly inferior to the
post of Moscow party boss.
   Stoitelnaya Gazeta sought Yeltsin's comments in connection with
a front-page article on woes in the Soviet contruction industry,
which is having to conform to the same cost-cutting and efficiency
measures as the rest of the economy.
   ``The situation here is serious in effect,'' Yeltsin said.
``Thus cardinal changes in our branch are especially needed.''
   He said Gorbachev's economic and social reform program, known as
``perestroika,'' or reconstruction, had reached a ``decisive
phase.''
   Its success, Yeltsin added, depends on ``the support of the wide
masses of workers who hope for changes for the better in their
lives and link them with perestroika.''
   Yeltsin, who graduated as a construction engineer in 1955 from
the Ural Polytechnical Institute in Sverdlovsk, said the reform
program could bring quick, beneficial changes in construction.
   ``What is reconstruction in a position to give people in the
near future? I think, first of all, an improvement in housing
conditions, growth in the number of up-to-date medical
installations, schools and kindergartens,'' Yelstin said.
   Housing is an acute problem in the Soviet Union, where one
family in five lives in dormitories or communal dwellings. A party
program has called for the construction of enough new housing so
each family will have its own home or apartment by the year 2000.
   Although the article printed in Stoitelnaya Gazeta made no
reference to Yeltsin's stormy political career, he defended the
criticisms he had made at the October meeting of the Central
Committee in an interview published abroad last month.
   ``I spoke in a straightforward manner and said what I felt and
thought was correct,'' Yeltsin said. ``Someone said correctly: each
must think independently so that later not all suddenly see the
light at once.''
   That interview was published in the inaugural edition of a
German-language version of the state-run weekly Moscow News, which
was printed and distributed in West Germany.
   Yeltsin's comments were not reproduced in Moscow News' Russian
editions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
