<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1039EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BalloonRace     05-03 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Balloon Race,0411</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Balloon Race Ends, Winners Land in Gulf of California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot and co-pilot of a race
balloon that floated perilously for hours above a jagged island in
the Gulf of California landed safely today and were declared the
race's winners, officials said.
   Joe Kittinger and Sherry Reed, both of Orlando, Fla., were
declared the unofficial winners of the annual Gordon Bennett
Balloon Race after they touched down at 3:43 a.m. on Angel de la
Guarda island, said race spokeswoman Mildred Brodbeck.
   Their balloon had floated about 365 miles southeast from its
starting point in Palm Springs, Ms. Brodbeck said.
   The pair had declared an emergency shortly after 1 a.m. and
called for assistance when their helium balloon began descending
over the rough, uninhabited island, Ms. Brodbeck said.
   ``They ran out of ballast to throw overboard and began dropping
about 100 feet a minute,'' she said. ``That's a lot.''
   Ballast is made of weights used to control the altitude of such
balloons. When the helium in the craft cools, it contracts and
loses its lift, said Jacques Soukup, an official with the Balloon
Federation of America.
   ``To counteract the sinking, you have to throw ballast, in this
case sand and water, overboard,'' he said.
   A U.S. Coast Guard jet and a U.S. Customs plane spotted the
balloon at about 3 a.m. and stayed nearby in case of a crash
landing. Upon touchdown, the jet dropped supplies including a raft,
food and water, the spokeswoman said.
   The couple were believed to have landed near the beach, but that
was unconfirmed, Ms. Brodbeck said.
   The official winners will be announced Saturday night during a
``Survivor's Banquet'' and will receive a trophy designed by Los
Angeles Times editorial cartoonist Paul Conrad, she said.
   The other six balloons in the race, which left here between 11
p.m. Sunday and 2 a.m. Monday, all landed by Monday afternoon.
   The winning crew is the one whose balloon lands farthest from
the start of the race.
   Restaurateur Rocky Aoki holds the record for the race, which is
named after New York newspaper publisher James Gordon Bennett, who
founded the event in Paris in 1906. Aoki flew 1,346 miles to
Millarton, S.D., in 1981. Fickle winds held last year's winner to
just 49 miles.
   Of the other entrants this year, distances ranged from 247 miles
down to 42.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
