<DOCNO> AP880503-0088 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1042EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MalpracticeAward 1stLd-Writethru a0537 05-03 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Malpractice Award, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0537,0345</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couple Wins $7.5 Million in Malpractice Suit Against Psychiatrist</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd and 12th grafs, ``Phyllis and xxx, to raise 1st
reference to Rotmans</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple has won $7.5 million in a
malpractice suit against a psychiatrist whose patient killed their
23-year-old daughter.
   Shelly Rotman, daughter of Phyllis and Alfred Rotman, was
fatally stabbed July 17, 1978, by Dennis Gould, who was later found
innocent of a murder charge by reason of insanity.
   Dr. Steven M. Merin had treated Gould during the three years
before the killing when he was medical director of a private
psychiatric hospital.
   Merin called the verdict ``shocking and regrettable'' because he
said he believed he had done ``everything I humanly could do with
the resources available to me to make sure Dennis Gould did not
kill Shelly Rotman.''
   His lawyer, Charles Reidy, said he may appeal.
   Merin said a number of psychiatric hospitals had treated and
discharged Gould between the time he was diagnosed as psychotic in
1973 and the slaying.
   According to testimony, Merin warned Ms. Rotman in a letter in
August 1976 that Gould had talked of harming her. Gould had dated
her for about one year before his breakdown.
   He believed he was a messiah and that he had to kill Ms. Rotman
to save the Jewish people, according to testimony.
   He continuously tried to contact her between 1973 and 1978, but
she did not return his telephone calls and tried to avoid him, said
Paul R. Sugarman, the Rotmans' lawyer.
   Sugarman argued that Merin should have hospitalized Gould while
he had psychotic delusions about Ms. Rotman and that his letter of
warning should have been stronger and more explicit.
   Ms. Rotman was stabbed when she arrived at a Quincy nursing home
where she worked.
   The Rotmans were awarded $4.5 million by a Middlesex Superior
Court jury. Interest payments will add $3 million to the award.
   Gould has been a patient at Bridgewater State Hospital since the
slaying.
</TEXT>
