<1ST_LINE>r w PM-SpaceConference     05-03 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Conference,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trust Fund Suggested to Finance Future Flights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House space committee
proposed today that Congress and industry explore setting up a
trust fund to finance future American ventures in space.
   Such a fund, said Rep. Robert A. Roe, D-N.J., chairman of the
House Science, Space and Technology Committee, would work like the
highway trust fund that financed the interstate highway system.
   Roe also said that the NASA budget authorization bill, which a
subcommittee will take up Wednesday, will for the first time
include a multiyear authorization.
   ``It stands to reason that any good and reasonable plan must
have a duration of longer than a year,'' Roe told the American
Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics at its annual meeting in
nearby Alexandria, Va. ``We insisted on the absurdity of funding
our plans in one-year cycles.''
   He said that had worked against rational planning because ``you
cannot devise a long-term research and development program, hold a
tactical team together, and keep your facilities and equipment up
to date if your primary concern is what next year's budget is going
to be.''
   Roe said the subcommittee will authorize spending for the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration for fiscal 1989
through fiscal 1991.
   He said there was a great need for innovative space financing
methods.
   ``How about developing a national space trust fund?'' he asked.
``We have built and maintained our country's highway system ...
through the highway trust fund.''
   He said that NASA, which will probably get $10.5 billion to $11
billion for the next fiscal year, needs at least $3 billion more.
He said a national space development bond program could raise the
money.
   ``Would the people of America buy bonds for their space
program?'' he asked. ``I'm sure they will if somebody asks them.''
   Roe said he may hold hearings to explore public and industry
reaction to his suggestion.
</TEXT>
