<HEAD>Pete Rose Suspended For Shoving Umpire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, ``Rose will xxx, to show that Rose must appeal
to Giamatti</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reds Manager Pete Rose called his 30-day
banishment from baseball for shoving an umpire ``excessive,'' and
says he'll fight the longest suspension handed a manager in 41
years.
   National League President Bart Giamatti ordered the suspension
Monday, two days after the incident he called ``one of the worst in
baseball's recent memory.''
   During the ninth inning of Saturday night's game, Rose rushed
from the dugout to argue a delayed call by first base umpire Dave
Pallone that allowed the New York Mets to score the winning run in
the 6-5 game.
   Rose said he pushed Pallone twice after the umpire poked him in
the cheek.
   The game was delayed 15 minutes and Pallone was forced to leave
after fans at Riverfront Stadium showered the field with debris.
The game was completed with three umpires.
   Coach Tommy Helms managed the Reds to a 3-2 victory over
Montreal on Monday.
   Rose said he was ``shocked'' by the length of the suspension and
would challenge it. ``While I expected to be suspended, I feel that
this unprecedented 30 days is excessive,'' he said.
   Rose will ask Giamatti to reconsider and will be allowed to
manage the team pending the outcome of the appeal. Giamatti's
decision would be final.
   The suspension was the longest for a manager since Leo Durocher
of the then-Brooklyn Dodgers was suspended the entire 1947 season
for allegedly associating with gamblers.
   Giamatti also said he had summoned two Cincinnati broadcasters,
Marty Brennaman and former Reds pitcher Joe Nuxhall, to New York
for ``inciting the unacceptable behavior of some of the fans'' by
criticizing Pallone for the call.
</TEXT>
