<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PrimariesRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0411 05-03 0944</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Primaries Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0411,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Likely To Notch Two Wins Today, With One For Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Jackson appearance, turnout reports in top 7
grafs, picking up in 2nd graf pvs, Vice President</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, steadily building his delegate lead over
Democratic presidential rival Jesse Jackson, was heavily favored to
score victories in Ohio and Indiana today while Jackson urged
ministers in the District of Columbia to ``vote with a passion.''
   Considered a certain victor in the nation's capital but given
little chance in Ohio and Indiana, Jackson campaigned in Washington
as the first votes were being cast and then plunged ahead on the
campaign trail, heading for appearances in Atlanta and West
Virginia.
   Early turnout estimates varied.
   In Ohio there were reports of heavier than normal turnout in
black precincts.
   ``They are out for Jesse,'' said Jim Dellick, director of the
Mahoning County board of elections.
   In Washington, where Jackson received two-thirds of the vote in
the 1984 presidential primary, the turnout was described as
moderate.
   Turnout was light in Indiana, where both Republican and
Democratic officials said interest had been affected by the lack of
close races. ``It takes the excitement out of it,'' said Kurt Wise,
press secretary for the Indiana Democratic Party.
   Vice President George Bush, his claim to the GOP nomination
secure, was hammering away at Dukakis as inexperienced on foreign
policy. Dukakis shot back with a swipe at Attorney General Edwin
Meese III and criticism of the Reagan administration for failing to
provide sufficient funding for day care.
   But the Massachusetts governor was also being criticized by
Jackson who called Dukakis a ``Teflon'' candidate not being forced
by the media to spell out the cost of his proposals.
   However, Dukakis held to his refusal to respond directly to
gibes from his Democratic rival.
   ``I'm not just a talker, I'm a doer,'' he said, repeating a line
he has used for months in response to Jackson attacks.
   Dukakis was expected to capture at least 200 of the 254
delegates at stake in Indiana, Ohio and the District of Columbia.
That harvest would place him fewer than 600 delegates shy of the
2,081 needed for the nomination, and about that many ahead of
Jackson.
   Ohio offered the day's biggest prize with 159 Democratic and 88
Republican delegates. At stake in Indiana were 79 Democratic and 30
Republican, while the District of Columbia offered 16 Democratic
and 14 Republican.
   Bush surpassed the 1,139 delegates needed for a GOP convention
majority last week in Pennsylvania and was celebrating his victory
at an ``Over the Top'' rally in a Washington hotel tonight.
   Bush campaign manager Lee Atwater said President Reagan would
formally endorse the vice president ``in the next couple of
weeks.'' Reagan stayed neutral while there was still a contest for
the GOP nomination.
   Asked if the Bush attacks on Dukakis represented a pattern for
the coming months, Atwater said, ``That's not the thrust of his
campaign. But he's not going to shy away from talking about that
kind of thing either. ... You are going to see him running an
aggressive campaign.''
   Campaigning in Ohio on Monday, Bush responded sharply to
Dukakis' criticism of administration policies in Central America
and his charge that the U.S. was paying Panamanian strongman Manuel
Noriega $200,000 a year.
   ``I can't wait for Mr. Dukakis to discuss the Noriega matter,''
Bush replied. ``And I'd say, `What would you do about it?' It's
fine sitting out there. You see, you can make a lot of unfounded
criticism. But what's his suggestion? What's he going to do, and do
it in a way that handles the delicate Central American
relationships that we're building?
   ``We're moving towards democracy. Ninety percent are now living
under democracy in this hemisphere. We don't want to set that back
by some kind of macho statement out of Harvard,'' Bush said.
   Dukakis also was in Ohio and spent part of his day visiting a
day care center at an inner-city high school as part of an attempt
to court more black support. He also told reporters he had no
intention of criticizing Jackson, whose black supporters will be
essential to any Democrat's chance of success in the fall.
   But he had no such hesitancy toward the Republicans.
   ``We want an attorney general that you and I can be proud of,
not ashamed of,'' he said, in a reference to Meese.
   He also said that in his administration, ``There won't be any
Robert Borks nominated to the Supreme Court.''
   He added, ``We can't have two and a half million people without
a home in this country and young families who can't afford a
home,'' he said. ``That's not the American dream.''
   Jackson, in a luncheon speech to the City Club in Cleveland,
called for a substantial increase in the minimum wage and for a
corporate code of conduct to press companies benefiting from
federal help to invest in America and not take jobs outside the
country.
   Jackson said he would raise the minimum wage of $3.35 an hour to
half the average hourly wage of production workers, which is $9.19.
   Jackson's staff said he gradually would increase the wage
standard to $5.50 an hour by 1993.
   The Democratic candidate also complained he was being held to a
different standard by the media than was Dukakis.
   ``So far the media is allowing him to have Teflon,'' Jackson
said, a reference to a situation in which opponents' criticism
slides right off.
   ``In time, that will change,'' Jackson said. ``The media
challenged me to show how I would pay for my dreams. I have done
just that.''
</TEXT>
