<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-US, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0531,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Third Convoy Heads For Kuwait</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Crowe arriving in gulf,
Navy comment. PICKS up 5th graf, `The convoy ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The third convoy of U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti
tankers in five days headed up the Persian Gulf today as the U.S.
Navy tried to make up for time lost to a mine threat and fighting
with Iranian forces.
   The convoy got under way as Adm. William H. Crowe Jr., chairman
of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff, arrived in the gulf to inspect
Navy operations and confer with Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less,
commander of the Joint Task Force Middle East, and other senior
officers.
   Crowe was expected to meet with top officials of Arab
governments in the gulf to outline the latest change in U.S. policy
that will permit American warships to respond to requests for help
from non-U.S. flag vessels under attack by the Iranians.
   Shipping industry and government officials in general have
reacted favorably to the change in the U.S. ``rules of engagement.''
   These had previously restricted commanders to protecting only
American-flagged ships and giving only ``humanitarian aid'' to
others if requested.
   The latest convoy was confirmed by a U.S. military spokesman
hours after shipping executives reported it sailing through the
Strait of Hormuz into the gulf for Kuwait.
   It included the 294,739-ton Townsend and the 81,283-ton Sea Isle
City, both oil products tankers, escorted by the destroyer USS
Merrill and the guided missile frigate USS John H. Sides.
   The convoy was the 28th this year and the 50th since the United
States agreed last summer to reflag and escort 11 Kuwait-owned
tankers to protect them from Iranian attack.
   The tankers' scheduled movement had been disrupted after the
missile frigate, USS Samuel B. Roberts, was severely damaged by a
mine in the central gulf April 14.
   The United States retaliated four days later by destroying two
Iranian oil platforms and sinking or disabling six armed vessels in
day-long fighting.
   The United States accused Iran of laying mines, including the
one that nearly sank the Roberts and wounded 10 crewmen.
   The convoys resumed after American and European minesweepers
found and destroyed several more mines in international shipping
lanes.
   Although U.S. officials in Washington denied there was any
postponement, six of the 11 tankers were backed up in the convoy
staging area in the Gulf of Oman, outside the gulf.
   Three of those, the Gas Queen, Chesapeake City and Surf City,
reached Kuwait on Friday, the first convoy to make the 550-mile
trip up the gulf since the U.S.-Iran clashes.
   The Merrill and the John H. Sides escorted a second convoy out
of the gulf Monday. It comprised one Kuwaiti tanker, the 46,723-ton
gas carrier Gas King, the U.S. Navy-chartered freighter Rover and
the Golden Monarch, a privately owned U.S. tanker.
   The Sea Isle City was making its first return trip to the gulf
since it was knocked out of service last Oct. 16 by an Iranian
missile.
   The tanker was waiting to load at Kuwait's main terminal when a
Chinese-made Silkworm missile hit the bridge and crew's quarters,
severely wounding the American captain and 17 others.
   The Sea Isle City left the gulf March 11 after nearly five
months in a repair yard.
</TEXT>
