<DOCNO> AP880503-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1137EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-InmateScam     05-03 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmate Scam,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Homosexuals Primary Victims of Prisoners' Postal Money Order Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARCHMAN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Men who answered ads in homosexual
magazines were the primary victims of a $330,000 postal money order
scam run by seven current and former Mississippi state penitentiary
inmates, officials said.
   The inmates and four other people, including several relatives
of the prisoners, have been charged by the federal government in
the scam.
   The April 22 indictments resulted from a probe by Baltimore
postal inspectors that began in 1986. The scheme, officials said,
involved the changing of 800 U.S. Postal money orders between
September 1986 and last month.
   Mississippi inmates using similar scams have cleared $5 million
over the past six years, officials estimate, and the schemes have
spread to other state prisons in Los Angeles, Indianapolis and
Michigan City, Ind. There have been 35 convictions connected with
the scams.
   According to the recent indictments, inmates wrote to those who
had either placed or responded to personal advertisements in
magazines. Inmates used fake names and claimed to be in prison on
minor charges, such as drunken driving.
   Two inmates would then call the individuals who responded and
pose as the inmate's case worker, social worker or lawyer.
Eventually, victims were asked to cash money orders from the ``case
worker'' and send the money to a third party.
   The non-inmates involved in the scheme would buy money orders
for between $1 and $5, then deliver them to the inmates, who would
alter the value to amounts up to $700.
   The people who received the money orders never knew they had
been altered, officials said. They would cash them for the altered
amounts and mail the money; the non-inmates involved would then
forward it to the inmates.
   Of more than 25 victims caught in the scheme by inmates,
Baltimore postal inspector J.R. Argubright said, ``the majority of
victims were from homosexual-oriented magazines.''
   For the last three years, the Mississippi State Penitentiary at
Parchman has stamped all prisoners' letters with the warning that
recipients should not cash any money orders enclosed, state
corrections department Ken Jones said.
   However, prisoners circumvent this precaution by sending letters
to co-conspirators outside prison, who mail them in other envelopes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
