<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoSlurs 2ndLd-Writethru a0500-1 05-03 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Slurs, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0500-1,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Mayor Says Apology May Not Be Enough</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, ``At the time xxx, to correct date of
Washington's death</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer has accepted an apology from
an aide accused of making slurs against Jews and Christians, but
the mayor later said the apology might not be sufficient.
   ``In this administration, with this mayor, we will not tolerate
any individual who has views of this type,'' Sawyer said Monday
night at a reception given by a Jewish group.
   ``We are reviewing the situation, and we will have something to
say about it in the near future,'' Sawyer added.
   His remarks came at the end of a day of demands that he fire the
aide, Steve Cokely, for remarks in four lectures before the
Chicago-based Nation of Islam between August 1985 and November 1987.
   In the lectures, taped and later sold at the Nation's bookstore,
Cokely, who is black, variously contended that Jews are conspiring
to gain world control and that the crucifix is a symbol of white
supremacy.
   ``I humbly apologize to Chicago residents of all races and
religious groups who were offended by remarks made prior to my
ascension to the mayor's office,'' Cokely, 35, said Monday in a
signed apology.
   At the time of the lectures, Cokely was an aide to then-alderman
Sawyer, who became mayor after the Nov. 25 death of Mayor Harold
Washington.
   ``I have, since working in the mayor's office, respected all
those I have had the privilege to serve,'' said Cokely, who makes
$35,000 a year.
   Sawyer said Monday night that Cokely's apology ``might not be
sufficient.'' He made that comment at a downtown reception for 300
people celebrating the 40th anniversary of the state of Israel.
   Sawyer had answered questions about Cokely earlier in the day by
saying: ``I don't think it's necessary to fire him. He's got a wife
and family. He needs the income, so I've asked him to tone down his
rhetoric.''
   A telephone call to Cokely at his City Hall office Monday was
not returned.
   A guest at Monday night's reception, State Sen. Howard Carroll
of Chicago, said an apology is not enough.
   ``It wasn't an accidental speech made in the heat of the
moment,'' Carroll said of Cokely's remarks.
   Alderman Bernard L. Stone called for Cokely's ouster, and
Alderman Edwin Eisendrath said the City Council would take up the
matter next week if the mayor fails to act.
   Eisendrath said he had drafted a resolution asking that Cokely
be fired if Sawyer has not already done so by the next regularly
scheduled City Council meeting, on May 11.
   ``I'm shocked that he hasn't already been told to pack his
bags,'' Eisendrath said.
   Groups denouncing Cokely's remarks and demanding that he be
removed included the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith; the
American Jewish Committee; the Community Renewal Society, an urban
mission agency; and the Illinois Ethnic Consultation, which
describes itself as the Midwest's oldest coalition of white, black,
Hispanic and Asian groups.
</TEXT>
