<1ST_LINE>r i AM-ShockingWoman     05-03 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shocking Woman,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman's Touch Knocks Out Electrical Appliances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pauline Shaw says her body is so full of
electricity that she knocks out ordinary household appliances with
a mere touch.
   She says she is one of about 40 people in Britain who are
similarly afflicted, and the experts are baffled.
   The Sun newspaper, which interviewed the 46-year-old housewife,
calculated that she has wrecked 25 household irons, 18 toasters, 15
kettles, 6 tumble dryers, 10 washing machines, 12 television
receivers, 12 radios, 3 videos and at least 250 lightbulbs.
   The total damage, the Sun calculated, is about $13,000. Mrs.
Shaw says she doesn't bother to count anymore.
   ``I don't touch the video or the microwave,'' she said in a
telephone interview Tuesday from her home in Manchester. ``I cook
only with gas.''
   She said she lost her job at the counter of a drycleaning store
``because I was making the tills go haywire.''
   She said she once knocked out her bank's computer by leaning on
a terminal.
   Mrs. Shaw said she has suffered from body electricity since
childhood, but it worsened in 1982. ``It's not a party trick,
something I do at will. It comes suddenly, by itself. You can get
quite a sharp shock shaking my hand.''
   Doctors who have examined her think it may be caused by an
allergy or stress, ``but I'm not a tense person. I'm a noisy,
sense-of-humor kind of person,'' she said.
   Mrs. Shaw, a bus-driver's wife with three children, said the
only solution she has come up with is to shower three times a day.
``It washes the electricity off the skin,'' she said.
</TEXT>
