<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PrizeRefused     05-03 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Prize Refused,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>French Professor Turns Down $136,000 Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A French mathematics professor has
turned down a $136,000 prize for theoretical research because he
earns enough as a teacher, an award spokesman said Tuesday.
   Alexander Grothendieck wrote to the committee for the
prestigious Swedish Craaford Prize to reject the prize.
   ``We were aware he had opinions ... but the letter did come as a
bit of a surprise,'' said Tord Ganelius of the Royal Swedish
Academy of Sciences, which awards the prize.
   ``It was a very polite letter, with beautiful French ways of
expression. He said he did well on his professor's salary and that
others get less if one single person gets more,'' said Ganelius.
``This kind of beautiful idealism is rare.''
   The committee announced April 13 that the German-born
Grothendieck of the Southern University of Science and Technology
in Montpellier would share the prize with Pierre Deligne, of the
Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton, N.J. They were cited for
fundamental research in algebraic geometry, which has practical
applications in satellite communications and other fields.
   Ganelius said Deligne was expected to attend the prize ceremony
in Stockholm Sept. 21 to collect his half of the prize. The other
half will be returned to the prize fund.
</TEXT>
