<HEAD>Charter 77 Activist Dead at 54</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaromir Savrda, a Czechoslovak human
rights activist and writer, has died, emigre sources in Vienna said
Tuesday. He was 54.
   Savrda died at home Monday of heart disease, said the sources,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Savrda signed the Charter 77 manifesto, the basis of the
independent human rights monitoring group of the same name. He also
was active in citizens' rights activities and a member of a banned
Czechoslovak-U.S. Friendship Society founded last year.
   Despite his heart condition, he was imprisoned several times for
his activities, the sources said.
   He was the author of several books of prose and poetry, but was
prohibited from working as a journalist after the August 1968
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia that crushed the Prague
Spring reforms of Alexander Dubcek.
