<DOCNO> AP880503-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1243EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RapeOrdeal     05-03 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rape Ordeal,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Officers Take Suspension In Rape Ordeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALUMET CITY, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers of this Chicago
suburb have accepted suspensions for failing to act promptly in the
rape ordeal last year of a 12-year-old girl.
   On Dec. 20, police waited for nearly 30 minutes outside an
apartment before rescuing the girl from a rapist despite repeated
pleas from the victim's mother to break down the door.
   Calumet City's Police and Fire Commission voted 2-1 Monday night
to find Officers Daniel Surufka and Kevin Beasley guilty of
violating department rules. The commission voted to drop three
other misconduct charges against each man.
   Lawyers for the officers had presented the negotiated settlement
to the three-member board.
   Surufka, 27, will be suspended without pay for 21 days, while
Beasley, 38, will be suspended for 15 days without pay.
   ``I wouldn't exactly say I'm bitter. I'd just say I'm a little
disappointed in the system I work for,'' Beasley said.
   But City Prosecutor Howard Rosenfeld called the officers'
punishment ``appropriate.''
   The agreement came three weeks after the commission found
Officer James Horka, the senior officer outside the apartment,
guilty of five misconduct charges and voted 2-1 to fire him.
   Rather than kick down the doors of the apartment, Horka waited
for the landlord to arrive with a key. He testified at his hearing
that he feared the rapist might kill the girl if he heard police
breaking in.
   A fourth officer, Peter Miller, did enter the apartment through
an unlocked back door, however, and rescued the girl as she was
being raped.
   Horka is appealing his dismissal in the Cook County Circuit
Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
