<HEAD>Cook County Board Stands by Its President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who says she had an affair with Cook
County Board President George Dunne has denied that she got her
county job because of the relationship.
   The Better Government Association, a private watchdog group, has
demanded that Dunne, board president for 19 years and Cook County
Democratic Party chairman, resign for giving county government jobs
or preferential job treatment to women who agreed to sexual trysts.
   But Marie Perkins, 35, said Monday she apologized to Dunne for
bringing the affair to the association's attention.
   ``If anyone should resign from a job, it is me,'' said Perkins,
a police officer with the Forest Preserve District. She said she
got her job ``not through sex but through proper channels.''
   The BGA contends that Dunne, a 75-year-old widower, engaged in
sex with four women between 1980 _ the year his wife died _ and
1986.
   Dunne has said he is guilty of nothing more than ``extremely
poor judgment'' and ``having relationships with the opposite sex,
which hurt no one.''
   Leading Democrats have rallied behind the veteran politician and
members of the Cook County Board gave him a hero's welcome Monday.
   Illinois House Speaker Michael J. Madigan and Senate President
Philip J. Rock were among office-holders saying Dunne should remain
at the helm of the county's Democratic Party organization.
   But not all of his colleagues agreed the matter should be
dropped.
   ``When you have such allegations, I think its the duty of the
state's attorney and the U.S. attorney to investigate,'' said
county board member Richard A. Siebel.
