<DOCNO> AP880503-0113 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1252EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Gulf-Pentagon     05-03 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Pentagon,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New US Gulf Protection Policy Now In Effect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf-US</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's new policy of
extending naval protection to neutral ships in the Persian Gulf has
been formally implemented, the Pentagon said today.
   Under the new policy announced last Friday, U.S. warships in the
gulf may come to the aid of any neutral, friendly commercial ship
not serving ports in Iran or Iraq if the ship comes under attack in
international waters.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said last Friday the new
policy would be implemented ``once we have informed those free
world, non-belligerent countries that maintain shipping interests
in the gulf.''
   Dan Howard, the Pentagon's chief spokesman, said ``the
appropriate people have been notified'' and the new policy was now
``in effect.''
   Howard said the policy applied equally to both Iran and Iraq
when it came to breaking up attacks on merchant ships.
   ``If it meets the criteria ... then the rules are the same for
whoever the attacker might be,'' Howard said.
   The spokesman noted, however, the United States did not expect
any confrontations with Iraqi forces because that country has
limited its attacks to ships steaming inside certain declared
exclusion or war zones.
   ``The pattern is pretty clear,'' said Howard. ``The exceptions,
the attacks have been for the most part by Iran outside the
exclusion zone.
   ``We are prepared, under certain circumstances, to offer
assistance to ... non-belligerent vessels serving neutral ports
that are attacked by anyone outside the exclusion zones.''
</TEXT>
