<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Germany-USRabbi 3rdLd-Writethru a0577 05-03 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-US Rabbi, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0577,0622</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Rabbi Named To Take Over East German Jewish Community</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with comments from rabbi.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Berlin Jews said today a Chicago rabbi had
been chosen to head their community on an interim basis, but the
rabbi said he had yet to receive an invitation and didn't know
whether he would go to East Germany.
   American Jewish Committee also denied that such an arrangement
had been made.
   However, Rabbi Ernst M. Lorge, contacted in Chicago, said he
would be willing to consider a short-term arrangement.
   ``I have not yet received an official invitation to come to East
Germany, and if I do I would have to think about it,'' said Lorge,
71. ``I might accept something shorter in term ... My life is here
in Chicago. I imagine with some understanding we could come to some
kind of agreement.''
   At issue is a successor for Rabbi Isaac Neuman, who is leaving
East Berlin after an eight-month tenure marked by several disputes
with the city's Jewish community president.
   Sources within the East Berlin Jewish community told The
Associated Press that President Peter Kirchner had received a
letter from the American Jewish Committee naming Lorge as interim
successor for Neuman.
   ``Kirchner has confirmed that Lorge is going to be the new
rabbi. But he will be a rabbi on an interim basis, until a
permanent rabbi can be found,'' sources close to the Jewish
community president said.
   They said Jewish leaders have in mind a rabbi in his 30s as a
permanent successor, but declined to elaborate. The sources spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Eugene DuBow, director of community services for the American
Jewish Community, denied that such an arrangement had been made
with Lorge.
   ``There is no truth to the report that he is coming,'' DuBow
said in a telephone interview from New York.
   He said Lorge had been a guest rabbi in East Berlin during the
High Holidays in the past.
   Lorge, who was born in Mainz, Germany and emigrated to the
United States to flee Nazi persecution in 1936, said he wanted to
help East Germany's Jewish community.
   ``I have a philosophy that Hitler should not get a posthumous
victory _ that there should not be any country where Jews are not
able to have any kind of community,'' he said.
   Neuman complained last weekend of interference from leadership
of the local Jewish community and outlined differences with the
communist government over funding. He said he would leave East
Berlin on May 16 and might return in September, but not to work.
   Jewish leaders, in a statement to the official East German news
agency ADN, denied they meddled in Neuman's activities.
   ``The assertion that Rabbi Neuman was hindered in carrying out
his functions by members, or the community representatives, or
other people must be rejected with emphasis,'' the statement said.
   It said Neuman told community members last month that he was
returning to his Champaign, Ill., home for medical reasons.
   ``His current assertion that anti-Semitic tendencies in the
press of the German Democratic Republic (East Germany) have caused
his return were never raised in his discussions with the
community,'' the statement added.
   In explaining why he was leaving in an interview at his East
Berlin home last weekend, Neuman, 65, talked of differences with
the East German press over coverage of Israel and attitudes toward
Jewish issues.
   The East German Jewish community has fewer than 350 officially
registered members and about 100 others. Last September, Neuman
became the first rabbi assigned to East Germany in 21 years.
</TEXT>
