<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimariesRdp Bjt 2Takes 05-03 0476</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp, Bjt, 2 Takes,470-1,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Seeks Ohio, Indiana Wins; Jackson Settles For DC
Consolation Prize</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First returns from Indiana expected shortly after 6 p.m. EDT.
Polls close in Ohio at 7:30 p.m. EDT and in D.C. at 8 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis looked to lengthen his delegate lead over a
contentious Jesse Jackson in Indiana and Ohio primaries on Tuesday
as the Democratic presidential campaign turned predictable. Jackson
sought a consolation prize in the District of Columbia primary.
   Dukakis held a large lead in pre-election polls in the two
Midwestern states. Jackson was favored even more strongly in the
heavily black nation's capital.
   But the day's delegate arithmetic clearly favored Dukakis, now
seemingly the prohibitive favorite to lock up the nomination weeks
before the Democratic National Convention convenes in July in
Atlanta. Ohio picked 159 delegates to the Democratic National
Convention, Indiana 79 and the District of Columbia 16.
   The Massachusetts governor, whose candidacy has been embraced in
recent days by a slow but steady trickle of Democratic Party
leaders, began the day with nearly 1,300 of the 2,081 delegates
needed to clinch the nomination, a lead of nearly 450 in The
Associated Press count over his sole remaining rival.
   Dukakis aides conceded Jackson's victory in the District of
Columbia in advance, but said they hoped it would be his last of
the primary season.
   If the Democratic primaries seemed to hold little suspense,
there was absolutely no mystery at all on the Republican side.
   Vice President George Bush faced no active ballot opposition in
Ohio, Indiana, the District of Columbia or elsewhere. He arranged
an ``Over the Top'' victory celebration at a Washington hotel to
celebrate the mathematical lock he gained on the GOP nomination
last week.
   Despite his certain nomination, Bush campaigned energetically in
Ohio and Indiana, previewing campaign themes for use in the fall
against the Democrats.
   He accused Dukakis of foreign policy inexperience and sought to
depict him and Jackson as advocates of policies that hearken back
to the Jimmy Carter era.
   On the left, Dukakis was being squeezed by Jackson, who turned
up the heat on his Democratic rival after last week's landslide
loss in Pennsylvania.
   He outspent Dukakis in Ohio television campaigning by a margin
of 4-to-1, and roughed up the Massachusetts governor for the first
time in a broadcast commercial.
   ``Bush wants to stay the course. Michael Dukakis wants to manage
the damage,'' said the commercial. ``Jesse Jackson wants to change
the course of America.''
   Dukakis declined to be drawn into a battle with Jackson as he
campaigned with his attention divided between the primary calendar
and the general election campaign. In blue collar precincts, he
sharply criticized President Reagan's decision to veto trade
legislation over a provision requiring notification to workers
before a plant can be closed.
</TEXT>
