<1ST_LINE>u p AM-PrimariesRdp 1stAdd a0618 05-03 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Primaries Rdp, 1st Add, a0618,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: be closed.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Massachusetts governor spent four days campaigning in Ohio
and Indiana, but figured only a two-day swing through next week's
primary states in West Virginia and Nebraska would be sufficient to
move them into his column.
   A new poll in California showed Dukakis with a handsome lead in
the state which selects 314 delegates _ the largest single prize in
the nation _ in a June 7 primary.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt, one of several campaign dropouts, was
quoted by one of his own supporters as saying the time had come to
rally around the Massachusetts governor.
   A few delegates backing Sens. Paul Simon and Albert Gore _ both
of whom have suspended their campaigns _ converted to the Dukakis
side, as well.
   As Dukakis' nomination moved toward the inevitable, Jackson for
the first time lashed out at his opponent.
   The Massachusetts governor turned aside Jackson's criticism by
saying, ``I'm not just a talker. I'm a doer,'' and criticized the
Reagan administration and Bush instead.
   He frequently mentioned the plant closing legislation and Bush's
support of Reagan's intended veto.
   He said Secretary of State George Shultz, a labor economist by
training, had once suggested in a book that displaced workers need
up to a year to adjust. ``Maybe the secretary can help the White
House understand the trauma and agony and pain of being laid off,''
he said.
   He criticized the administration on foreign policy, as well.
   ``I want to know why we were doing business with (Manuel)
Noriega, why they were paying off Noriega, why they were doing
business with a drug-running Panamanian dictator,'' he said.
``That's the first thing we need, a full explanation, and I think
the people of America are entitled to it.''
   While Dukakis turned his attention increasingly to the fall
campaign, Jackson decided to step up his challenge for the
nomination.
   He squelched campaign aides who were uttering semi-concessions
of defeat in the nominating race, and began demanding that Dukakis
be bolder and more specific in his campaign.
   ``So far, Dukakis has operated with caution when we must operate
with courage, clarity and candor,'' he said at one point, pressing
his rival to speak out on Southern Africa and economic issues.
   Bush devoted more time than Dukakis did to campaigning in Ohio
and Indiana, saying he didn't intend to project overconfidence.
   He criticized the Democrats wherever he went, scorning Dukakis
at one point for heeding ``macho'' advice from Harvard University
on foreign policy.
   ``I can't wait for Mr. Dukakis to discuss the Noriega matter.
And I'd say, What would you do about it?''
   He sought to link Dukakis' and Jackson's views to the tough
economic times found by the Reagan administration in 1981. ``The
country wants to move ahead, not go back to the misery we
inherited,'' he said. .
   Bush also said he was prepared to fire back if Dukakis sought to
make an issue of Meese and his legal difficulties.
   ``There is plenty of evidence to kind of go into a
guilt-by-association mode where we can find in Massachusetts
politics or campaign stuff or things of that nature,'' he said. ``I
hope we don't have to do it.''
</TEXT>
