<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--PusserHouse     05-03 0146</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Pusser House,0149</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sheriff's Home Purchased</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADAMSVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Adamsville has bought the home of the
late ``Walking Tall'' Sheriff Buford Pusser and is converting it
into a museum, officials say.
   The grand opening of the one-story brick home will be May 28,
Judy Essary, coordinator of the event, said Tuesday.
   The city purchased the home and its furnishings for $150,000
from the state, Ms. Essary said. The state had bought it from
Pusser's daughter, Dawana.
   The museum will include Pusser's clothes, furniture, the blue
light of his cruiser and a metal stick used in one of the ``Walking
Tall'' movies to smash a car windshield.
   Pusser, McNairy County sheriff from 1964 to 1970, died in a car
crash in 1974. While sheriff, he survived several attempts on his
life, including an ambush that killed his wife. His exploits
inspired a series of movies.
</TEXT>
