<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1321EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Anti-AbortionArrests 1stLd-Writethru a0557 05-03 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Anti-Abortion Arrests, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0557,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Second Day of Weeklong Anti-Abortion Blitz Begins</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs with today's arrest figures; picks up
4th graf pvs, ``All of those xxxx</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 175 chanting anti-abortion
demonstrators at a medical center today, one day after more than
500 protesters were arrested while blocking the entrance to a
doctor's office.
   By mid-morning, half the estimated 350 demonstrators who
converged on the Queens Women's Medical Office had been arrested,
charged with disorderly conduct and released, said Sgt. John
Venetucci, a police spokesman.
   Spokesman Lowell Patterson of Operation Rescue said the
demonstrators were holding a ``peaceful, prayerful presence in an
effort to block the doors'' at the office.
   Operation Rescue has been holding daily protests at New
York-area abortion clinics. On Monday, police arrested 503
demonstrators as they sat or lay in the street in an effort to
block the entrance to gynecologist Dr. Herbert Schwarz's office on
the Manhattan's Upper East Side.
   All of those arrested were given summonses for disorderly
conduct and released, said Officer Louis Llanes, another police
spokesman. No violence was reported.
   Joined by several clergymen, the group estimated at 600 people
prayed and sang hymns while a smaller group of about 50
abortion-rights advocates held a counter-demonstration across the
street, organizers said.
   Police refused to estimate the size of today's crowd.
   Cardinal John O'Connor issued a statement Monday, saying, ``We
support all peaceful efforts to bring an end to abortion which has
seen over 15 million pre-born babies aborted since the Roe vs. Wade
Supreme Court decision of 1973.''
   Barbara Page, a spokeswoman for the anti-abortion group, said
the group believes in peaceful demonstrations and added that their
main goal was to ``counsel women going into the clinic.''
   ``We don't harass or harangue anybody. We don't hang onto the
woman. We don't punch her or hit her ... but we may be able to
deter her by blocking access,'' Mrs. Page said.
   Karen Rood, a member of the New York chapter of the National
Organization for Women, said they had about 50 people outside the
doctor's office ``to help people get access to the clinic and
escort women inside.''
   She said they were unable to do that because police put them
across the street from the anti-abortion demonstrators. But no
patients tried to enter the small residential building housing the
doctor's office before the demonstration ended early in the
afternoon.
   The doctor, who performs abortions and does pregnancy
counseling, was unable to open his office because of the
demonstrators, Ms. Rood said.
   An answering machine was on in the doctor's office all day. He
did not return phone calls.
</TEXT>
