<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1343EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a PM-MOVE     05-03 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-MOVE,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Returns No Indictments in MOVE Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE LINDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special grand jury today called city
officials' conduct in the 1985 MOVE siege that led to 11 deaths
``totally unacceptable,'' but returned no criminal indictments in
what it called the city's greatest tragedy.
   Eleven people died and 61 homes were destroyed on May 13, 1985,
when police dropped a bomb on a barricaded west Philadelphia row
house occupied by the radical group MOVE.
   ``Applying the law to the facts as we find them, no charges are
warranted, yet we do not exonerate the men responsible for this
disaster,'' the grand jury said in its 279-page report. ``Rather
than a vindication of those officials, this report should stand as
a permanent record of their morally reprehensible behavior.
   ``This city, its leaders and citizens, must never forget the
terrible cost of their misjudgments.''
   The confrontation started after neighbors who had been targets
of threats and harassment for several years told authorities they
would try to evict MOVE themselves unless the city acted.
   The grand jury report, released this afternoon, denounced the
city's planning for and actions in the siege as incompetent and
inept. It especially castigated Mayor W. Wilson Goode.
   ``As the city's chief executive officer and the man legally
responsible for law enforcement in the city, Goode delegated too
much, deferred too often, and asked too few questions,'' the report
said.
   The MOVE group championed back-to-nature rituals, lived in filth
with rats and other animals, refused to send their children to
school and disobeyed health and safety laws. It was decimated by
the disaster, and most of its living members are now in jail.
   The report said other top officials also were uninformed,
including the city's No. 2 executive at the time, former Managing
Director Leo Brooks.
   During the confrontation, when police gunfire failed to drive
out the MOVE members, Goode approved a plan to drop an explosive
device on the row house from a helicopter.
   The bomb started a fire, not immediately fought, that eventually
destroyed 1{ city blocks and killed 11 people, five of them
children, in the fortified MOVE compound. Damage caused by the
police action already has exceeded $20 million, including
rebuilding the burned-down neighborhood.
   The grand jury said it considered criminal charges involving
conspiracy, murder, involuntary manslaughter, aggravated assault
and other charges. It determined in not bringing charges, ``that
Goode's conduct was not reckless under the law; that is, that he
did not consciously disregard a substantial and unjustifiable risk
that people would be placed in danger of death or serious bodily
injury'' by the dropping of the bomb.
   A federal grand jury _ which has been probing for more than a
year whether the civil rights of the 11 victims were
unconstitutionally violated _ is nearing the end of its work.
   A report from the federal panel, with a possibility of
indictments, is expected in a few months, possibly by the start of
summer.
   Beside police participants, others criticized by the mayor's
investigating commission were Brooks, who ran operations at the
MOVE scene, former police commissioner Gregore Sambor,who planned
the bombing, and Fire Commissioner William Richmond, accused of
delaying fighting the blaze because officials allegedly hoped the
flames would drive out the occupants.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
