<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Lebanon,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Lebanon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House, in a response to the Israeli
incursion into Lebanon, today expressed concern about the
increasing level of violence in that country and called for
withdrawal of all foreign forces.
   ``The United States believes there is a need for mutually agreed
security arrangements to assure stability and security in
Lebanon,'' presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said.
   ``We are concerned about the increasing level of violence and
call for restraint by all parties,'' Fitzwater said. ``Violence
does not serve anyone's interest and underscores the need for
comprehensive political solutions.''
   ``In this regard, the United States continues to support
Lebanese unity, sovereignty and independence and the withdrawal of
all foreign forces and the extension of central government
authority throughout Lebanon,'' he said. ``We have consistently
supported political reform and dialogue in Lebanon.''
   ``On the broader issue of Middle East peace, we continue to
consult with the parties involved,'' he said. ``To date, we have
not heard anyone say no. This is a positive sign in itself. We will
continue to work for peace.''
   Asked why the statement was being issued, Fitzwater said, ``It's
a response to the incursion.''
   Israeli tanks pushed to within a few miles of Syrian troops in
south Lebanon today as heavily armed Israeli soldiers searched for
Palestinian guerrillas in the area's rugged hills in an operation
that began Monday night.
</TEXT>
