<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MarineService     05-03 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marine Service,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Service Honors Two Marines Killed in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Marines lost in the Persian Gulf
last month were ``excited and proud'' and dedicated to their duty,
a Marine officer said today at a memorial service for the men.
   More than 450 people gathered inside a chapel at New River Air
Station, where two tables covered in black cloth held the helmets,
swords and wings of the Marines, Capt. Kenneth Hill, 33, of
Thomasville and Capt. Stephen Leslie, 30, of New Bern.
   The two were aboard a helicopter that disappeared in the Persian
Gulf last month during a skirmish between the United States and
Iran. They were declared killed in action April 28.
   ``Steven and Ken were positive men, and they would want us to
press on,'' Maj. George Messier told the mourners during the
service.
   ``They didn't just climb into it (helicopter) _ they strapped it
on,'' Messier said.
   The Marines were on an evening patrol serving as backup for U.S.
combat ships the day they disappeared, Messier said after the
service.
   The two had been asked to check out a ``presence'' detected by a
U.S. ship. While doing so, they radioed they had detected an enemy
radar tracking their own helicopter, Messier said. That was the
last the Navy heard from them, he said.
   ``They almost certainly were shot down that evening,'' Messier
said.
   Hill's wife, Laura, and 4-year-old son, Andrew, and Leslie's
wife, Lisa, who is seven months pregnant with the couple's first
child, attended the service. Both Hill's and Leslie's parents were
also there.
</TEXT>
