<2ND_LINE>PM-German-Bomb,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Found At British Army Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETMOLD, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A home-made bomb was discovered at
a British army base today, just two days after IRA attacks killed
three British soldiers based in West Germany.
   Detmold municipal officials said the two-pound bomb was
discovered in a civilian parking area on the base, and that
explosives experts were on the scene.
   They said in a statement that it was not certain whether the
experts could defuse the bomb, or whether they would be forced to
explode it. The officials said British authorities sealed off the
parking lot and the surrounding area.
   Three senior airmen in the Royal Air Force Regiment died in bomb
and shooting attacks Sunday in the Netherlands. The airmen were
visiting Dutch discotheques and bars when they were killed.
   The Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility for a
machine-gun attack in Roermond, which killed one airman, and the
booby-trap car bomb in Nieuwbergen, which killed two others. Three
other servicemen were injured.
   The British armed services have nearly 70,000 personnel and
80,000 dependents stationed in West Germany at four Royal Air Force
and five army bases.
   The IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern Ireland
and unite the province with the Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
