<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--IndianTaxes     05-03 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Indian Taxes,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court: State Can't Tax Sales To Tribal Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state may not tax the Potawatomi
Indians for cigarette sales to tribal members at the tribe's store
near Shawnee, a judge has ruled.
   U.S. District Judge Lee West ruled recently that the tribe must
work with state officials to set up a system for charging taxes on
purchases made by people who do not belong to the tribe.
   ``I think this will apply to any sales made at their store,''
David Miley, state Tax Commission general counsel, said Tuesday.
``We will have to see the wording in the final judgment, but from
reading the order, I think it would apply to all their sales.''
   The Tax Commission billed the Citizen Band Potawatomi Indian
Tribe in March 1987 for $2,691,470 in taxes it said were owed on
cigarettes sold since 1982 at the Gallery Trading Post.
   The tribe sued, contending such taxes violated tribal
sovereignty.
   Miley said the commission would decide whether to appeal after a
final judgment is issued.
</TEXT>
