<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     05-03 0350</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who went into business as an
``optimism consultant'' has had to close her office because she was
not optimistic enough in estimating her prospects.
   Inga Lill Enbom shut her ``Optimism Center'' in Lulea when
demands for her lectures kept her traveling too much, the national
news agency TT reported Tuesday.
   ``I virtually never had time to spend in my beautiful office in
Lulea and realized the pointlessness of having space that was not
any use,'' she said.
   Her message is that positive thinking is a prerequisite for
solving any problem or getting results. Her clients include
schools, government institutions, companies, clubs and professional
organizations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Illinois Innovators and
Inventors, or I-Cubed, say they're just ordinary folks, unlike the
mad scientist stereotypes who often appear on the big screen.
   Through the group's exposure, some members say, they hope to
change the image of inventors as eccentric, hyperactive, wild-eyed
and wild-haired people in unkempt clothing, bursting with ideas but
absent-minded.
   Susan Burgess of I-Cubed, which provides pointers and business
information for inventors, recently said the biggest misconception
people have about inventors is ``they're all weirdos _ and they're
not.''
   ``They don't all sit around in their basements and shout
`Eureka!' all the time,'' Ms. Burgess said.
   But group members do come up with novel ideas.
   Take Robert Biby of Troy, for instance, who created a portable,
quiet air conditioner to keep police officers cool on hot
stakeouts. And there's Mark Derby of O'Fallon, who invented a
bear-proof food-storage box for campers.
   Author and group member Dennis Shinn, who has compiled two books
of ``1,001 Names For Your Pet'' _ that's 2,002 names _ said
inventors are just plain folks.
   ``Once I-Cubed gets proper exposure, I think people will realize
inventors are not mad scientists,'' Shinn said.
   ``They just have ideas they want to let the public know about.''
   Based in offices overlooking Tower Lake at Southern Illinois
University at Edwardsville, I-Cubed was created in August 1986 to
help inventors turn ideas into finished products.
</TEXT>
