<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Federal Fraud,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Panel Approves Anti-Fraud Sanctions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Judiciary Committee approved by
voice vote Tuesday legislation to impose federal criminal sanctions
against major contractors who are convicted of defrauding the U.S.
government.
   The measure, introduced by Rep. Bill Hughes, D-N.J., chairman of
the Judiciary crime subcommittee, also establishes a new system of
rewards and job protections for so-called ``whistleblowers'' in
private industry who provide information leading to convictions in
fraud cases.
   Hughes said the legislation is intended to crack down on a
procurement fraud problem which is robbing the government of
hundreds of millions of dollars a year and, in some cases, costing
lives.
   He said the proposed law would give the Justice Department a
more precise tool to use against contractors who attempt to defraud
the government on contracts of $1 million or more.
