<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Twins     05-03 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Twins,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Separate Siamese Twins Joined At Head</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doctors separated 17-month-old
Siamese twins, joined at the head, in an intricate operation
Tuesday that took 7{ hours, officials at Soweto's Baragwanath
hospital reported.
   They described the surgery by a 40-member medical team on Mpho
and Mphonyana Mathibela as successful. The hospital is in the huge
black township outside Johannesburg.
   Sophie Mathibela, mother of the girls, said: ``I feel so happy.
... I want to sleep a little, pray and thank God for all he has
done.''
   A statement by the hospital said Mpho, the stronger of the two,
was doing well but Mphonyana suffered extensive blood loss and was
in critical condition. It did not elaborate.
   Last September, doctors at Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore,
Md., separated West German twins joined at the head. The two boys,
Benjamin and Patrick Binder, survived and were released in March,
but are said to have some physical and mental problems.
   Johns Hopkins doctors advised those at Baragwanath on the
difficulties they were likely to face.
   Members of the medical team performed two operations on the
girls last October in preparation for Tuesday's surgery.
   In those operations, doctors partially clamped a shared major
blood vessel in the twins' heads in hopes that lesser blood vessels
would take over its functions.
   Dr. Robert Lipschitz, chief of the surgical team, told a news
conference last Friday chances for success were not good.
   ``This is going to be a ... lengthy, intricate operation which
carries many dangers with it,'' he said. ``The prognosis is still
very grave.''
   Ms. Mathibela, an unmarried, 33-year-old domestic worker who
earns about $60 a month, gave birth to the twins Dec. 7, 1986.
   She attended a prayer service in the hospital chapel Tuesday
morning. About 100 people, most of them nurses and patients, said
prayers and sang hymns for the girls.
   The mother said she had been horrified by giving birth to
Siamese twins and refused to see the girls for three days, but
``once persuaded to see them, I immediately accepted and loved my
little gifts from God.''
   They had a combined weight of 33 pounds before the surgery. Mpho
appears to be developing normally and recently began to speak, but
Mphonyana is slightly smaller and does not appear to be as
advanced, said officials at Baragwanath, the main hospital in
Soweto.
   Ms. Mathibela was asked to make a $5 contribution to the costs
of the operations and related care, which will total hundreds of
thousands. The costs are being absorbed by the hospital and the
Witwatersrand University medical school.
   The Sowetan, a daily newspaper that covers the black township,
established a trust fund for the twins and the equivalent of about
$26,000 has been raised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
