<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1558EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SchoolBreakfasts     05-03 0280</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-School Breakfasts,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Healthy Breakfast Tied to Higher Test Scores</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A healthy breakfast helped Lawrence
students score higher on tests, according to a study released
Tuesday.
   About 1,000 children in third through sixth grades from six
schools were involved in the study conducted by two Boston
pediatricians.
   Alan Meyers and Michael Weitzman of Boston City Hospital
presented their findings Tuesday in Washington, D.C., at the annual
research meeting of the Ambulatory Pediatric Association. They hope
to encourage colleagues to push for a national breakfast program.
   ``Only a handful of states besides Massachusetts mandate the
breakfast program,'' said Meyers. ``We are trying to give these
kids every break they can have. It looks like there may be some
benefit here.''
   Massachusetts ordered communities with large numbers of poor
families to begin school breakfasts in January 1987. The Lawrence
study began three months after the law took effect. Test scores
from 335 children in the program were compared to scores from 688
children who were not. Almost all the children were from poor
families.
   Among the results:
   _ Test scores showed greater improvement for children in the
breakfast program. Their scores went up 13.5 percent the following
year, compared to 11 percent for children not in the program.
   _ Children in the program were late or absent less frequently,
and breakfast eaters made fewer mistakes in the morning.
   School lunches are now available to most U.S. children, but
breakfast is offered to about 40 percent.
   The study estimates about 600,000 children skip breakfast every
day. Cost is a problem. The federal government spent $400 million
in 1986 to serve breakfast to 33,000 public school students, Meyers
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
