<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Poison-Students     05-03 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poison-Students,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Junior High Girls Admit Trying To Give Poison To Vice Principal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FOREST LAKE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three girls accused of conspiring to
kill an assistant principal by putting lye in his coffee have
pleaded guilty to a reduced charge, officials said.
   A seventh-grader and two ninth-graders at Forest Lake Southwest
Junior High School in east-central Minnesota admitted to juvenile
delinquency petitions _ the juvenile court equivalent of guilty
pleas _ accusing them of conspiracy to commit bodily harm by
adulteration.
   ``It means they conspired to put poison in their assistant
principal's coffee cup, but it wasn't intended to kill him,''
Washington County Juvenile Court Judge J.E. Cass said.
   On Feb. 25, Vice Principal Robert Espelien became suspicious
when he saw a brownish-tan substance, which tests later showed was
lye, floating in his coffee cup. Espelien did not drink the coffee.
   The Washington County attorney's office filed juvenile petitions
accusing the students of conspiring to commit murder in the first
degree. The girls were suspended from school and later expelled for
the remainder of the 1987-88 term.
   In Minnesota, juvenile court matters are usually kept
confidential, but in certain situations judges have discretion to
disclose some facts of a case.
   Cass said he decided to release some information because of
widespread public interest in the case, but declined to reveal
what, if any, penalties were applied.
   ``I wish I could release more information,'' Cass said. ``These
cases don't have a lot of value as deterrents to crime unless the
public knows what happened in court.''
</TEXT>
