<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AmnestyRush Bjt   05-03 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amnesty Rush, Bjt,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>INS Offices Prepare for Last-Day Rush, Will Stay Open Till
Midnight</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM GILLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Lines snaked outside federal immigration centers in cities
around the country Tuesday, as thousands of undocumented aliens
applied for legal residency status a day ahead of the deadline for
the yearlong program.
   To accommodate late applicants, all 107 offices of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service will remain open until
midnight Wednesday, the deadline for the yearlong amnesty program.
Many district offices extended hours Tuesday, too.
   In Baltimore, the line of applicants stretched around the block
Tuesday morning, as people waited for the district office to open,
said Louis D. Crocetti, acting deputy district director.
   Two weeks ago, Crocetti said his office was processing 15 to 20
applications a day. Now it's more than 200 a day.
   ``I just kept procrastinating, but the time just caught up with
me,'' Anna Maldonado, 26, of Mexico said Tuesday as she waited with
750 other people at the INS office in downtown Los Angeles.
   Her sister, Carmen, who applied for amnesty in January,
persuaded her to apply, she said.
   ``The applications are finally coming in,'' said INS spokesman
James Jasey in New York, where more than 500 applicants stood in
line at midday outside the Manhattan office.
   As of Sunday, 1.33 million applications had been received,
according to the INS. An additional 464,000 people are seeking
legal status under a separate program for seasonal agricultural
workers. The deadline for that program is Nov. 30.
   Applicants who file by the deadline also may request up to 60
days for submitting other documents necessary to prove they have
lived in the United States continuously since before Jan. 1, 1982.
   ``We've gotten dramatically busier in the last few days,'' said
Roger Nye, chief legalization officer for the INS office in Boston,
which handles applications from Massachusetts, Rhode Island and New
Hampshire.
   ``Our average throughout the program has been about 28
applications a day but last week we had 828, which works out to
over 160 a day. And (Monday) alone we had 329 applicants and I
expect to surpass that by a good deal today.''
   In Charlotte, N.C., the INS office received 204 applications on
Monday; it had received 454 applications in the preceding three
weeks. However, about 90 percent of the applicants came from farm
workers who have the longer deadline.
   ``We knew it was going to happen this way,'' said Ana Pardo,
chief immigration officer for North and South Carolina.
   In Los Angeles, nearly 1,000 Central American applicants for
political asylum lined up overnight at the main federal building,
mistakenly believing that they, too, faced a deadline.
   ``I had to call up a couple of federal police officers to
assist. There was a mob outside,'' guard Walter Bonner said
Tuesday. ``It was like a stampede when we opened the doors at 5
a.m.''
   The San Francisco district, which covers Nothern California, is
handling close to 4,000 applications a day, up from a high of about
600 a day in early February, according to INS spokesman John R.
Davis.
   South Florida immigration offices have mostly escaped long
lines, but local INS director Perry Rivkind said Tuesday the number
of applications had increased sharply recently.
   ``It's been running about 2,000 a day,'' he said. ``But we have
no problem taking applications.'' About 110,000 people have applied
for amnesty there, and Rivkind said he expects the total to reach
125,000.
   One reason the program has not had as great an impact in South
Florida is that the two most populous immigrant groups _ Cubans and
Haitians _ had their situation legalized under special legislation
that followed the 1980 Mariel boatlift, said Rivkind.
   Nonetheless, Rivkind said he expected a ``last-minute push''
Wednesday and promised ``we'll take everyone _ even if we have to
wake 'em up in line.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
