<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South-West Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0608,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Namibian Leader Wants to Meet with Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf pvs, bgng: The talks, to CORRECT troop total to
40,000, sted 100,000</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South-West African guerrilla leader Sam Nujoma
said Tuesday he had come to the United States to meet with the
three presidential candidates and seek their support for South
Africa's expulsion from the territory, also known as Namibia.
   Nujoma said he had been assured by campaign managers for
Democratic hopefuls Michael Dukakis and Jesse Jackson that he would
meet with the two candidates during his stay here. Vice President
George Bush has not responded to his request for a meeting, Nujoma
added.
   Nujoma, who heads the South-West African People's Organization
(SWAPO), also said he had received assurances from Angola that
Namibia's interests would be faithfully represented at negotiations
being held in London Tuesday between American, South African, Cuban
and Angolan representatives.
   The talks are designed to get Cuba to pull out its 37,000
soldiers from Angola, in return for a pullout of South Africa's
estimated 40,000 troops from Namibia. ``It will be a package, I am
assured of this by the Angolan government,'' he said in an
interview.
   But South Africa is doing ``all it can to strengthen its hold''
on the mineral-rich territory, stepping up a campaign of arson and
bombing attacks against Namibia's predominantly black population of
1.5 million, Nujoma said. He accused South Africa of burning down
14 Namibian church schools last month.
   ``South Africa has no intention whatsoever to leave Namibia,''
said Nujoma, who has lived in exile for 28 years, the last 12 in
Angola. The South Africans will have to be ``forced out by the
combined resistance of the Namibian people and international
pressure.''
   He commended the economic sanctions imposed by Congress on South
Africa in 1986 and urged the next U.S. administration to take
further steps to pressure South Africa into relinquishing Namibia.
   Nujoma said he had requested a meeting with Secretary of State
George P. Shultz but had not received any response. A State
Department official said she did not know of such a request.
   The United States supports a South African pullout and an
independent Namibia, but its contacts with SWAPO have been limited.
   South Africa is ruling Namibia under an expired League of
Nations mandate, in defiance of a 1978 U.N. resolution which calls
for Namibian independence.
   Nujoma also said that should the United States be willing to
supply SWAPO with weapons ``we will certainly accept it with great
pleasure.''
   Most of the group's arms and training come from the Soviet
Union, Cuba, Yugoslavia, Angola and several other members of the
Organization of African Unity, he said.
   Iran, India, and the Scandinavian countries supply humanitarian
assistance to SWAPO, Nujoma said.
</TEXT>
