<DOCNO> AP880503-0149 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1630EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-GulfPool     05-03 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf Pool,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crowe Says Iran A Serious Foe Despite Recent Setback</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDITOR'S NOTE _ The following was based on a Pentagon news pool
report.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ABOARD THE USS CORONADO IN THE PERSIAN GULF (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman
of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Adm. William J. Crowe Jr., said
Tuesday that Iran remains a dangerous foe in the Persian Gulf
despite heavy losses in battles with the Navy two weeks ago.
   ``I believe the Iranians would clearly like to damage us, to
hurt us, to humiliate us if they could,'' Crowe, the nation's top
military commander, said during a surprise visit to the gulf.
   ``I think terrorism is one of the ways that they might try to do
it. It's a very serious threat.''
   Crowe presided at an awards ceremony on the sun-baked after deck
of the 15,000-ton USS Coronado.
   He plans to visit at least three of the 28 other U.S. warships
in the area, including the mine-damaged 3,700-ton guided missile
frigate Samuel B. Roberts, on his two-day tour.
   Iran has warned Washington not to mount new military actions in
the Persian Gulf and has threatened reprisals from anywhere in the
world.
   Crowe was interviewed by the Pentagon media pool.
   The admiral said he was disappointed at the Reagan
administration's decision against sending six fast Coast Guard
cutters to help patrol the gulf.
   ``They would have been very useful in these shallow waters
because we need fast boats with shallow drafts,'' he said. ``They
are the best patrol boats in the world and the Navy had no
substitute.''
   Crowe said he was aware of, but could not confirm, reports that
Iran may have 100 new C-801 type Chinese missiles, a much more
sophisticated missle than the land-based, anti-ship Chinese
Silkworms Tehran has deployed so far.
   He said the Pentagon still had not decided if Iran actually
fired Silkworms at U.S. ships in the April 18 battle, even though
reports from ships in the area initially identified incoming
missiles as Silkworms.
   President Reagan had warned Tehran that U.S. forces would strike
at coastal Silkworm missile batteries if they were ever fired at
American ships.
   Iran's Revolutionary Guards have used a fleet of about 50
Swedish-built Boghammer armed speed boats to harass shipping in the
gulf.
   Tehran said on Monday it has resumed boarding ships in the gulf
to determine if they are carrying cargoes to Iraq for use in the
7{-year-old war with Iran.
   Rear Adm. Anthony A. Less, commander of the Joint Task Force
Middle East, said ``the biggest headache is the opportunity they
have to put mines out there.''
   Nearly 50 mines have been found in the gulf this year, but Less
said that no new ones have been detected recently by the fleet of
allied mine sweepers that roam the gulf waterway through which 20
percent of the world's oil is shipped.
   Crowe, 63, called the recent sea battle with Iran ``unique in
the annals of U.S. Navy history'' because of the exchanges of
missile fire and praised the men for their performance.
   In a brief ceremony on the afterdeck, Crowe presented awards
that included the Distinguished Flying Cross, the Bronze Star and
Air Medal to 13 pilots and crew members for bravery during the
action April 18.
   During the action, American forces attacked two Iranian oil
platforms and sank or disabled six naval craft in raids described
by Washington as a ``measured response'' to hostile acts, including
the mining of gulf waters and firing on U.S. helicopters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
