<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Nielsens     05-03 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nielsens,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Magnum' Swan Song Helps Put CBS in First Place</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas Sullivan Magnum went out in style,
winning first place in the Nielsen ratings and giving CBS its first
clear claim to first place this season.
   The ``Magnum, P.I.'' movie special Sunday night got a rating of
32.0 for the week ended May 1, more than eight points ahead of
second-place NBC's ``Cheers.''
   CBS knocked its competition, the ABC miniseries on Aristotle
Onassis and the NBC movie ``Mad Max: Beyond Thunderdome,'' out of
the ball park. The ``Magnum'' movie ranks as the 14th-highest rated
made-for-TV movie ever.
   An original episode of ``Murder, She Wrote,'' in fifth place,
also helped CBS win the week.
   ``It goes to show what a couple of hit shows can do for you,''
said Arnold Becker, CBS vice president for television research in
Los Angeles.
   The victory for CBS was its first clear title this season. NBC
was second and ABC was third. In the previous week, CBS was third
and NBC was first. CBS tied with NBC for first for the week ended
April 10. CBS also grabbed first place in the opening round of the
May sweeps.
   ``Magnum, P.I.'' ended eight years with a two-hour movie special
that allowed Magnum, played by Tom Selleck, to get his personal
life in order, including the return of his daughter, and to rejoin
the Navy as a commander.
   The show also cleared up whether Jonathan Higgins, played by
John Hillerman, was really best-selling novelist Robin Masters. The
answer was no.
   CBS was first for the week with a rating of 13.9 in the A.C.
Nielsen Co. survey. NBC was second with 13.4 and ABC was third with
12.1. The rating is a percentage of the nation's estinated 88.6
million households with television.
   In the May sweeps, CBS took an early lead. The Arbitrons, from
April 27 to May 1: CBS 14.9, NBC 13.7, ABC 10.1. The Nielsens, from
April 28-May 1: CBS 15.8, NBC 13.8, ABC 9.0. The sweeps are periods
in which the audiences of local television stations are measured to
set their advertising rates.
   Here are the top 10 shows: CBS Sunday Movie ``Magnum, P.I.''
NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``A Different
World,'' CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' NBC's ``Golden Girls,'' ABC's
``Just the 10 of Us,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' ABC movie ``Little Girl
Lost,'' and ABC ``Growing Pains'' special.
   The ``Growing Pains'' special was the opening for the new spring
series ``Just the 10 of Us.'' ``Little Girl Lost'' was ABC's
highest-rated movie of the year.
   The movie pilot of the ABC series ``China Beach'' was in 12th
place; the first episode was 21st.
   The ABC Sunday miniseries ``The Richest Man in the World: The
Story of Aristotle Onassis'' placed 37th. The NBC Sunday movie
``Mad Mad: Beyond Thunderdome'' was 57th.
   The five bottom shows were: ABC's ``Ohara,'' ABC's ``Hotel,''
ABC's ``Buck James,'' CBS' ``Houston Knights'' and ABC's ``Max
Headroom.''
   The shows on the Fox Broadcasting Co. network got higher ratings
than some of the network shows. ``America's Most Wanted'' did
better than ``Houston Knights'' and Fox's ``Married With Children''
and ``21 Jump Street'' came in ahead of ``Max Headroom.''
   The two-hour movie pilot for Fox's ``Dirty Dozen'' got a 3.6
rating, more than a full rating point behind ``Max Headroom.''
   ABC came in first among the evening news shows, moving ahead of
CBS. NBC stayed in third place. The ratings: ABC 10.4, CBS 9.6, NBC
8.6.
</TEXT>
