<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Yeltsin     05-03 0719</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Yeltsin,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted Moscow Official Joins Chorus Of Commentary On Reforms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ousted Moscow Communist Party boss Boris N.
Yeltsin returned to the spotlight Tuesday to join a chorus of
critics of the status quo and to support Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's economic restructuring drive.
   In an article in the daily Construction Gazette, Yeltsin called
on Soviet workers to make the reforms work. He also warned the
Kremlin leadership that it should be careful not to deceive the
people and make them lose faith.
   Yeltsin, who gained wide popularity in the capital with his
raids on food stores and personal inspection of public transit, was
fired as Moscow party leader on Nov. 11 after he criticized the
slow pace of reforms during a closed-door meeting of the party
Central Committee.
   His ouster sent a chill through the ranks of reformists, who
worried that Yeltsin's removal signaled strong resistance to
Gorbachev's efforts at allowing more openness about problems
plaguing Soviet society.
   A week after losing the party job, Yeltsin was named first
deputy chairman of the State Construction Committee, which carries
ministerial rank but falls far short of the influence he enjoyed as
Moscow party leader.
   Construction Gazette sought Yeltsin's comments in connection
with a front-page article on woes in the Soviet contruction
industry, which is having to conform to the same cost-cutting and
efficiency measures as the rest of the economy under the
``perestroika,'' or rebuilding, campaign. It made no reference to
his former party job.
   Yeltsin told the newspaper that Gorbachev's reforms are at a
``decisive phase,'' and that the leadership should be careful to
fulfill the hopes and expectations of the working people.
   ``This hope must not be deceived, or then it will not be easy to
restore faith to the people, to elevate them to great tasks,''
Yeltsin said.
   Success, he said, depends on ``the support of the wide masses of
workers who hope for changes for the better in their lives and link
them with perestroika.''
   He said the reforms could produce some long-needed improvements
in the near future, including better housing, more modern medical
facilities and more schools and kindergartens.
   Housing is still an acute problem in the Soviet Union, where one
family in five lives in dormitories or communal dwellings. A party
program has called for the construction of enough new housing so
each family will have its own home or apartment by the year 2000.
   The Construction Gazette article was the first mass-circulation
Soviet publication to quote Yeltsin since his departure from the
party job. Last month, the inaugural German-language edition of the
weekly Moscow News carried an interview with him. That publication
is printed and distributed abroad.
   Yeltsin's public return came a day after the party daily Pravda
published on its front page a letter from another government
official, who criticized his fellow party members for pursuing
careerist ambitions over the ideals set down by Soviet founder
Vladimir I. Lenin.
   The official, identified as V. Selivanov of the Ministry of the
Aviation Industry, contended that party members have tainted
Lenin's postulate that ``The party is the mind, honor and
conscience of our epoch.''
   He called for improvements within the party as well as industry
and society as part of the restructuring campaign and introduction
of more democracy in Soviet life.
   Tuesday night's edition of the government newspaper Izvestia
carried a lengthy criticism of Soviet industry and agriculture.
   Prominent author Chingiz Aitmatov said Soviets continue to
justify poor production with weak excuses about losses suffered
during World War II, although countries like Japan and West Germany
hit even harder long ago outdistanced Soviet performance.
   Aitmatov, a popular writer whose literary works attack
totalitarianism, said Gorbachev's reforms hold out the only hopes
for improving Soviet farm and factory output.
   The commentaries on democratic and economic reforms appear to be
part of the preparations for next month's party conference, at
which Gorbachev will seek broader endorsement for his campaigns and
likely remove some of the more conservative forces fighting the
changes he has advocated.
   The criticism of social and economic progress to date voiced by
Yeltsin, Selivanov and Aitmatov, and their calls for support for
Gorbachev's reforms, embrace the leader's two main themes of
greater openness and a wholesale rebuilding of the nation.
</TEXT>
