<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea     05-03 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Korean President Ready to Share Power</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo is ready to
share power with the opposition in the National Assembly after his
party's losses in legislative elections, party officials said
Tuesday.
   Officials of Roh's Democratic Justice Party said they wanted to
reach an agreement with the opposition soon so the new National
Assembly can hold its opening session around May 20.
   ``We would favorably consider an opposition demand that the
parliamentary leadership be shared by parties according to their
assembly seats,'' the governing party's floor leader, Kim
Yoon-hwan, said after meeting with senior party leaders.
   Opposition candidates made a strong showing in legislative
elections a week ago, stripping the government party of its
parliamentary majority for the first time in South Korea's modern
history.
   The three opposition parties took 164 seats in the 299-member
assembly. Roh's party won 125 seats, 25 shy of a simple majority. A
handful of independent candidates also won seats.
   Kim, who was appointed floor leader in a shakeup of the party's
leadership on Monday, said formal discussions of the new Assembly's
leadership could start after opposition parties hold their national
conventions next week.
   Kim said the government party wants to hold the speakership but
would cede the two vice speaker's posts to the opposition.
Traditionally, only one vice speaker's post has been left to the
opposition.
   The chairmanships of 13 assembly committees should also be
shared with the opposition, Kim said. In the past, all committees
were headed by governing party members.
   After the legislative elections, the president said he would
``humbly'' accept the outcome. He added he would work with the
opposition to continue to carry out his promises for democratic
reforms.
   In a first move to reorganize the government camp after the
election, Roh replaced the head of his party with a moderate senior
politician. Other senior party posts also were filled with
moderates.
   Government officials said Roh was expected to shake up his
Cabinet, probably next week, but leave Prime Minister Lee Hyun-hae
in place.
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung, whose Party for Peace and
Democracy emerged as the No. 1 opposition force in the elections,
said he would like to delay debates on controversial issues if they
would disrupt the 1988 Olympics in Seoul.
</TEXT>
