<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Survivor-Fatal     05-03 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Survivor-Fatal,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Who Survived Persian Gulf Attack Dies In Burning Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who survived an attack on an oil tanker
in the Persian Gulf last month has been found dead in his burned
car, authorities said.
   Lawrence Glass Jr. of Selma, who was featured on the front page
of Sunday's Selma Times-Journal for being among the last to leave
the tanker after dousing flames on the vessel, was found dead
Sunday morning.
   The cause of the fire was unknown, state Fire Marshal Roy
Thornell said Tuesday.
   ``I don't think it was an accident,'' said Glass's father,
Lawrence Sr. ``The heat and the way his car had been pulled off the
road leads me to suspect foul play.''
   Doris Teague, a spokeswoman for the Alabama Department of Public
Safety, said she could not comment on any investigation.
   Glass, 36, was at the Linden Country Club on Saturday afternoon
and met a friend later before leaving around midnight, according to
his father. He said his son smoked but that the friend said he was
not intoxicated when he left the house.
   Thomaston Fire Chief Jeff Laduron said the car was parked beside
Alabama Highway 66 and it appeared Glass ``may have pulled off the
road and gone to sleep and it caught fire.''
   In the interview published Sunday in the Selma newspaper, Glass
said Iranian Revolutionary Guard gunboats on April 18 attacked the
oil tanker on which he was safety engineer. While other crew
members were evacuated, Glass remained aboard to put out fires on
the vessel, which was carrying 353,000 barrels of oil.
   Glass, who worked 35 days on board the oil tanker and then had
35 days off, told the newspaper he hoped to get hazardous duty pay
when he returned to the Persian Gulf in a few weeks.
   Glass, whose survivors include a wife and son, had worked in the
Persian Gulf since 1981.
</TEXT>
