<HEAD>400 More Arrested At 2nd Anti-Abortion Rally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-abortion demonstrators shut a medical
office where abortions are performed for the second consecutive day
Tuesday and their protest produced 422 arrests.
   ``We have completed our objective,'' said Lowell Patterson,
spokesman for Operation Rescue, which organized the demonstration.
``The facility was closed for the day and no babies were killed.''
   Protestors from various anti-abortion groups from 20 states
converged on the Women's Medical Office in the borough of Queens
after 8 a.m. and laid down on the sidewalk and street.
   Dozens of officers made arrests, lifting demonstrators by
stretchers and loading them onto buses. They were taken to a park,
charged with disorderly conduct and released, said Officer Janice
Swinney, a police spokesman.
   Two men from a smaller group of pro-choice demonstrators also
were arrested after scuffling with police who were separating the
two groups.
   A man who said he was a doctor answered the phone at the private
clinic Tuesday morning and confirmed the center was closed because
of the protest, which lasted for several hours.
   Police arrested 503 people for disorderly conduct Monday after
Operation Rescue staged a similar demonstration outside a Manhattan
doctor's office.
   During both protests, the demonstrators prayed and sang hymns as
police made arrests.
   Patterson said the group would hold a news conference Wednesday
and demonstrate again Thursday and Friday.
