<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2015EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-WHO     05-03 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-WHO,0280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Says It Paid Full 1987 Budget Share to UN Health Agency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States said Tuesday it gave more
favorable treatment to the World Health Organization than to other
U.N. agencies and paid its full 1987 budget assessment of $62.8
million.
   Don Newman, undersecretary of health and human services, said in
a speech to the WHO annual assembly: ``The United States has been
able to pay its full assessment for the year 1987.
   ``Through this payment, WHO received favorable treatment over
that accorded to many other organizations in the United Nations
system, including the United Nations itself.''
   He did not elaborate, but sources said privately the Food and
Agricultural Organization, based in Rome, and the U.N. General
Assembly also probably would be paid the full U.S. assessments.
   The United States is assessed about 25 percent of the budgets of
the United Nations and its agencies.
   Payments have been held up by congressional stipulations that
contributions depend on the effectiveness of an agency and its
fairness to the United States, and that overall U.S. payments be
reduced because of the American budget deficit.
   WHO officials and health experts in the United States have said
lack of funds threatened important programs. Warren Furth,
assistant director-general, told reporters in December the lack of
money was certain to affect such life-preserving work as child
immunization.
   Newman did not say when Washington paid its WHO assessment but
U.S. spokesman Art Skop said the decision was made ``very
recently.''
   About 1,200 delegates from the health agency's 166 member
nations are in Geneva for the 41st general assembly. The two-week
meeting began Monday.
</TEXT>
