<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1647EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WarholAuction     05-03 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Warhol Auction,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bottom Line on Warhol Auction: $25 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MITCHELL LANDSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten days of Andy Warhol-mania ended Tuesday when
Sotheby's auction house brought down the last gavel on its sale of
the late artist's personal collection. The grand total: $25.3
million.
   The sale, which featured more than 10,000 items owned by Warhol,
attracted an estimated 60,000 people to the Sotheby galleries and
set tongues wagging and jaws dropping throughout the art world.
   Proceeds from the auction vastly exceeded Sotheby's official
pre-auction estimate of $9 million to $13 million. While auction
house officials admitted that they purposely underestimated the
collection's value, they expressed surprise over the extent of the
miscalculation.
   ``Our feeling when we figured the estimates was that we wouldn't
add any `Warhol factor,''' said Diana D. Brooks, president of
Sotheby's North America. ``I think what we're seeing today is an
indication not only of the `Warhol factor' but of a very strong art
market.''
   For whatever reason, buyers were willing to pay dearly for just
about anything owned by Warhol, who died in February 1987 and owned
many, many things.
   Sales figures included $2,640 for three plastic watches bearing
the likenesses of Fred Flintstone, Judy Jetson and Gumby; $23,000
for a pair of cookie jars; $55,000 for a set of Salvador Dali ear
clips; and $605,000 for a Roy Lichtenstein painting, ``Sailboats.''
   Proceeds from the auction go to the Andy Warhol Foundation for
the Visual Arts, which was established by the artist to support
cultural institutions.
   The highest-priced item at the sale was an untitled 1967
painting by Cy Twombley that fetched $990,000 _ a record for a work
by that artist. It was one of many records set during the marathon
sale.
   Works of art routinely sold for double or triple _ or more _
their estimated value. A David Hockney drawing of Warhol, valued at
$60,000 to $80,000, sold for $330,000 _ an example of the ``Warhol
factor'' working overtime.
   ``It's a joke to attempt to buy here,'' complained one Toronto
art dealer, Geert von der Veen. ``I don't think there are many
dealers who could touch those prices _ or want to. You'd look
crazy.''
   ``I think the prices have no relation to the value,'' said
another dealer, Ames Brown of Manchester, Vt. ``The Warhol
imprimatur is just inflating prices irrationally.''
   Von der Veen and Brown both said that private collectors, not
art dealers, were doing most of the buying at the Warhol auction _
something Sotheby's officials disputed.
   ``For those of us who buy for resale, or for investment, it's
not a very attractive auction,'' said Brown.
   But for others, the Warhol auction was exceedingly attractive.
   ``It's not an exaggeration to say this was a historic event,''
said Jeffrey Deitch, vice president of the Citibank Private Banking
Group, who buys art on behalf of bank clients.
   ``A lot of the prices sound high to the casual bidder, but
they're not insanely high,'' Deitch said. ``For instance, in the
auction of the Warhol furniture, many of the pieces went for what
you'd pay for new furniture.''
   Anyway, he said, ``I think it sends an interesting signal that
our culture values these things, and I think that as a culture we
can feel very good that works of art are valued to this extent.''
   Deitch predicted that anything associated with Warhol would
continue to escalate in value as more people come to appreciate the
artist, who remains controversial in death as he was in life.
   ``It's just beginning,'' he said. ``Just beginning.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0166 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DearbornParks     05-03 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dearborn Parks,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeal of Dearborn Parks Case Heard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A predominantly white suburb should have the
right to ``control its own possessions'' by barring non-residents
from its parks, a lawyer for the town said Tuesday.
   A three-judge state Court of Appeals panel heard arguments on an
appeal of a 1986 ruling overturning a referendum in Dearborn. In
November 1985, the voters in the town, located on Detroit's western
border, had approved a measure that would ban non-residents from 35
of its 37 parks.
   The American Civil Liberties Union challenged the law, saying it
effectively discriminated against blacks from neighboring Detroit.
   William Saxton, representing Dearborn, said Tuesday that the
ruling should be overturned because the same argument could be used
to strike down a number of other laws that had potential
discriminatory effects.
   ``The plaintiffs are making an abhorrent argument, ...'' he said
in an interview outside the hearing. ``The city has a right to
control its own possessions.''
   But Wayne State University law Professor Robert Sedler, who
argued in behalf of the ACLU, said the ordinance ``is going to make
the Dearborn parks all white.''
   However, he added, the case is limited and should apply only to
Dearborn parks.
   ``Our view is a very narrow one,'' he said.
   In September 1986, Wayne County Circuit Judge Marvin Stempien
ruled that the ban was unconstitutional because of its possible
discriminatory effect and its proposed random checks of park users
for identity documents.
   Citing two of parks that were particularly close to
predominantly black Detroit neighborhoods, the judge said: ``The
impact of the non-resident provisions ... is to deny the use of
both Ford Woods Park and Crowley Park to almost every potential
black user within the ... service area.''
   The 1980 census showed that of about 90,000 people living in
Dearborn, fewer than 100 were black. Detroit's population at the
time was about 63 percent black.
   Nearly a year before the ruling, the Dearborn City Council voted
4-3 to reject the parks ordinance. But a petition drive put the
matter on the Nov. 5, 1985, election ballot, and residents approved
it in a 17,790 to 13,976 vote.
   Attorneys said an appeals ruling may be made within 120 days.
</TEXT>
