<2ND_LINE>AM-Frat Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0697,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Indictments Announced In Frat Drinking Death</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to include background, details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen Rutgers University students
have been indicted in the drinking-related death of a fraternity
pledge, authorities said Tuesday.
   The students, including seven officers of the now-closed Lambda
Chi Alpha fraternity, were charged with aggravated hazing, which
carries a penalty of up to 18 months in prison and a $7,500 fine
upon conviction.
   Middlesex County Prosecutor Alan Rockoff said that as first
offenders, the students probably would not face prison.
   A grand jury in Middlesex County returned the indictment Friday,
but it was not announced until Tuesday because prosecutors wanted
to tell the students and their families first.
   The 15 students did not have to post bail, Rockoff said. They
are to appear May 20 before Superior Court Judge George J. Nicola
in New Brunswick.
   Among those facing charges is fraternity chapter President Roy
P. Dudak, 20, of Florence; Vice President Glen L. Kelley, 20, of
Sewickley, Pa.; and rush chairman David M. Selenko, 20, of Old
Bridge, according to the indictment.
   Rockoff said the officers were not charged as a result of their
positions but were among fraternity members who allegedly
endangered the life of James Callahan, 18, of North Bergen.
   Callahan died after a fraternity pledge party at the Lambda Chi
Alpha fraternity house Feb. 12. Tests revealed Callahan had four
times the legal amount of alcohol in his body when he slipped into
a coma.
   Robert Ochs, vice president of public safety at Rutgers, said a
university investigation continues and that the 15 students named
in the indictment could face school charges, the most serious being
expulsion.
   Also on Tuesday, Rutgers football player Robert Lowther of
Wadsworth, Ohio, died in a car accident in which the driver had
twice the legal amount of blood alcohol in his system, Rockoff said.
   The car, driven by Rutgers linebacker Robert P. Speidel, 21, of
Wayne, had veered into oncoming traffic and crashed head-on into a
truck, Rockoff said.
   Tests on Speidel, who remained hospitalized in critical
condition Tuesday, showed he had a blood alcohol level of 0.253
percent, Rockoff said. People are considered legally intoxicated in
New Jersey when blood alcohol content reaches 0.10 percent.
   Speidel turned 21 on Tuesday, making him younger than the legal
drinking age Monday, Rockoff said.
   Another passenger in the car, linebacker Paul Garea, 19, from
Hamden, Conn., was in serious condition Tuesday.
   Rockoff said tests were being conducted on Lowther's body, but
authorities say a preliminary investigation revealed that the three
began drinking Monday afternoon in a dormitory.
   No charges had been filed Tuesday, Rockoff said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
