<DOCNO> AP880503-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2034EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FoodLabels     05-03 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Food Labels,240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Food Labeling System Called Confusing, Inadequate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's food labeling and information
system is confusing, inadequate and in need of an overhaul,
according to a congressional report released Tuesday.
   ``The food information system lacks common criteria. In
addition, controversies surround the nutritional issues that
underlie regulatory decisions,'' the General Accounting Office said
in its report.
   ``Consumers need the clearest, most consistent information
possible,'' the report said. But the current system sends
``confused signals'' to consumers, it said.
   The report was requested by Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., chairman
of the House Energy and Commerce Committee's oversight and
investigations subcommittee. Dingell asked GAO to investigate
conflicting regulations on the use of cheese substitutes in frozen
pizza toppings.
   The Agriculture Department, which regulates meat-topped frozen
pizza, requires disclosure on the front panel of the pizza box if
less than 10 percent of the cheese on the pizza is ``traditional''
cheese.
   The Food and Drug Administration, which regulates all other
frozen pizza, requires front-panel disclosure if a pizza topping is
not 100 percent real cheese.
   GAO reported in 1980 that FDA and the Agriculture Department had
119 regulations covering consumer economic protection and product
safety. In 1982, GAO said the piecemeal labeling system had led to
regulatory inconsistencies and consumer confusion.
   The latest report said efforts to develop a workable approach to
collecting and disseminating food information have lagged behind
``the explosion of manufactured food products'' _ nearly 3,400 in
1986 compared with 1,000 in 1982.
</TEXT>
