<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Transport     05-03 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Transport,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Impose Transport Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas on Tuesday
imposed a nationwide road transport ban that forced workers to walk
to their jobs or pay high fares to truck drivers.
   The ban, the third this year, reduced traffic on intercity roads
and highways by up to 90 percent, according to several dispatchers
and broadcast reports from the provinces. City traffic appeared to
be about a third of that on a normal day.
   Only two privately owned city buses were seen in a tour of the
capital and the surrounding area. Several state-owned buses with
soldiers aboard for protection were providing transport, as were
some army trucks.
   But most Salvadorans either walked or boarded overcrowded
pickups and vans converted to public transport by their owners. The
drivers charged an average of two colones (40 cents) per trip, or
about six times the average bus fare.
   Guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front, who
have waged an 8-year campaign against the U.S.-backed government,
warned drivers to heed the measure. They did not say how long it
would last.
   On the clandestine Radio Venceremos, the rebels said they were
taking down license plate numbers of vehicles violating the ban and
would retaliate with sabotage.
   The guerrillas said the ban was a response to increased
repression by security forces.
   Police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity for security
reasons, said a taxi was commandeered then burned Tuesday morning
by urban commandos in northeastern San Salvador.
   During transport bans in February and March, four people died,
11 were wounded and 15 vehicles were burned or shot.
   As was the case during the previous bans, the guerrillas on
Tuesday stepped up their sabotage against the state-owned electric
utility. Bombs toppled several utility posts or transmission
towers, cutting electricity to wide swatches of this nation of 5
million.
   Gen. Adolfo Blandon, chief of the joint chiefs of staff, said
all leaves for members of the 56,000-strong armed forces had been
canceled to provide security along the nation's thoroughfares.
   Several citizens condemned the transport ban.
   ``The ones most hurt are the humble people who use public
transport,'' said a middle-aged man who refused to give his name
for fear of the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
