<DOCNO> AP880503-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JockeyTrainer     05-03 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jockey Trainer,0609</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>School Gets Would-Be Jockeys Out Of The Starting Gate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN STRAUSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COMMISKEY, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There's a world of difference between
riding a thoroughbred horse and driving a car, but there is also
one similarity: Let either one get out of control and you have a
problem.
   ``These horses are a little bit crazy,'' said Lisa C. Schulte, a
former history teacher who is owner of Hawkeye Hill Racing School.
``Students who have had a horse run off with them say it's like
being in a Formula One race car with the throttle stuck open, very
little steering and no brakes.''
   About 70 percent of those in the Hawkeye Hill riding program
wash out because they can't master the powerful, high-spirited
animals from the saddle. But since they also study stable
management before planting their feet in the stirrups, employment
after graduation usually isn't a problem. The school has a 40-page
list of stables looking for help.
   ``These are people who write or call in orders and say, `I need
a groom or an exercise rider,' '' said the 43-year-old Ms. Schulte,
who started the school in 1979.
   The 68-acre complex has two training tracks, barns, a dormitory
and a classroom. Ten groups of 12 students per year take a home
correspondence course before arriving for the minimum one-month
course in exercise riding _ how to give racehorses their workouts _
that many students hope will lead up the ladder to a jockey's life.
   The state-accredited campus is an alternative to the traditional
school for jockeys: the school of hard knocks. People wanting to
become jockeys usually are handed a pitchfork instead of the reins
and have to work their way up.
   ``Unless you have good connections such as parents who are
trainers or who are wealthy horse owners, it's very hard to get a
job at the track,'' Ms. Schulte said. ``So this gives them a good
foundation of hands-on experience with thoroughbred race horses.''
   Brad Hopp, 18, of Kahoka, Mo., graduated from the school in
March and was back this week to prepare for his test to get an
apprentice jockey license.
   ``I was getting run away with quite a bit, and now I feel I can
ride about anything out there ...,'' said Hopp, whose family owns
thoroughbreds. ``There was my way of riding and their way or
riding, and theirs was better.''
   Jane Evans said the program would help her train the
thoroughbreds she owns at her farm near Carlisle, Mass. Unlike most
of the students, who are in their late teens or 20s, Mrs. Evans has
several grown children.
   Summer and fall are the busiest times at the school 50 miles
north of Louisville, but business picks up around Derby time. This
year's Kentucky Derby is set for Saturday.
   ``Many of the foreign students come especially for the Derby,''
Ms. Schulte said. ``They come from Europe and South America.
They've also come from the Middle East. They're wanting to learn
about American ways of training race horses and riding, and about
American racetracks.''
   The school has 50 horses graded in riding difficulty from ``the
ones you could put your grandma on, to the real hair-raising
horses,'' Ms. Schulte said.
   The only thing harder to handle than an out-of-control horse
might be a class of junior high school students, the former teacher
said.
   ``Get you about 30 of them and put (the students) in a situation
where they don't want to be,'' she said. ``After that,
thoroughbreds are a challenge, but a pleasure.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1729EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-CleanAir 1stLd-Writethru a0644 05-03 0942</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Clean Air, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0644,900</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Cities Failed to Meet Ozone Standards Last Year</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 3, ``Twenty cities,'' with estimate of 135 million
people; INSERTS grafs 13-14, `Sen. George ... Air Act,'' with
comment</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More areas have failed to meet federal clean
air standards for ozone, a major component of smog, but carbon
monoxide pollution has cleared up slightly, the Evironmental
Protection Agency said Tuesday.
   EPA's annual list of areas violating national clean air
standards for the two pollutants shows 68 cities not meeting the
ozone goals last year, an increase of six from the year before, and
59 out of compliance for carbon monoxide, a decrease of six.
   Twenty cities appeared on both lists, so 107 cities and rural
areas containing 135 million people, according to the National
Clean Air Coalition, violate one standard or both. The 24 largest
metropolitan areas were on one or both lists, leaving Kansas City
the largest area in compliance.
   Both pollutants are influenced by the weather, and for that
reason EPA uses more than a year's data in judging compliance _
three years for ozone and two years for carbon monoxide. The ozone
tabulations cover the years 1985-87 and the carbon monoxide 1986-87.
   If, for example, only 1986 data had been used, 50 cities would
have flunked the carbon monoxide test. If 1987 readings alone had
been used, 37 cities would have failed. But to be in compliance, a
city must make the cut both years.
   The influence of weather on ozone is more pronounced.
Pittsburgh, Detroit, Grand Rapids, Mich., and Richmond, Va., are
listed as violators this year, but not last year. All four were on
the 1986 list using 1983-1985 data.
   The relevant ozone readings for those four areas for 1985-1987
are similar to those for 1983-1985, possibly because their summers
were similar in 1983 and 1987, EPA spokesman Chris Rice said.
   ``We had a hot, dry summer in the East, which tends to push up
ozone levels,'' Rice said. ``It was much like the summer of 1983,
except confined to the East.''
   This year's lists are perhaps more important than most because
Congress will use them in deciding if and how to revise the Clean
Air Act. While revisions are being considered, Congress barred EPA
from imposing penalties on any non-complying areas before Aug. 31.
   EPA contends that it may not impose penalties for sheer failure
to meet numerical standards, but must do so for areas that fail to
work toward compliance. Penalties for at least 14 areas were held
up by the congressional action.
   Those penalties can be the suspension of federal highway, sewer
and air pollution program aid.
   Aug. 31 is now the deadline for complying with the standards,
which no one expects or believes possible for many cities. Various
proposals in Congress would extend the deadlines according to the
severity of pollution and efforts needed to clean it up.
   Sen. George Mitchell, D-Maine, sponsor of one bill that has
cleared the Senate Environment Committee, said in a statement the
new report ``demonstrates that the ozone nonattainment problem
continues to worsen'' and that his bill is needed.
   He was echoed by Richard Ayres, chairman of the National Clean
Air Coalition, a grouping of environmental and other organizations,
who said the new data ``confirm that we are no longer winning the
battle against air pollution and we need a revitalized Clean Air
Act.''
   Carbon monoxide interferes with the oxygen-carrying capacity of
the blood. Ozone, the major component of smog, worsens breathing
problems.
   Motor vehicles are involved in producing both pollutants.
   Carbon monoxide is emitted directly in the exhaust. As cars
built before 1981, when the latest emission standards took effect,
are retired, urban air should get cleaner regardless of the weather.
   EPA says average carbon monoxide concentrations have been
improving by about 4 percent a year since the mid-1970s. The agency
expects all but a handful of cities _ four to six, according to
Rice _ eventually to meet clean air standards for carbon monoxide
without special effort.
   Ozone compliance is more difficult, in part because it is not
emitted in exhaust.
   Ozone is formed by chemical reactions in sunlight between oxides
of nitrogen _ still another pollutant emitted by all fossil fuel
combustion, including vehicle fuels _ and volatile compounds like
gasoline vapor, both from tailpipes and from normal evaporation in
fuel systems.
   These reactions can proceed downwind of the source of the raw
materials, which accounts for the presence of several rural
counties, five of them in Maine, on the ozone non-compliance list.
Ozone raw materials for the Maine counties were emitted somewhere
upwind in the Boston-Washington corridor.
   Though many areas will improve as old cars are junked, far more
will remain out of compliance than will be true for carbon
monoxide, EPA believes. Some 25 or more cities will be unable to
comply with tighter controls on stationary sources of other,
non-gasoline compounds like solvents, EPA says.
   By a wide margin, the Los Angeles area is again worst for ozone
pollution, in part because of the mountains around the city that
keep polluted air from moving away. The area has peak ozone
concentrations nearly three times the standard and an estimated 143
days of violation per year.
   The second worst city is Bakersfield, Calif., with peaks 50
percent above the standard and 35 days of violations per year. Four
other California cities _ San Diego, Fresno, Modesto and Visalia _
have more than 10 days above the standard.
   Outside of California, only Houston, Atlanta and Philadelphia
have more than 10 days of violation per year.
</TEXT>
