<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Mozambique 1stLd-Writethru a0674 05-03 0272</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Mozambique, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Pleased By South Africa-Mozambique Cooperation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS two grafs at end with reaction from South Africa</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is pleased by recent
measures of cooperation between South Africa and Mozambique, the
State Department said Tuesday.
   Specifically, the department praised a new agreement between the
two countries for electric power supply from the Cabora Bassa Dam
in Mozambique to the eastern part of South Africa's Transvaal
province.
   ``We are pleased by the recent steps taken by the governments of
Mozambique and South Africa to reduce tensions and expand
cooperation, through such means as restoring the Cabora Bassa
electrical power system which links the two countries,'' said
spokesman Charles Redman.
   He added that ``we encourage both governments to follow through
on this and other efforts to work toward accommodation.''
   South Africa is also negotiating to train and equip as many as
three battalions of Mozambican troops, according to a South African
official quoted in a New York Times report from Maputo.
   The official, Timo Beukes, said the training would cost about
$14 million annually and South Africa would also supply ration
packs, vehicles, uniforms, radios and mine detectors.
   The reported agreement constitutes a reversal of South Africa's
traditional support for the RENAMO guerrilla group seeking to
overthrow the leftist-oriented government of Joaquim Chissano.
   In Cape Town, Roland Darroll, a spokesman for the Department of
Foreign Affairs, denied that South Africa was negotiating to train
Mozambican troops.
   He did say that South Africa was considering non-lethal military
aid for Mozambique to help protect the hydroelectric project, but
that no decision had been made yet.
</TEXT>
