<2ND_LINE>AM-Political Briefs,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McCain Says He May Skip GOP Convention If Mecham Is Delegate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz, says he may skip
the Republican National Convention in August if former Arizona Gov.
Evan Mecham is a member of the state's delegation.
   ``I'd have to think long and hard about that, but my inclination
would be not to be (a delegate),'' McCain said in Tucson Monday.
   Mecham said in a telephone interview from his Glendale office
that McCain ``must have a guilty conscience if he can't be around
me.''
   Arizona's 33 delegates to the national convention will be chosen
at the state GOP convention May 14 in Phoenix. Mecham will be one
of 717 regional delegates from which the delegation will be picked.
   McCain, a supporter of Vice President George Bush, said the news
media will be searching for more interesting news stories in New
Orleans than the vice president's virtual lockup on the GOP
nomination.
   ``It's going to be a dull convention, obviously,'' he said.
``And there would be enormous media attention to Gov. Mecham.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Secret Service Stops Jackson's Plan to Stay With Miner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plans by Democratic presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson to spend a night with a Mingo County coal
miner were undone by bad roads, campaign officials say.
   Jackson was to stay with miner Scott Cisco of Meador, but the
plans fell through when the Secret Service objected to the
treacherous roads in the area.
   Cisco, 27, said he first thought officials were pulling his leg
when they asked whether Jackson could stay at his home in the coal
town of 300. He consented to the visit after he realized the call
was no joke.
   ``What else could I do?'' he said.
   Cisco, who plans to vote for Jackson in November, pointed out a
bright side to the canceled visit _ he doesn't have to worry about
what he would serve for dinner.
   ``When I thought of that I just threw my hands up in the air and
said, `Oh God help me.' I'd hate to serve him TV dinners,'' he said.
</TEXT>
