<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     05-03 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Move to Erase Alaska Oil Curbs in Trade Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrats moved to erase the trade bill's
curbs on Alaska oil exports Tuesday even before the measure reached
President Reagan's desk and a threatened presidential veto.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said the move was designed to
offer Reagan a compromise and thus perhaps avert a veto of the
1,000-page bill which won final approval from the Senate last week.
   Republicans countered that the real reason was to win over the
votes of Alaska's GOP senators for a veto override.
   The move to drop the Alaska provision was contained in a
resolution authorizing technical corrections in the bill.
   The bill cleared the Senate last week by a vote of 63-36 last
week _ three short of the number needed to override Reagan's
threatened veto.
   The House is expected to take up the resolution this week and
senators will deal with it next week when they return from a recess.
   One of the curbs would enable Alaska to export 50,000 barrels of
crude a day to Canada but would require that the oil be transported
to a West Coast port first in American vessels.
   The provision is a favorite of politically influential maritime
unions, and a similar feature is contained in the current
U.S.-Canada free trade agreement. The other provision would limit
exports from new refineries to 70,000 barrels a day and half of
total production.
   At a news conference, Wright portrayed the move as designed to
keep the trade bill from going down the drain through a Reagan veto.
   The president has been concerned about a provision that would
require all but the smallest employers to give 60-day notice of
plant closings and large-scale layoffs. But more recently he has
also reportedly found fault with the Alaska provisions.
   ``We're trying to meet him (Reagan) halfway if we can,'' Wright
told reporters. `` ... We're trying in every way to appeal to his
better nature.''
   Before the plan won committee approval, Rep. James H. Quillen,
R-Tenn., described it as ``a ploy to change some votes in the
Senate in order to override a possible presidential veto.''
   ``I don't think this committee ought to be used for this
purpose,'' Quillen said.
   Alaska's Republican senators, Ted Stevens and Frank Murkowski,
voted against the trade bill because of its resrictions on oil
exports. Democrats believed that they would have supported the
measure had the curbs been dropped.
   Stevens said at one point, however, that he could not guarantee
support for the bill even if the Alaska provisions were stripped
out.
   House Minority Leader Robert H. Michel, R-Ill., took the floor
earlier and accused Wright of trying to ``win at all costs.''
   ``I am told there is a proposed new rule in the works that will
allow the majority to delete the Alaskan oil provisions in a
last-ditch attempt to manipulate a veto override in the Senate,''
Michel said.
   ``Is there nothing left of the integrity of our rules and
procedures?'' Michel said. ``Good policy is the product of good
legislation produced honestly and openly in a deliberative manner.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0178 </DOCNO>
