<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2117EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Germany-Bomb     05-03 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-Bomb,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Found At British Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETMOLD, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homemade bomb was discovered
Tuesday at a British army base and detonated by explosives experts,
a military spokesman said.
   Col. Rob Stewart, of the 1st British Army Corps, said the
two-pound bomb was attached to a car in a civilian parking lot at
the base, located near the north-central town of Bielefeld.
   No one claimed responsibility for planting the bomb.
   On Sunday, three off-duty British airmen were killed in bombing
and shooting attacks in the Dutch towns of Roermond and
Nieuwbergen. Those assaults were claimed by the Irish Republican
Army.
   Stewart told The Associated Press that the explosives were found
Tuesday by a soldier during a routine afternoon inspection and that
experts blew up the bomb.
   A spokesman for the Ministry of Defense in London, who spoke on
condition of anonymity in line with British practice, said the bomb
was discovered near Ripon Barracks, the headquarters of the 1st
British Corps in Bielefeld.
   He said an ammunitions technical officer carried out two
controlled explosions.
   The discovery of the bomb Tuesday ``does emphasize that all
those responsible for the safety of our servicemen must continue to
take very great care,'' said British Minister of Defense Ian
Stewart.
   He spoke to reporters at the Royal Air Force barracks in
Wildenrath, near the Dutch border, where he was visiting two people
who were wounded in Sunday's attacks.
   Meanwhile, West German border police said a report on Britain's
Independent Television that police were looking for a brown car
with the license number SH71BR in connection with the attacks was
no longer valid.
   Police spokesman Harry Klabbers in the Netherlands also said the
car had been cleared of any connection with Sunday's incidents.
   The outlawed IRA is fighting to drive the British from Northern
Ireland and unite the predominantly Protestant province with the
mainly Roman Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
