<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Monastery     05-03 0526</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Monastery,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardinal Fails in Plea to Dissuade Reagan Visit to Moscow
Monastery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. Dale Nelson</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Tuesday he will go to an
Orthodox monastery in Moscow during his summit visit despite a
Ukrainian Catholic leader's plea that he cancel the event as a sign
of support for religious freedom.
   ``He said he already made plans and he has to go,'' Myroslav
Cardinal Lubachivsky told reporters after meeting privately with
the president at the White House and declaring that Ukrainian
Catholics continue to suffer persecution.
   The cardinal added that the president promised to ``be firm
about the issues'' of religious freedom in his discussions with
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``Being there, he will mention that freedom of the churches is
necessary for all the people,'' Cardinal Lubachivsky said.
   He said Reagan also pledged to try to meet with Ukrainian
Catholic leaders while in the Soviet Union May 29 to June 2.
   Addressing a White House conference on religious rights in the
Soviet Union just before his meeting with Reagan, the cardinal said
that ``the age of suffering has not passed'' for Christians in the
Soviet Union.
   ``Today, we hear so much about glasnost and perestroika,'' he
said. ``But, Mr. Gorbachev's reforms have yet to touch the
Ukrainian Catholic Church. Our priests are punished or fined for
celebrating the liturgy in private homes, and the faithful live in
constant fear of imprisonment. Such violations of basic human
rights simply must not exist.
   ``Therefore, in the name of all that is sacred, I implore you
... to advise the president to reconsider his trip to the Danilov
monastery at this time,'' he said. ``The symbolism of this event
would lend credence to the atheistic Kremlin's usurping of the
1,000-year-old Ukrainian Christian legacy.''
   The monastery on the outskirts of Moscow, the central building
of which is more than 700 years old, is being restored with
government financial help. The building is noted for splendid
religious decoration of gold and jewels.
   The cardinal also said he urged the president to meet with
Ukrainian religious leaders of the underground church during his
trip to Moscow ``as a public manifestation of U.S. support for the
resurrection of our banned Ukrainian churches.''
   Reagan, in his speech at the conference, said, ``I promise you
that the witness of faith you brought here today will not be
confined to these four walls or forgotten when this meeting is
ended.
   ``I will carry it in my heart when I travel to the Soviet Union
at the end of this month and I will say that the most fitting way
to mark the millenium of Christianity in Kiev ... would be granting
the rights of all the peoples and all the creeds of the Soviet
Union to worship their god in their own way.''
   While noting the 1,000th anniversary of Christianity in the
Soviet Union, Reagan also said, ``The rights of Soviet Jews have
taken up much of our official time and this is very close to my
heart. Our hope is for doors to open completely to emigration and
to full freedom for all faiths.''
</TEXT>
