<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-War     05-03 0315</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-War,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Writer Criticizes Post-War Development, Blames Stalin</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent writer said Tuesday the Soviets are
still blaming the devastation of World War II for their poor
performance in agriculture and industry, while Japan and West
Germany have rebuilt and prospered.
   Chingiz Aitmatov wrote in the government newspaper Izvestia that
the Soviet Union has fared worse than the vanquished nations in
postwar economic recovery.
   He said dictator Josef Stalin began the practice of ignoring the
real causes of slow development and blaming it on the war.
   More than 20 million Soviet citizens died in the war and about
one-quarter of the housing and industry in the European part of the
country was destroyed.
   Stalin launched a rebuilding campaign that replaced many
factories wrecked in the war, but housing remains a serious problem
and farms still fail to produce enough food for the country.
   ``Sometimes it is necessary to compare how quickly and
powerfully has been the economic rebirth of the capitulated nations
West Germany and Japan, which were brought to ruins, thoroughly
destroyed, dismantled to the last nut,'' Aitmatov wrote.
   He said Soviet officials also remain reluctant to credit the
United States and Britain for their help in winning the war.
Aitmatov specifically mentioned nearly 15,000 warplanes provided to
the Soviet Union.
   Aitmatov is a severe critic of totalitarianism and the
dehumanizing influences of Stalinism. He condemned the
collectivization of the 1930s that removed peasants from the land
and noted that, half a century later, the government must buy grain
abroad.
   Soviet planners should take a lesson from reforms carried out in
China, where ``no one is particularly sad about the failure of
communes,'' he said. Aitmatov's point seemed to be that more family
farms would improve output.
   Embracing the reforms of Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, he
said more democracy and openness were the only hope for a better
future.
</TEXT>
