<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2032EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SovietJewry     05-03 0673</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Jewry,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Now Processing Exit Applications `Reasonably Fast'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet authorities are now processing
emigration applications ``reasonably fast'' and Jews who wish to
leave should take advantage of the opportunity in case the
situation changes, a high-ranking U.S. official said Tuesday.
   Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for human rights
and humanitarian affairs, also said he saw some signs of growing
religious toleration in the Soviet Union.
   Schifter, in remarks to the National Conference on Soviet Jewry,
said he believed a huge percentage of the Soviet Union's two
million Jews would emigrate if given the chance.
   Most have not applied, knowing they would be subject to
discrimination in employment and other opportunities during the
long _ often unending _ period while waiting for approval.
   Schifter said, however, ``It looks as if a good many people
could get their cases processed reasonably fast if they were to
apply right now. They're afraid and they're afraid quite rightfully
because anything can turn in the Soviet Union with a very short
time and they can find themselves in great difficulty after that.
   ``A good many of them also are not fully aware today of what the
possibilities are: that you can indeed fill out the forms, get them
filed and there's a chance within six weeks or two months perhaps
to get your application processed,'' he said.
   Schifter said Soviet Jews should be assured ``that the
possibilities are there now and they ought to take advantage of it
if this is what they want to do.''
   After reaching a high point of 51,320 exit permits in 1979,
Soviet emigration declined to 914 in 1986. It rebounded to 8,155 in
1987 and will go even higher this year if the monthly figures hold
up. In March, for example, 986 Jews emigrated, the highest monthly
total since 1981, according to the Conference on Soviet Jewry.
   The United States has been urging the Soviets to allow freer
emigration and religious freedom. Schifter said a pledge by
Gorbachev last week to show more tolerance toward religion
represented ``somewhat of an opening.''
   He also said it appeared that for the past half year the Soviets
have not enforced laws prohibiting adult Jewish education classes.
Schifter expressed some optimism that the Soviets will permit the
importation of bibles.
   Schifter did not appear particularly concerned about Gorbachev's
condemnation, during a visit by Secretary of State George P. Shultz
last month, of the Reagan administration's continued criticism of
Soviet human rights practices.
   ``He gets annoyed about these things,'' Schifter said of
Gorbachev. ``He is a person who has a short fuse on matters of this
kind. But the fact of the matter is that they are moving in this
area.''
   President Reagan is expected to continue raising the issues when
he goes to Moscow for the May 29-June 2 summit.
   Shultz told the Soviet Jewry conference that during his visit to
Moscow in April, he raised several human rights concerns, but
concentrated on Jewish emigration. He said the United States is
seeking improvements on five aspects of the issue:
   _Processing time. ``There are too many bureaucratic delays,''
Shultz said of the application process. ``While they can't admit it
they (Soviet leaders) see it as a real problem.''
   _Applications denied for security reasons. Many Jews'
applications are rejected on grounds they hold state secrets, even
those who haven't worked in defense plants for decades. There's
been no movement from the Soviets on this, ``but at least the
problem is up there on the table,'' Shultz said.
   _Family restrictions. The Soviets deny applications to those who
do not have close relatives in the West, a practice that violates
human rights accords the Soviets have signed, Shultz said.
   _Ill applicants. The Soviets should loosen up on applications
from people seeking medical care elsewhere, the secretary said.
   _Parental veto. Under Soviet law, the parents of an applicant
can veto the granting of a permit, even if the child is an adult.
``They're looking into it,'' Shultz said.
</TEXT>
