<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Germany-USRabbi 1stLd-Writethru   05-03 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Germany-US Rabbi, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0702,0641</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>East German Jews Criticize Departing Rabbi</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to add earlier comment from Neuman;
picks up 3rd pvs: A statement...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German Jews on Tuesday accused their
departing American rabbi of high living and improper performance of
duties and said they were looking for another man to become the
communist nation's only rabbi.
   One local Jew, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said some
community members had begun calling Isaac Neuman ``the Hollywood
rabbi.''
   Numerous telephone calls to Neuman's home were unanswered
Tuesday. However, Neuman said on Sunday that such issues as his
apartment and car were not part of the tensions that prompted him
to decide to leave.
   A statement from the East Berlin Jewish community, carried by
the official ADN news agency, responded to criticisms made by
Neuman when he announced last weekend he was leaving May 16 after
only eight months.
   The 65-year-old rabbi from Champaign, Ill., had complained of
what he called anti-Semitism in East Germany and interference in
his work from local Jewish leadership.
   Tuesday's statement from local Jewish leaders said, ``His
current assertion that anti-Semitic tendencies in the press ...
have caused his return were never raised in his discussions with
the community.''
   East Germany officially maintains it has wiped out anti-Semitism
in its nearly four decades of existence.
   The statement also charged Neuman with improperly carrying out
some of his duties, such as dealing with the elderly and preparing
youths for Bar Mitzvah.
   The Polish-born Neuman, a Nazi prisoner during World War II, in
September became the first rabbi in 21 years for this nation's
Jewish community of about 450 people.
   There was no official word on a replacement for Neuman.
   Community members who spoke on condition of anonymity said
Neuman would be succeeded by Chicago Rabbi Ernst M. Lorge. Others
sources close to the community said Lorge would be appointed only
on an interim basis, while a young rabbi was sought as a permanent
replacement.
   Lorge, 71, said Tuesday in Chicago he had received no official
invitation to come to East Germany. ``If I do, I would have to
think about it,'' he said.
   He said he did not want to stay in East Germay year-round but
might accept a short-term arrangement.
   Lorge was born in Mainz, Germany, and emigrated to the United
States fleeing Nazi persecution in 1936.
   Neuman, explaining his reasons for leaving in an interview
Tuesday, said, ``I am unhappy about East Germany and
anti-Semitism.''
   He criticized the East German news media's depiction of
Palestinian unrest in Israel.
   ``Sometimes the way Israel is depicted is in a Nazi-like
fashion,'' he said. ``They have cut anti-Semitism but have not
succeeded in uprooting it.''
   He also complained about interference in his work. His main
objections focused on the local Jewish community president, Peter
Kirchner, who signed the statement distributed Tuesday by the East
German news agency.
   ``The assertion that Rabbi Neuman was hindered in carrying out
his functions by members, or the community representatives, or
other people must be rejected with emphasis,'' the statement said.
   East Berlin Jewish community members, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said there had long been criticism of Neuman and his
lifestyle.
   ``He would drive to West Berlin every day to get fresh
tomatoes,'' said one local Jew.
   Community members said Neuman was provided with a large
apartment and a car during his tenure.
   The community supported Neuman with funds provided by the
government.
   The East German Jewish community includes less than 350
officially registered members and about 100 other worshipers,
Neuman said. However, some estimates say that there are as many as
2,500 non-practicing Jews in East Germany.
</TEXT>
