<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseSpending 1stLd-Writethru a0716 05-03 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Spending, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes for Minimum Number of Missile Subs in Any U.S.-Soviet
Treaty</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th graf pvs, bgng: `It is, to UPDATE
with Persian Gulf vote. Picks up 9th graf pvs, In another</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Tuesday urged President Reagan to
maintain at least 20 missile-firing submarines as part of any
U.S.-Soviet agreement to cut back strategic nuclear weapons.
   The voice-vote decision came as the chamber adopted an amendment
to a bill authorizing the Pentagon budget for the fiscal year
starting Oct. 1.
   Both nations are now negotiating to achieve a Strategic Arms
Reduction Talks (START) treaty that could provide reductions of up
to 50 percent in each country's stockpile of long-range atomic
weapons.
   Those stockpiles are made up of submarine-launched missiles,
land-based missiles and bombers. Under the proposed treaty, both
sides would be required to reduce and restructure their arsenals.
   The United States now has more than half its strategic firepower
aboard 36 missile-firing subs, including 28 Poseidon-class boats
and eight of the giant Trident-class subs. Seven more Tridents are
under construction, while a 16th is authorized in the bill now on
the House floor.
   The United States hasn't yet decided how to restack its
stockpile under a START treaty, but the amendment offered by Rep.
Stephen Solarz, D-N.Y., said at least 20 submarines should be
retained.
   ``Our ability to prevent nuclear war depends more than anything
else on the maintenance of a survivable nuclear deterrent,'' said
Solarz, who added that subs are virtually invulnerable to attack
while they are at sea.
   ``It is in our interest to have the maximum number of submarines
possible,'' Solarz said.
   As it worked through the bill, the chamber also gave voice vote
approval to an amendment banning the sending of any Coast Guard
vessels to help the Navy patrol the Persian Gulf.
   Supporters of the amendment had said a day earlier they planned
to drop the proposal in the wake of a Pentagon announcement that
the deployment plan was being shelved. But as the issue arose
Tuesday, a procedural snare meant it was easier to simply approve
the amendment than to bypass it.
   In another decision, the House voted 213-195 to give federal
contractors more freedom to set pay scales.
   The vote approved an amendment overhauling the Davis-Bacon Act,
the 1931 law which requires that employees covered by contracts on
federal jobs worth more than $2,000 should be paid the prevailing
local wage rate, a figure determined by the Labor Department. The
rate is commonly the same rate paid union workers.
   The measure approved Tuesday would raise the threshold figure
from $2,000 to $50,000.
   The vote came shortly before the chamber rejected, 210-204, a
move that would have raised the Davis-Bacon threshold from $2,000
to $250,000.
   The Davis-Bacon law was enacted during the Great Depression amid
worries that construction companies would hire cheap labor.
   Tuesday's votes on the bill went generally along party lines,
with Democrats backing the $50,000 threshold and Republicans
supporting the $250,000 threshold.
   There have been a number of attempts during the Reagan
administration to change the law by critics who contend that the
$2,000 figure is outdated. Organized labor has strongly supported
the Davis-Bacon law.
   The amendment approved Tuesday was essentially the same measure
passed last Aug. 4 by the House Education and Labor Committee. That
bill hasn't yet come to the floor, but committee leaders said they
offered it as an amendment to the Pentagon budget bill in an effort
to forestall the amendment proposing a $250,000 threshold.
   Neither the START nor the Davis-Bacon amendments adopted Tuesday
is part of the Pentagon budget bill which the Senate will be
considering next week.
   Differences between the measures that eventually pass each
chamber will be worked out in a House-Senate conference committee.
   Both measures authorize $299.5 billion in Pentagon spending for
the next fiscal year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
