<2ND_LINE>AM-Dyson,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman to Leave Seclusion, Hold News Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Roy Dyson, D-Md., scheduled a news
conference in his district Wednesday after remaining in seclusion
following the death of his top aide last weekend in a plunge from
the 24th floor of a New York City hotel.
   The session with reporters was announced Tuesday by Katie
Tucker, who also told reporters that she has been elevated from
press secretary to chief of staff.
   Ms.Tucker will replace Tom Pappas, who police said apparently
jumped to his death Sunday from his room in the Helmsley Palace
Hotel after leaving a note.
   ``Congressman Roy Dyson will introduce Ms. Tucker to the people
of the First District on Wednesday, May 4 at 2 p.m. at the Southern
Maryland Electric Cooperative in Hughesville, Md.,'' said Ms.
Tucker's statement.
   Ms. Tucker returned to Dyson's office as press secretary just a
week ago. She had worked there as press secretary and legislative
assistant in 1985.
   While Dyson did not attend a session of the House of
Representatives on Tuesday, the House approved an amendment offered
by him to the defense authorization bill. The amendment would
require the secretary of the Navy to establish a ``Tethered
Aerostat Radar Surveillance System'' near the Patuxent Naval Air
Station that could be used by the Defense and Treasury departments
in drug surveillance operations.
   Dyson also missed a meeting of the House Merchant Marine and
Fisheries Committee, but voted by proxy on amendments to a bill
that would open up the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge to oil
drillers. A check of the proxy by The Associated Press showed that
it was signed by Dyson last week.
   Pappas was Dyson's closest aide and top adviser from the time
Dyson was elected to the state legislature in 1974. His death came
the same day The Washington Post published an article quoting
former aides as saying that Pappas pressured male staffers to
socialize with him.
   The staffers said the pressure did not go beyond demands that
they attend parties and social functions with Pappas.
   There also have been numerous articles recently concerning
payments made from Dyson's campaign funds to a media relations
company owned by Pappas. Payments to Pappenbauer Associates totaled
$119,642 since 1980, a revised Dyson campaign report showed.
   Democratic leaders in the congressional district say they don't
believe Dyson's prospects for being re-elected to a fifth term in
November will be jeopardized by publicity surrounding the death of
Pappas and the campaign payments to him.
   They say, however, that the extent of the damage will depend on
how Dyson confronts his problems.
   ``There are a lot of folks who need some direction. I think he
needs to make a statement,'' state Delegate Daniel Long, a Dyson
supporter, said Tuesday.
   Long said, however, he doesn't blame Dyson for going into
seclusion.
   ``He has lost his friend, his mentor, his campaign manager, his
top aide,'' he said.
</TEXT>
