<HEAD>Precede MORGANTOWN, W.Va.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Celebrates Clinching The Nomination _ A Week After The Fact</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 17 grafs on Bush rally; picks up 8th graf pvs,
bgng: In his; edits to tighten</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush told a victory
rally on Tuesday his clinching of the Republican presidential
nomination was just a first step, while his son told campaign
workers to ``go out and kick some Mike Dukakis.''
   Bush celebrated his mathematical lock on the nomination at an
``Over the Top'' party at a Washington hotel.
   The vice president said surpassing the 1,139 delegates needed
for nomination _ which he actually did in last week's Pennsylvania
primary _ ``wrapped this thing up sooner than I think any of us
thought might take place.''
   Bush was was expected to pick up another 132 delegates in
Tuesday's winner-take-all GOP primaries in Ohio, Indiana and the
District of Columbia.
   ``It all boiled down to working together,'' Bush told his
campaign staff and volunteer workers.
   ``And yet,'' he added, ``I don't feel any finality to what has
happened now at all. We've passed the first step, a tremendously
important step... But now we've got a long way to go.''
   George Bush Jr., sharing the platform with his father, told the
group: ``Our dad needs a real job.''
   ``Sometimes sons can say things a father can't. We want you to
go out there and kick some Mike Dukakis, and kick him hard,'' he
said.
   The younger Bush's remarks about the Democratic front-runner
were a play on Bush's celebrated off-color gloat to New Jersey
longshoremen in which he characterized his performance in his 1984
debate with Democratic vice presidential candidate Geraldine
Ferraro.
   The vice president declared to rousing cheers that ``the party
is united.''
   ``I don't believe there are any deep divisions in this party at
all,'' he said. ``Let Mike Dukakis go around here talking about
pink slips, despair, pessimism in the United States. I'll be the
guy out there talking about hope and opportunity and challenge.''
   Republican Party Chairman Frank Fahrenkopf told the gathering:
``Tonight we officially celebrate the fact that George Bush will be
our nominee following the convention in New Orleans.''
   Although Bush campaign aides earlier had said there was a
possibility that President Reagan would attend the rally to
formally voice his endorsement of Bush, the president was not in
attendance.
   ``It never really jelled,'' said Bush spokesman Peter Teeley.
   However, campaign and White House aides suggested that it was
likely Reagan's endorsement would come soon, perhaps within the
week.
   Campaigning earlier in Morgantown, W.Va., Bush said that
Americans have gotten ``a little fat, dumb and happy'' about the
nation's energy needs and growing dependence on foreign oil.
   At West Virginia University, Bush watched university scientists
display a model of a ``circulating fluidized bed'' that eases the
mining process by converting minerals to liquids.
   In his speech after leaving the research facility, he quipped,
``At one point, some guy was going into all this fluoride bed thing
and the doctor said, `Do you understand that?' and I said, `Hell,
no. The last thing I understood was when the guy said hello.' But
it was impressive.''
   Earlier, he said the acid rain problem that Canadian Prime
Minister Brian Mulroney recently discussed with President Reagan
made it even more urgent to find clean ways to burn coal.
   ``There's no way you can make an energy model for the future
without coal as a very important part,'' he said.
   Bush called his trip to West Virginia, which has its primary
next Tuesday, ``a relatively non-political visit,'' and avoided
partisan remarks in his speech.
   Asked by reporters about barbs he has traded with Dukakis, Bush
said, ``I found myself going back at him a little more than I
wanted to.''
   On picking a vice president, Bush said he wanted someone loyal
whom he could trust.
   When a reporter said that sounded like Bush himself, he replied,
``That's just fine with me. And he ought to be prepared to take a
helluva lot of flak for handling it that way.''
</TEXT>
