<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Indians     05-03 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Indians,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Indians Surrender, Government Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 200 rebel Indians backed
by the United States surrendered their weapons and agreed to join
the Sandinistas, the government newspaper El Nuevo Diario said
Tuesday.
   It said the Indians agreed to stop military actions against the
Sandinistas and to ``not allow the presence of guerrilla groups in
the territory.''
   The Indians, like other Contra groups operating from Honduras
and Costa Rica, had U.S. backing and fought the leftist Sandinista
government since 1981.
   Tens of thousands of Miskito, Rama and Sumo Indians left their
tribal homelands beginning in 1981 after the government tried to
impose Marxism in the area and said it would move them to
relocation camps.
   Many Indians crossed the Rio Coco and sought refuge in Honduras
rather than move to relocation camps. Thousands took up arms,
creating rebel movements which, like the larger Nicaraguan
Resistance, received U.S. aid.
   Most of the refugees have returned to their native 75-mile-long
region along the Atlantic seaboard. The region is considered a
national security area and foreigners are barred unless they have
Interior Ministry permission.
   The Sandinistas some years ago acknowledged their errors with
the Indians and sought their support.
   By March 1, nearly 7,000 had returned from Honduran refugee
camps, according to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
   The government has not been as successful with other Contra
groups. A fragile interim truce has been in place since April 1 as
Contras and Sadinista leaders negotiate a permanent peace accord.
</TEXT>
