<DOCNO> AP880503-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2021EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ChicagoMayoral     05-03 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chicago Mayoral,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago Elections Board Sets 1989 Special Mayoral Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city elections board voted unanimously
Tuesday to hold a special mayoral election in spring 1989 to choose
a successor to the late Mayor Harold Washington, whose term would
have ended in 1991.
   ``We're proceeding with the 1989 election unless we're ordered
to the contrary by the court,'' said Tom Leach, a spokesman for the
city Board of Elections Commissioners.
   The board had voted April 24 to hold a special mayoral election
in April 1989 if City Clerk Walter Kozubowski declared that
Washington's death in late November created a vacancy in the
position.
   Kozubowski said at the time he wouldn't issue such a declaration
unless ordered to do so by a court. But on Monday, he apparently
changed his mind and provided the elections board with the
documentation, Leach said.
   ``The board decided to accept the declaration of a vacancy from
the city clerk and decided to go ahead with the 1989 election
unless we're ordered not to by the courts,'' Leach said.
   Circuit Judge Eugene Wachowski said last week he expected to
rule on the issue at a hearing Friday.
   Supporters of acting Mayor Eugene Sawyer and Alderman Tim Evans,
a rival and potential mayoral candidate, have been feuding over
when the next mayoral election should be held.
   Evans hailed Tuesday's decision as ``a great victory for all of
Chicago.''
   ``We have never doubted that 1989 is the legally correct time
for a special election,'' he said in a statement issued from
Atlanta, where he is attending a meeting of city finance officers.
   ``Now, however belatedly, the board of elections has heard the
voices of the people and has followed the dictates of law. It is a
great victory for all of Chicago, one that is certain to be upheld
by the courts,'' Evans said.
   Sawyer's press secretary, Monroe Anderson, did not return a
telephone call seeking comment.
   Under the plan approved Tuesday, Leach said, a primary election
would be held Feb. 28, followed by a general election April 4,
1989, that also would be used to choose a 6th Ward alderman to
succeed acting Mayor Eugene Sawyer.
   Sawyer was elected Washington's successor by the City Council
shortly after the city's first black mayor died of a heart attack
in late November.
   Both sides filed lawsuits asking the Cook County Circuit Court
to decide the issue. Evans forces have sought a 1989 special
election, while Sawyer's allies have been fighting for the 1991
election.
   ``Naturally, it's going to be fought out in the court,'' Leach
said Tuesday.
   He said the elections board would not contest any court decision
dictating when the next mayoral election should be held.
   ``We take a neutral position. We don't fight anything,'' Leach
said.
</TEXT>
