<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2115EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Meese     05-03 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Meese,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Says Police Need Worldwide Links</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Attorney General Edwin Meese III said Tuesday
that police worldwide need to cooperate more closely because
terrorism, organized crime and drug trafficking have reached
international dimensions.
   ``It is not unusual for a person to commit a crime and be half a
world away in the next few hours,'' Meese told the fifth annual
meeting of the International Association of Police Chiefs.
   He predicted that many local police cars in the United States
would be equipped with minicomputers with access to international
computers.
   Meese cited possible links between a fatal bombing outside a
U.S. military club in Naples, Italy, and the arrest of a Japanese
man carrying pipe bombs on the New Jersey Turnpike.
   He said U.S. investigators determined that the man, Yu Kikumura,
was ``a known member'' of the Japanese Red Army, a terrorist group
whose members were blamed for detonating a car bomb on April 14
outside the Naples USO club.
   Meese said such incidents require ``the highest level in the
sharing of intelligence between governments.''
   Italian officials issued arrest warrants for two fugitive
members of the Japanese Red Army in the Naples bombing. The attack
killed four Italians and an American servicewoman.
   Meese also told the law enforcenment officials from 60 countries
that crime in the United States is climbing and that the spread and
sale of drugs ``seems to be getting worse instead of better.''
   Recalling his trip last month to Latin America, Meese said he
flew over a coca field 75 miles wide and 200 miles long, proving
the pervasive spread of cocaine production in the area.
   He said drug production now has ``a potential for undermining
governments.''
   Before the opening of the three-day meeting in Rome, Meese met
with Justice Minister Giuliano Vassali to discuss improving
extradition procedures between Italy and the United States and to
organize joint education programs for police and other law
enforcement agencies.
   Meese said he granted an Italian request to consider
transferring an Italian convicted of subversion, Silvia Baraldini,
now in a high security prison in Lexington, Ky., to another
facility currently under construction.
   Members of parliament have asked that her prison conditions be
improved.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
