<DOCNO> AP880503-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AutoRecall     05-03 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Auto Recall,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toyota Announces Program to Fix Brake Pedal Pulsation in Camrys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toyota announced Tuesday that owners of about
380,000 Camrys are entitled to have a brake pedal pulsation problem
repaired free.
   The voluntary recall, which is available to owners of 1983-1986
Camrys and certain early 1987 Camrys, is designed to correct a
brake pedal pulsation problem that some owners have complained
about, said Debra Sanchez, a spokeswoman for Toyota Motor Sales
U.S.A. Inc. in Torrance, Calif.
   Brake pedal pulsation can be felt by drivers when their foot is
on the pedal, but it does not affect braking effectiveness or
steering control, Sanchez said. Brake pedal pulsation is caused by
movement of the brake pads as they pass over the brake disc, she
said.
   Later this month, Toyota plans to notify owners of the cars in
phases based on model years. The problem will be fixed at no charge
to the customer for a period of 12 months from the date of
notification, the company said.
   The action comes in the wake of a class-action lawsuit filed in
California state court by two public interest law firms seeking
free repairs and reimbursement for car owners who have paid to have
their Camrys fixed or checked.
   ``We're impressed with this step they're taking. There's no
question it's a major commitment,'' John Phillips of the Center for
Law in the Public Interest said of Toyota's announcement.
   Attorneys will pursue the suit, however, because, ``We've
alleged that they've engaged in a secret warranty for this defect
by notifying the dealers and not notifying the owners,'' Phillips
said.
   The Center for Auto Safety in Washington, D.C., joined in the
suit filed April 20 in Los Angeles County Superior Court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
