<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     05-03 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Detain Five More Strike Sympathizers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista police detained five hunger
strike sympathizers on Tuesday when they tried to talk to reporters
in the area where workers were on the ninth day of a fast to demand
higher pay.
   The officers, members of the Interior Ministry's Special Forces
unit, cited a ban on unauthorized public activities.
   Police have taken at least 40 people into custody during the
past week in connection with the hunger strike by more than 30
construction workers and car mechanics.
   Sandinista policewomen, wearing black berets and toting rubber
truncheons, cordoned off the front of the headquarters of the
General Workers Federation, a coalition of socialist
anti-government unions, and kept journalists away.
   The five sympathizers stood around the corner from the union
hall and told reporters that authorities would not let them get
close to the union building, where some hunger strikers peered
through locked gates.
   Police pushed through the journalists, grabbed the five and
shoved them into three different vehicles.
   ``This is an unauthorized public act,'' said a Sandinista police
officer who refused to give his name.
   Police last Friday night permitted a group of Sandinsta students
to hold a rally at the same spot where the arrests were made.
   Interior Minister Tomas Borge last week reportedly punched in
the mouth the director of an anti-government radio station for
broadcasting what Borge said was wrong information about the
strike. The Sandinista newspaper Barricada reported the altercation.
   About 1,500 construction workers and auto mechanics have been on
strike since the end of February for higher salaries and improved
working conditions.
   The wildcat strikes are an embarrassment to the leftist
Sandinista government.
   Such strikes were illegal for almost six years under a state of
emergency that was lifted in January.
   President Daniel Ortega removed the restrictions as part of a
regional peace plan which includes calls for democratic reforms.
Ortega and the presidents of Honduras, Guatemala, El Salvador and
Costa Rica signed the agreement last August.
   Public demonstrations are allowed only with Interior Ministry
permission.
   The state-run telephone company meanwhile cut off service to
about 6,000 offices and homes in Managua because of overdue bills
totaling $1.8 million.
   The cutoff left the national banking system, embassies,
state-run enterprises, government offices and thousands of homes in
the capital without telephone service. There are a total of 29,000
phones in Managua, a city of about 900,000 people.
   Hundreds of Nicaraguans went to the Nicaraguan
Telecommunications and Postal Institute protesting the shutoff and
saying they had paid their bills.
   A telephone company spokeswoman, Maritza Flores, acknowledged
that some phones were disconnected because of ``computer
problems,'' but said other customers had not paid their bills for
several months.
   The cutoff came Saturday and was reported in local newspapers
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
