<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-03 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0421</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>Showers and Thunderstorms Cover Central States
^By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms covered much of the central United
States Tuesday and pelted Arkansas and Missouri with hail, after
areas of Kansas and Nebraska soaked up more than 5 inches of rain.
   Sunny skies prevailed over the northern Midwest states, and
temperatures soared into the upper 70s in central and northern
Minnesota.
   The heaviest thunderstorms hit northern Arkansas, Missouri and
eastern Kansas.
   In northeast Arkansas, walnut-size hail was reported near
Pocahontas and one-inch hail fell in Lawrence County. Marble-size
hail was reported in several parts of central Missouri.
   Showers and thunderstorms also stretched from western Tennessee
to the Missouri Valley into eastern South Dakota. There were also a
few showers over eastern Pennsylvania and eastern Maryland and over
the central Gulf Coast.
   Rain tapered off during the morning over Kansas and Nebraska. In
the 24 hours ending at 8 a.m. EDT Tuesday, McDonald, Kan. reported
5} inches of rain and 4 inches were recorded during the same period
over parts of central Nebraska.
   Skies were sunny over Michigan and Wisconsin and temperatures
climbed well into the 70s in Minnesota. International Falls, Minn.,
on the Canadian border, registered a balmy 77 degrees at 3 p.m. EDT.
   Skies were cloudy and temperatures stayed in the 40s and 50s
over the northern and central Plains. Temperatures in New England
also stayed cool in the 50s.
   Showers continued along coastal sections of the Pacific
Northwest with some snow at the higher elevations. A snow advisory
was in effect for the Oregon Cascades.
   Sunny skies and warm temperatures prevailed from central Texas
to southern California.
   At 3 p.m. EDT, temperatures ranged from 37 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo., to 89 degrees at Cotulla, Texas, and Chase Naval
Air Station, Beeville, Texas.
   The low for the nation Tuesday morning was 7 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
   Showers and thunderstorms were forecast Wednesday to extend from
the Middle Atlantic states to the Carolinas and into the Tennessee
and Ohio Valleys. Showers and thunderstorms also were predicted to
stretch from the northern Pacific Coast to the northern Rockies and
into northern Nevada.
   High temperatures were predicted to be in the 50s in Washington,
Oregon, western Idaho, northwest Nevada and northern California.
Highs were forecast in the 80s in Florida, the Gulf Coast and most
of Texas, and into the 90s in the desert southwest. Highs elsewhere
were forecast to be in the 60s or 70s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
