<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland 2ndLd-Writethru   05-03 0924</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0689,0950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikers Demand Legalization of Solidarity; Walesa Speaks at
Shipyard</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WAR50,51</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 grafs after 6th pvs, ``A striker...'' to UPDATE
with sympathy strikes in Gdansk, march in Warsaw; picks up 7th pvs:
Walesa, who...; SUBS 19th graf pvs, ``Government and...'' with 1
graf to UPDATE with mine strike ending.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 7,000 strikers at the Lenin
shipyard, where Solidarity was born eight years ago, demanded
Tuesday that the outlawed union federation be made legal again. The
government called that ``not negotiable.''
   Solidarity founder Lech Walesa, 44, spoke to the strikers
several times, but said he would not lead the strike.
   ``I am not your leader. I'm tired,'' said the man who vaulted
the shipyard fence in 1980 and took charge of a labor revolt that
brought down a government. ``You need a new Walesa, many more new
Walesas.''
   ``You declared this strike,'' he said. ``I'm with you and I'll
always be with you. I can advise you. I have some experience.
   ``If we don't achieve a real reform this time, then we will have
a bloody revolution.''
   A striker offered a loaf of bread, a Polish gesture of
hospitality. Walesa broke off a piece and munched on it.
   Four thousand ship-repair workers and 1,000 port workers at
another Gdansk shipyard stayed off the job Tuesday in sympathy with
the strikers at the Lenin shipyard, said Joanna Wojciechowicz, a
Solidarity activist in Gdansk.
   The report could not be independently confirmed. There was no
answer at the ship repair yard.
   In Warsaw, meanwhile, protesters marched in the streets in
support of the strikers, an opposition spokesman said. They were
dispersed by police.
   Walesa, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, still works at the
shipyard as an electrician but is on sick leave this week,
complaining of back pains and low blood sugar.
   On the first day of the shipyard strike Monday, workers asked
that a local Solidarity chapter be approved, but on Tuesday
demanded reinstatement of the union nationwide. Solidarity, the
first independent union in the Soviet bloc, was crushed and
outlawed after martial law was declared Dec. 13, 1981.
   A large poster at the gate listed the other demands: higher pay,
release of political prisoners and reinstatement of fired activists.
   Polish workers want pay raises of up to 60 percent to compensate
for price increases of 42 percent that resulted from reduction of
subsidies by the Communist government.
   The labor trouble, which has lasted more than a week, is the
worst in Poland since the crackdown on Solidarity. The biggest
strike is by 15,000 workers at the Nowa Huta steel complex in the
south, the nation's largest industrial plant.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said of the demand for
nationwide recognition of Solidarity: ``This is not a question that
can be an object of negotiations. It is not negotiable.''
   During a Warsaw news conference, he said strike leaders were
``professional politicians'' working for Western powers.
   Despite his protests, Walesa was emerging Tuesday as the
dominant figure among the Gdansk strikers.
   ``We lost eight years,'' he said through a loudspeaker. ``Here,
in the birthplace of Solidarity, I state to the authorities that
they are deepening the losses, they are forcing Solidarity to lead
the nation onto the road to reforms.''
   In Poland, strikers customarily occupy their places of work.
When police cordoned off the shipyard Tuesday, Walesa stayed inside
with the strikers, said his adviser, the Rev. Henryk Jankowski.
   Strikes began April 25 with a wildcat action by transit workers
in Bydgoszcz that was settled the same day with pay raises of at
least 50 percent. The Nowa Huta strike began the next day.
   On Friday, thousand of employees at the Stalowa Wola heavy
machinery plant quit working but the strike was settled Saturday by
promises of higher pay.
   Government and opposition spokesmen confirmed a brief work
stoppage Tuesday at a railroad car plant in Wroclaw, and opposition
spokesmen said about 1,000 miners occupied a copper mine in western
Poland for eight hours. Jerzy Jarmuzek, manager of the Rudna mine,
said only 150 workers were involved.
   University students in Krakow, Poznan and Gdansk struck in
sympathy with the workers, according to opposition spokesmen in the
three cities.
   Police have rounded up about a dozen dissident leaders and
apparently cut off the telephones of others. Sources said some
people were staying away from home for fear of detention.
   Walesa told reporters that Bogdan Lis, a Gdansk regional
Solidarity chief, and eight other regional leaders were detained.
Other prominent figures reported arrested were dissident
intellectual Adam Michnik and Leszek Moczulski, leader of the
rightist opposition Confederation of Independent Poland.
   Urban called the detentions ``preventive.''
   The strike at the 12,000-worker Lenin shipyard began Monday soon
after the breakfast break and grew to between 7,000 and 8,000
people by Tuesday morning, said Alojzy Szablewski, chairman of the
strike committee.
   On Tuesday, the shipyard cranes were idle and only transport,
power and some other essential operations appeared to be
functioning.
   Hundreds of strikers were at the main gates, wearing Solidarity
badges and arm bands. The gate was festooned with yellow flowers,
Solidarity banners, and pictures of Pope John Paul II, a native of
Poland, and the Black Madonna, Poland's revered icon.
   Some workers sat atop the gate, which bore a huge sign saying
``Occupation Strike.'' Others climbed on the roofs of buildings to
hear Walesa speak.
   Cheers of ``Solidarity!'' and ``Lech, Lech!'' rose on both sides
of the gate when Walesa arrived.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
