<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0838 05-03 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0838,000</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Wins In District Of Columbia, Repeating '84 Showing</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 4 grafs Jackson reax; loss in Ohio; picks up 4th
graf pvs, bgng: As voters</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender Jesse
Jackson scored an easy win in the District of Columbia's primary on
Tuesday, telling backers: ``We're moving right along.''
   Earlier, he had urged supporters in the capital to ``vote with a
passion.''
   It was his first primary election victory since he won Puerto
Rico in March. Jackson also swept the District of Columbia primary
in 1984.
   Jackson did not fare as well in the day's two other contests,
losing to Michael Dukakis in Indiana and Ohio.
   As voters were going to the polls in the nation's capital,
Jackson spoke to the group of ministers, and joked about moving
into the White House.
   ``Today we stopped by Washington to pick out some furniture for
our new house,'' he said.
   Later, in Atlanta, Jackson spoke at the National Machinists
Union convention, where he was enthusiastically received by several
thousand unionists.
   Jackson focused his speech on labor issues, telling the group he
had stood with union members on many picket lines and plant
closings. It has been a consistent theme in recent weeks as Jackson
campaigned in industrial-state primaries.
   ``I'm a working person,'' he said.
   Jackson spoke of his plan to reinvest public pension funds in
domestic infrastructure projects which would provide jobs for
Americans and counter the current rash of jobs that corporations
are taking to cheap foreign labor markets.
   His speech was interrupted by thunderous applause and shouts at
several points.
   ``Do I make sense?'' he asked them.
   ``Yes,'' screamed the workers.
   ``Then vote for me,'' Jackson said. ``I stood with you. Now you
stand with me. When I win, you win.''
   Jackson had headed into the three primaries sounding a combative
note, accusing front-runner Dukakis on Monday of running a
play-it-safe ``Teflon'' campaign.
   Addressing a crowd of 11,000 people at Ohio State, Jackson
continued to portray himself as the candidate of specific proposals
and budget plans, accusing Dukakis of being vague.
   ``So far Dukakis has operated with caution when we must operate
with clarity and courage and candor,'' he told reporters Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2149EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-StatePrimaryRdp 4thLd-Writethru a0834 05-03 1006</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Primary Rdp, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0834,1030</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New to dash with latest figures, quotes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Ohio Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, one of the most liberal members of
Congress, easily won the Democratic nomination for a third term
Tuesday, paving the way for a big-money battle against Cleveland's
Republican Mayor George Voinovich.
   In two other state primaries, Indiana Secretary of State Evan
Bayh and North Carolina Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan captured Democratic
nominations for governor and will seek to reclaim their states' top
post from Republicans.
   With 26 percent of the Ohio vote counted, Metzenbaum had 261,416
votes or 82.3 percent, and his lone opponent, Ralph Applegate, who
runs a Columbus lawn-care business, had 56,359 votes or 17.7
percent.
   In Indiana, with 35 percent of precincts reporting, Bayh had
156,731 votes or 82.3 percent, former Kokomo Mayor Stephen J. Daily
had 22,183 votes or 11.6 percent and Senate Minority Leader Frank
L. O'Bannon had 11,499 votes or 6.0 percent.
   Lt. Gov. John M. Mutz, 52, was unopposed for the Republican
nomination.
   Bayh, 32-year-old son of former Sen. Birch E. Bayh, was aided by
one of the most famous names in Indiana politics in his bid to end
20 years of Republican rule. Gov. Robert D. Orr was barred by state
law from seeking a third term.
   O'Bannon is Bayh's choice for lieutenant governor, but he put
his name on the ballot as a precaution when it appeared Bayh might
be ruled ineligible because of a five-year residency requirement.
But the state Supreme Court ruled last week that Bayh met the
qualifications.
   ``This campaign begins tonight and it will be as important as
any in the history of Indiana,'' said Bayh in claiming victory.
   Indiana also has a Senate race this year, but neither Republican
Sen. Richard G. Lugar nor Democratic attorney Jack Wickes had
primary challenges.
   In North Carolina, with 21 percent of the vote in, Jordan had
70,197 votes or 80 percent. Next came Billy Martin, a
service-station employee not related to governor, with 9,751 votes
or 11 percent; then Carroll W. Crawford of Mount Ulla, a former Ku
Klux Klansman, with 3,921 votes or 4 percent; James T. LLoyd of
Salisbury with 1,786 votes or 2 percent, and Bruce Friedman, an
anti-nuclear activist from Sylva, with 1,765 votes or 2 percent.
   Jordan called the viictory ``the highest honor and the best
opportunity the North Carolina people have ever given me,'' and
predicted his campaign against GOP Gov. Jim Martin would be ``a
classic race.''
   Martin, only the second Republican this century to hold the
office, had no primary opposition as he sought a second term.
   Metzenbaum, 70, has consistently drawn top ratings from the
liberal Americans for Democratic Action based on his voting record,
and as a member of the Senate Judiciary Committee he helped lead
the fight against the Supreme Court nomination of Robert Bork.
   Voinovich, 51, who was unopposed for the GOP nomination, is a
moderate who recently came out in support of the trade bill which
President Reagan pledges to veto.
   Voinovich used the occasion to formally open his central Ohio
headquarters in the state capital, and predicted a hard-hitting,
cliff-hanger race in November against Metzenbaum.
   ``You mark my words. The most focused-on race in the United
States is going to be Metzenbaum-Voinovich. This will be a
barn-burner,'' Voinovich said in Columbus.
   Metzenbaum, who spent the night in Cleveland, issued a statement
saying he was honored that Democrats had given him an overwhelming
vote of confidence.
   ``And as I've said before,'' he added, ``when the votes are
counted in November, I'm confident that 1988 will be a very
disappointing year for Republican candidates named George.'
   Ohio also had two lively congressional races. A GOP primary in
the northwestern 5th District matched Ohio Senate President Paul
Gillmor against Robert Latta, son of Rep. Delbert Latta who is
retiring after 30 years in Washington. A third Republican, Rex
Damschroder, was also in the race, while Thomas Murray ran
unopposed for the district's Democratic nomination.
   In the Cleveland area's 20th District, six-term Rep. Mary Rose
Oakar faced a Democratic primary challenge from former Cleveland
Mayor Dennis Kucinich. Michael Sajna, a Republican write-in
candidate, was unopposed for the GOP nod.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Even before the primary, Voinovich and Metzenbaum squared off by
spending thousands on television ads questioning each other's
commitments to Social Security, retirement benefits and challenging
disclosure of personal financial information.
   Federal Election Commission reports showed that as of March 31
Metzenbaum had raised $4.4 million, the third-highest amount of any
incumbent senator seeking re-election this year.
   Voinovich, who raised $2.9 million by the same date, had
initially criticized his rival for collecting money out of state.
But he recently announced a fundraising drive of his own in major
cities around the country.
   In Indiana, Mutz, a 20-year veteran of the General Assembly and
executive branch, sought to make an issue of Bayh's youth and
experience, saying ``We're not talking about electing somebody
class president here.''
   Bayh responded that age was ``not relevant'' and said the
governorship was ``not just some kind of gold watch that someone is
awarded after 20 years of service.''
   A poll published Sunday by the Fort Wayne Journal-Gazette showed
Bayh with a 45 percent to 32 percent advantage over Mutz.
   The Democrats are on the losing side of current polls in North
Carolina, where the Greensboro News & Record reported that a recent
survey showed Jordan trailing Martin 47 percent to 39 percent with
14 percent undecided.
   Jordan has attacked Martin as trying to take credit for
Democrats' accomplishments. Martin claims that in his first three
years, more than 300,000 new jobs have come into the state ``from
poultry to high tech.''
   Jordan drew criticism in March when he told black newspaper
executives he agreed with them on some issues that he wouldn't
discuss publicly because he could not win ``without the white
redneck vote in eastern North Carolina.''
   Jordan said he hadn't meant to be derogatory and considered
himself a redneck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
