<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     05-03 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Hails ``Great'' Results in Indiana, Ohio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic front-runner Michael S. Dukakis refused
to lay claim to the presidential nomination after primary wins
Tuesday in Ohio and Indiana but said ``it's going to be difficult''
for rival Jesse Jackson to overtake him now.
   ``I feel great about today and the results today,'' the
Massachusetts governor told a Boston news conference after racking
up big wins in two of Tuesday's three primary contests. Jackson won
the District of Columbia primary.
   ``We've got to keep working,'' Dukakis said, reminding backers
he was still more than 500 delegates short of the 2,081 needed to
nominate.
   Despite a series of primary wins over Jackson, Dukakis said the
race for the nomination is not over. He vowed to campaign
aggressively through the final day of the primary season _ June 7 _
when voters in New Jersey and California cast ballots.
   ``I think it's going to be difficult,'' he said when asked if
Jackson had a chance to win the fight for the nomination. Asked if
he thought Jackson would view the latest primary results as a
trend, Dukakis smiled and said: ``I hope so.''
   Jackson has been increasingly critical of Dukakis in recent
days, but the governor declined to say whether he thought his rival
should tone it down.
   ``He's going to have to make that judgment,'' Dukakis said.
``I'm going to try to keep this as positive as I can. I don't mind
disagreement on issues. I just hope we can both continue to
campaign with the respect we've had for each other in the past
year.''
   Asked whether he believed President Reagan was delaying an
endorsement of Vice President George Bush to keep the media
spotlight on the almost-certain Republican nominee, Dukakis laughed
and said, ``You mean the astrology endorsement?''
   The White House acknowledged Tuesday that Nancy Reagan checks
the positions of the sun, the moon and the stars in terms of
scheduling the president's activities. However, Reagan said he has
never based any policy or decision ``in my mind'' on astrological
forecasts.
</TEXT>
