<DOCNO> AP880503-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2218EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-Letter     05-03 0960</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Letter,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Ethics Office Probing Letter Sent by Meese for Japan
Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Office of Government Ethics launched an
investigation Tuesday into a letter signed by Attorney General
Edwin Meese III and sent to 30,000 people encouraging them to
attend a conference in Japan, the head of the office said Tuesday
night.
   ``It started today,'' said Frank Q. Nebeker, head of the ethics
office. ``As a judge, I have received invitations of this sort in
year's past. I don't know at this point what this one is.''
   Nebeker, a former judge on the District of Columbia Court of
Appeals, said he was not sure what the problems might be with the
mailing, adding, ``We're attempting to ascertain what the facts
are.''
   In the letter, Meese is soliciting attendance at a meeting for
which the U.S. sponsor is a profit-making organization.
   The presidential order on ethics that is policed by the ethics
office forbids federal officials from engaging in any conduct that
might present the appearance of a conflict of interest or of losing
objectivity in governmental decision making or favoritism. The
appearance of such a problem is enough to trigger an investigation,
even when such problems don't exist in reality.
   It is a crime to use the Justice Department seal for
non-authorized purposes.
   Meese's letters on Office of the Attorney General stationery
with the Justice Department seal invited the recipients to join him
at a legal and economic conference in Japan on Aug. 29 to Sept. 1.
Meese will be heading the U.S. delegation to the conference called,
``The U.S.-Japan Bilateral Session: A New Era in Legal and Economic
Relations.''
   The meeting is sponsored in part by the Citizen Ambassador
Program of People to People International, according to the letter.
   While People to People International is a non-profit
organization set up originally in the State Department by
then-President Dwight Eisenhower, the Citizen Ambassador Program is
a profit-making organization, the chairman of that firm said
Tuesday night.
   ``Yes, the Citizen Ambassador Program is for-profit, which is
how Eisenhower established the program with the intention of making
it self-supporting,'' Norm Swanson said in a telephone interview
from his home in Spokane, Wash.
   Swanson said the letter went to about 30,000 people whose names
were ``provided by everyone from the American Bar Association, the
advisory committees on both sides, to the American Chamber of
Commerce in Japan.''
   Justice Department spokesman Terry Eastland said the department
was unaware that a profit-making organization was involved, but he
contended that even if it were, Meese's involvement might still be
justified due to the department's interest in international legal
questions.
   ``People to People International came to us and represented
themselves as a non-profit, tax-exempt organization,'' Eastland
said. ``To the extent that they're linked to some group that is
profit-making, that was not known by those making decisions on the
attorney general's participation.
   ``In the event it turns out a profit-making entity is involved,
it could be argued that the department could engage in a joint
venture so long as it was in the department's interest, and
obviously we have an interest in international legal questions,''
he said.
   Eastland said legal and ethics authorities in the department
reviewed both this letter and a similar one sent by Meese for a
conference sponsored by People to People International last summer
in China to make sure it was all right for the attorney general to
participate. The attorney general also hosted the American
delegation in China last year. In both cases, Meese's expenses will
be paid by the department, he said.
   The two-page letter from Meese was dated April 26 and says, in
part, ``Although attended and assisted by senior officials of the
governments of both Japan and the United States, the conference is
fittingly a non-governmental one administered on behalf of the
Japanese by Japan's Federation of Economic Organizations
(Keidanren) and on the American side by the Citizen Ambassador
Program of the People to People International organization.''
   ``I invite and encourage your participation. Sincerely Edwin
Meese III, Attorney General.''
   The letter was accompanied by an engraved invitation and a
response card to be sent to the Citizen Ambassador Program in
Spokane which would provide details on the trip.
   Swanson said he could not say how much profit might be involved
for his firm, which is quoting participants a cost of $3,240,
including transportation and lodging and an $800 registration fee
set by the Japanese organizing committee.
   ``I wish I knew,'' he said. ``It's not large. It depends on the
participation in the conference. Those profits are used to
encourage further exchanges, as they have for the last 35 years.''
   Meese's wife, Ursula, was paid by People to People International
to go on last summer's China trip, Swanson said.
   ``Her way to China was paid last year by People to People
International in return for the frankly exhausting role that she
fulfilled in being head of the women's contingent for the
conference,'' Swanson said. ``This was an economic law conference
in China which Mr. Meese hosted last year and which was very much
the precursor to the Japanese meeting.''
   Eastland said department regulations allow for payments for
spouses to be reimbursed by an outside entity, profit-making or
non-profit making, if certain conditions are met. In this case, the
conditions were met, he said.
   Swanson said the cost for the China meeting, including
transportation, was about $2,500. The registration fee there was
$400.
   Meese's expenses for the Japan trip will be picked up by the
government, since he is making an official visit at the invitation
of the Japanese Minister of Justice, Yukio Hayashida.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Associated Press writer Michael J. Sniffen also
contributed to this story.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
