<1ST_LINE>u a AM-AmtrakCrash     05-03 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amtrak Crash,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Conrail Announces $58 Million Settlement in Amtrak Crash Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consolidated Rail Corp. said Tuesday it has
tentatively agreed to pay $58 million to families of people killed
in Amtrak's worst accident, the 1987 collision of a passenger train
with Conrail engines in Chase, Md.
   The agreement was reached with attorneys representing the
estates of the victims and is subject to the approval of Conrail's
directors and various courts, according to a Conrail statement.
   Conrail spokesman Don Holloschutz said he did not know how many
of the victims' families the agreement covers.
   The $58 million would be in addition to the $7.5 million Conrail
has agreed to place in escrow as a part of a proposed settlement
with those injured in the collision, he said.
   Conrail said it did not concede liability for the accident in
the proposed settlements.
   On Jan. 4, 1987, former Conrail engineer Rick L. Gates missed a
track signal and drove three linked Conrail locomotives into the
path of a 660-passenger Amtrak train traveling an estimated 125 mph.
   The accident, the worst in Amtrak's history, killed 16 people
and injured more than 175.
   Conrail is suing to force Amtrak to cover payments for the
passenger injuries and deaths, contending that a prior agreement
required Amtrak to cover the payments.
   If that suit fails, Conrail will pursue its claims against its
insurers, according to the company.
   Gates, who wasn't injured in the accident, was sentenced earlier
this year in Baltimore County Circuit Court to five years in prison
after pleading guilty to manslaughter. Gates' brakeman at the time
of the crash, Edward Cromwell, was granted immunity from criminal
action after agreeing to help prosecutors.
   Gates, an acknowledged alcoholic, has admitted smoking marijuana
on the train but the court ruled that it could not determine if he
was under the influence of the drug at the time of the accident.
   Gates also faces charges in U.S. District Court in Baltimore for
conspiracy, obstruction of an agency investigation, and lying to
investigators from the National Transportation Safety Board about
drug use.
</TEXT>
