<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PolygamistTrial 2ndLd-Writethru a0765 05-03 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Polygamist Trial, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0765,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys Make Final Arguments In Polygamist Trial</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf to UPDATE that jury deliberations not expected
until sometime Wednesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE SULLIVAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Religious beliefs do not excuse four
polygamist clan members from blame for a church bombing and
standoff with police that they claim were mandated by God, a
prosecutor said Tuesday.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Lambert, in closing arguments
capping the federal trial of the four defendants, admonished jurors
not to ask themselves what they would do if they felt divinely
inspired to break the law.
   ``There is no revelation exception to the laws of the United
States,'' he said.
   Lambert was among a trio of prosecutors wrapping up their cases
against clan matriarch Vickie Singer; her son-in-law, Addam Swapp;
Swapp's brother, Jonathan Swapp; and Mrs. Singer's son, John
Timothy Singer. They are charged in the Jan. 16 bombing of the
Mormon Church's Kamas Stake Center and an ensuing 13-day standoff
at their Marion farm.
   The prosecutors were followed by summations from defense
attorneys. After instructions from U.S. District Judge Bruce
Jenkins, the jury was expected to begin deliberating sometime
Wednesday.
   Clan members have said they believe God ordered the bombing as a
sign of the impending collapse of church, state and nation, and
that he guided them through the siege. The standoff ended in a
shootout that killed state Corrections Lt. Fred House and wounded
Addam Swapp.
   U.S. Attorney Brent Ward said Mrs. Singer, 45, was as much a
part of the bombing as Addam Swapp, who admitted on the witness
stand that he planted the dynamite. He was the only one of the four
defendants to testify.
   While conceding that Mrs. Singer never actually took part in the
bombing, Ward contended that she aided Swapp, making her ``just as
guilty of committing that crime herself.''
   ``They were just waiting for the day. This was the biggest thing
in their lives since John Singer pulled a gun on lawmen several
years ago,'' Ward said.
   The prosecutor's reference to John Singer, the slain polygamist
husband of Mrs. Singer, drew hard stares from his widow. Singer was
gunned down in 1979 at the same farm by lawmen serving arrest
warrants stemming from his refusal to send his children to public
schools.
   However, Mrs. Singer's attorney, Kathyrn Collard, countered that
prosecutors had ``simply no evidence that Vickie Singer committed
any of these crimes that she is accused of.''
   Collard said Mrs. Singer consistently stated that during the
standoff, she would simply pray and ``trust in the Lord.... Hardly
the words of a hardened criminal bent on killing FBI agents.''
   Ward cited Mrs. Singer's telephone statements to an FBI hostage
negotiator and a reporter the day of the bombing. He also referred
to her diary and ``prayer cards'' which asked for a divine blessing
on the 87 sticks of dynamite.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Schwendiman focused on the
attempted murder and assault charges, devoting much of his time to
evidence against John Timothy Singer, 21.
   Schwendiman argued that Singer decided to kill lawmen when he
took aim at the doorway of a nearby building where a six-man FBI
team, House and another dog handler had secretly hidden themselves
the night before.
   Five bullets from Singer's .30-caliber carbine, including the
slug that killed House, were found embedded in the doorway and
walls of the building, Schwendiman said.
   State authorities have said they will file murder charges after
the federal trial is over.
   The federal indictment charged the defendants with maliciously
damaging the church building with an explosive device; use of a
bomb; attempted murder of federal agents; assaulting, resisting and
impeding federal officers; possession of a bomb; possession of a
sawed-off shotgun; and use of a firearm linked to the charges
involving the federal agents.
   Mrs. Singer is charged with all counts, while Addam Swapp faces
all but the shotgun-posession charge. John Timothy Singer and
Jonathan Swapp both are charged with the assault, attempted murder
and firearms violations.
   Charges against two other family members _ who are both
daughters of Mrs. Singer and wives of Addam Swapp _ were dropped.
   In his defense summation, Addam Swapp's attorney, Bill Morrison,
told jurors that his client had expected a violent confrontation
from authorities following the bombing, but he didn't plan one.
   Morrison also said the testimony of FBI agents about the
shootout contained inconsitencies.
</TEXT>
