<DOCNO> AP880503-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1104EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-CaineMutiny Adv06   05-03 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Caine Mutiny, Adv 06,0856</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs, May 6, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Caine Mutiny' Film Inspired by Iran-Contra Hearings</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Altman almost declined to direct the
television version of ``The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial,'' until he
realized how many people were glued to their TV sets every day for
the Iran-Contra hearings.
   ``I thought, if I can do the same thing, maybe they've trained
an audience for me,'' Altman said.
   Trained or not, audiences seeking fine drama will do well to
catch ``The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'' Sunday on CBS. The play is
still riveting, Altman's direction is poetic, and the performances
by his distinguished young cast are superb all the way around.
   Altman, best-known for his feature films (``M-A-S-H,''
``Nashville'') and a veteran of filming stage works (``Streamers,''
``Come Back to the 5 & Dime, Jimmy Dean, Jimmy Dean''), said he at
first had no interest in the project because of the 1954 Edward
Dmytryk film classic ``The Caine Mutiny,'' which starred Humphrey
Bogart as quintessential petty tyrant Capt. Queeg.
   This is not a remake of the movie, but rather the Broadway play
Herman Wouk adapted from his Pulitzer Prize-winning novel. The
movie was based on the entire novel. The play is just the
court-martial, the dramatic core of the book.
   Altman, who co-produced the piece, intentionally cast a younger
Queeg than audiences who remember Bogart will expect, Brad Davis
(``Midnight Express'').
   ``Queeg was 37 years old in that book, and Brad Davis is 38,''
said Altman. ``I tried to bring all those ages down to what was
real.''
   It was a wise move. Davis makes the role his own.
   Eric Bogosian, a New York actor and playwright (``Talk Radio''),
will be new to most viewers, though he's done guest shots on such
network shows as ``Crime Story'' and ``Miami Vice.'' He's excellent
as Lt. Greenwald, the reluctant defense attorney.
   Jeff Daniels plays Lt. Maryk, the not-too-bright young officer
on trial for mutiny for relieving Queeg of command in a typhoon.
   Peter Gallagher (``The Murder of Mary Phagan'') plays Lt. Cmdr.
Challee, the prosecutor who gets more than he bargained for.
   Kevin J. O'Connor has a small but meaty role as Lt. Keefer, the
non-committal witness who turns out to be a pivotal character in
the drama.
   Michael Murphy, who stars in the HBO series Altman is directing,
``Tanner '88,'' plays Capt. Blakely, the judge.
   ``The tragic figure in that case to me was Challee,'' said
Altman. ``He's the guy who felt betrayed.''
   As the court-martial opens, Challee is so sure of his case
against Maryk, he has talked his friend, Greenwald, into serving as
defense attorney. At first Greenwald is contemptuous of his own
client and seems almost negligent in his defense.
   But Greenwald wants to win, and as the court-martial progresses,
he takes his distasteful task to heart, expertly baiting Queeg
until the captain breaks down on the stand before the shocked but
sympathetic court-martial.
   Altman didn't get much of an audience for his first network TV
projects, the Harold Pinter plays ``The Dumbwaiter'' and ``The
Room'' for ABC.
   ``The Caine Mutiny Court-Martial'' is a lot more accessible to a
large audience. As evidenced by viewer interest in the Iran-Contra
and Bork hearings and the success of television shows about
lawyers, there's a natural drama to the courtroom setting.
   Altman enhances Wouk's piece with a unique brand of realism. The
camera roams around the courtroom like an eye, picking up details
here and there, like Queeg's incessant clicking of two steel ball
bearings to calm his nerves. True to the Altman style, characters
talk over each other in asides that can't quite be made out, until
a conversation finally predominates.
   In the first half of the drama, a band practices outside on the
parade field, providing patriotic background music for the
prosecution's case. When the defense takes over the next day, it is
raining.
   In an especially poetic moment, after Queeg has been excused
from the stand, Altman's camera stays on him in a very long shot as
he leaves the far end of the building, a lost and broken man.
   ``I think at the end after it's all over there'll be a lot of
that, `What was that? Who's the bad guy?' That's what I want,''
said Altman, who seems to have already gotten the only review he
needs:
   ``I got a nice letter from Herman Wouk who said it was the first
time any of his work had ever been translated even close to his
satisfaction,'' Altman said. ``I have it in my jacket.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   CALLING DR. SPELLING _ Aaron Spelling Productions, having
discovered a whole new world in medical shows, is in production on
another one, for NBC, ``Nightingales,'' about a group of student
nurses. ``Heartbeat,'' a spring replacement on ABC, was set in a
women's clinic. ``Nightingales'' is Spelling's first project for
NBC.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, May 6</NOTE>
