<1ST_LINE>a i AM-South-WestAfricaAdv10     05-03 0775</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South-West Africa Adv 10,0793</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, May 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Many in Namibia Wary of South Africa's Motives</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINDHOEK, South-West Africa (AP) _ In a far-off garrison town,
blacks complain of abuse and atrocities by South African soldiers
based there. Here in Windhoek white secretaries take memos from
black Cabinet members and pour their tea.
   Officially, South Africa's vision of South-West Africa's future
reflects the hilltop harmony of Windhoek, the territory's capital,
rather than the garrison town, Oshakati, near wartorn Angola to the
north.
   But many South-West Africans, moderates as well as militants,
are deeply suspicious of South Africa's intentions toward Africa's
last colony, also known as Namibia.
   These suspicions were heightened in early April when President
P.W. Botha of South Africa came for a visit and proposed new powers
for his chief representative in the territory. The proposal was
seen as weakening the ``transitional'' government installed by
South Africa in 1985 to lay the groundwork for independence.
   Moderates who hold a majority on the coalition Cabinet accused
Botha of undermining their efforts to gain credibility as an
alternative to the pro-independence guerrillas of the South-West
African People's Organization, SWAPO.
   ``Actions like this won't help force SWAPO to the bargaining
table,'' said the Cabinet's chairman, Moses Katjiuongua, a black,
who has threatened to quit. ``We're trying to get people to talk to
us, but you don't talk to people who don't have power.''
   SWAPO, meanwhile, carries on in its 22-year-old bush war for
independence despite heavy losses and South Africa's overwhelming
military advantage. Guerrilla leaders and many others are skeptical
of South Africa's professed willingness to allow United
Nations-supervised independence elections in the territory upon the
withdrawal of Cuban troops helping fight a pro-Western faction in
neighboring Angola.
   The United Nations, which formally recognizes the name Namibia,
has designated SWAPO as the ``sole and authentic'' representative
of the South-West African people, atlhough more than 40 political
parties operate in the territory. By all accounts, SWAPO would be
the likely winner in a U.N.-run election because of its strong
support in the Ovambo region around Oshakati, where about half the
territory's 1.3 million people live.
   But widespread doubts persist that South Africa would agree to
elections in which the Marxist-oriented SWAPO leaders had the edge.
   On at least one major issue, South-West Africa's moderates and
militants share common ground. Both want an end to apartheid-style
laws that create ethnically based political structures and enable
the 78,000 whites to maintain segregated schools and hospitals.
   Botha, although hinting at some flexibility on the issue, has
made it clear he wants to protect the ``group rights'' of whites.
   The president's chief representative in the territory,
Administrator-General Louis Pienaar, says whites should have the
option of joining a non-racial system or maintaining a segregated
administration to finance and run their own affairs.
   ``The whites are only 6 percent of the population, but they
manage the infrastructure and the economy,'' Pienaar maintained.
``They can't be written off because of their small numbers.''
   This attitude irks white moderates such as Dirk Mudge, the
minister of finance and government affairs, who opposes ethnic
politics and holds that whites don't need discriminatory laws to
preserve their culture.
   But conservative whites are pressing Botha to maintain some type
of political apartheid, and the increasingly powerful far-right in
South Africa is likely to create an uproar if non-racialism becomes
law in the territory.
   ``It's discrimination that makes so many people hostile to South
Africa,'' said Katjiuongua, the Cabinet chairman. ``I want to be a
national leader, not an ethnic leader.''
   As big as France and Italy combined, mineral-rich South-West
Africa has been administered by South Africa since the end of World
War I, under a League of Nations mandate. In the early 1970s the
United Nations formally declared it a territory illegally occupied
by South Africa and has called repeatedly for independence
elections that would include SWAPO.
   The new powers extended to Administrator-General Pienaar
authorize him to act against news media and organizations deemed to
be ``subversive,'' but for now a relatively high degree of
political freedom exists. SWAPO is allowed to function as a
political organization, and a pro-SWAPO weekly newspaper, The
Namibian, regularly reports on alleged atrocities by the security
forces in Ovambo.
   During Botha's visit, SWAPO supporters demonstrated in downtown
Windhoek, displaying placards with slogans such as ``Botha: Stop
Sucking Our Blood.'' The police kept a low profile.
   Not everyone blames South Africa for the many divisions within
South-West Africa, but the widespread sentiment is that
heavy-handed moves by Botha's government won't improve the
situation.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, May 10</NOTE>
