<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surge in imports caused Japan's merchandise trade
surplus to fall 7.2 percent to $94.3 billion in the 1987 fiscal
year, the Finance Ministry has announced.
   Monday's report confirmed the continuing strength of Japan's
economy in spite of the strong Japanese yen, which hurts the
competitiveness of Japanese products in domestic and overseas
markets.
   Exports grew 10.5 percet to $233.4 billion, but imports grew
even faster, rising 26.9 percent to $139.1 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's second-largest bank says it is seeking
to acquire a majority stake in Irving Bank Corp., but analysts say
that swaying shareholders away from Bank of New York Co.'s
competing hostile bid remains an uphill battle.
   Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, which had sought a 45 percent
stake in Irving, said Monday it would seek to purchase 9.5 million
Irving shares, or about 51 percent of the New York-based bank, for
$75 a share.
   Bank of New York is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 shares of its
stock for each of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers and Chrysler
Corp. moved closer to a national contract settlement after wrapping
up all but final details of related agreements covering former
American Motors Corp. workers in Wisconsin, UAW Vice President Marc
Stepp said.
   ``It means now we can turn our full attention to the national
talks. They're going very well,'' Stepp said Monday, adding that
since last week, Chrysler management's ``attitude has changed for
the positive.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As part of its inflation-fighting program,
Mexico will hold the peso at its current value against the U.S.
dollar until the end of the year, says Treasury Secretary Gustavo
Petricioli said.
   Petricioli told local reporters that economic conditions permit
the government to continue a freeze on the exchange rate that has
been in effect since March. His remarks were reported in Monday's
newspapers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Postal executives will be introduced this week
to a new breed of postal clerk that may never smile, but which also
never frowns or gets cranky or takes a break when there's a line
waiting.
   It's the new face of postal technology _ automated postal clerks
_ and they will begin ``greeting'' the American public later this
summer.
   One of the clerks, Infopost, answers customer questions. The
other, Autopost, weighs mail, takes money, makes change and sells
postage.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   On Wall Street Monday, blue-chip issues staged a modest rally
but the rest of the stock market lagged in a sluggish session. The
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.94 to 2,043.27.
   The dollar was mixed against major currencies. Bond prices fell.
   Precious metals futures prices plunged along with those for
crude oil and refined oil products following the failure of OPEC
oil ministers to agree on production cuts. Grain and soybean
futures were mixed; cattle and livestock were mostly higher and
stock-index futures advanced.
</TEXT>
