<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     05-03 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slide In Reaction to OPEC News</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices have turned sharply lower in
response to OPEC's failure to set temporary production cuts in four
days of negotiations.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the June contract for West
Texas Intermediate oil, the U.S. benchmark crude, slid to $17.14
per barrel on Monday, down 85 cents from Friday's close.
   Most of the ground was lost early in the day as traders reacted
to the news that the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
had suspended talks over proposals to cut its output in conjunction
witheindependent producers.
   Prices stabilized temporarily in the afternoon, then slipped
again in a late spurt of nervous selling.
   Prices for refined products also tumbled. Wholesale prices for
unleaded gasoline fell 2.24 cents per gallon to 49.37 cents, while
heating oil dropped 2.42 cents to 45.95 per gallon.
   OPEC ministers broke off their talks with several outside oil
producers after Saudi Arabia scuttled a plan for cutting production
temporarily.
   Analysts said the suspension of the talks and the Saudis'
reluctance to agree to the cuts caused a violent shift of sentiment
in the futures markets, where prices had recently advanced on the
expectation of a global move to reduce production.
</TEXT>
