<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     05-03 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on Short-Term T-Bills Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities shot up in the government's latest auction with rates on
three-month bills climbing to the highest level since the October
stock market collapse.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.13 percent on Monday, up from 5.92
percent last week. Another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.41 percent, up from 6.28 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since three-month bills averaged 6.84
percent on Oct. 19, the day of the stock market collapse, and
six-month bills averaged 6.48 percent on Dec. 21.
   Concerns raised by rising interest rates have been cited as one
of the factors contributing to the stock market collapse last fall.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 6.31 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,845.00 and 6.72 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,675.90.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 7.07 percent last week
from 7.03 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
