<1ST_LINE>r f PM-NBC-Cable Bjt   05-03 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NBC-Cable, Bjt,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NBC Agrees to Buy Cable Channel, Launch Two New Cable Services</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   National Broadcasting Co., which operates the
nation's top-rated television network, plans a major cable
television venture featuring original business and sports
programming.
   The move marks the network's biggest step yet into the cable
industry, which it long has eyed as a potential way to complement
its over-the-air broadcasting.
   The General Electric Co. subsidiary said Monday it had signed a
letter of intent to buy a cable television newtork, Tempo
Television, and hoped to have new business and sports programming
on it later this year or early in 1989.
   Terms of the deal were not disclosed.
   ``We believe this is an important step in our efforts to broaden
NBC's business base,'' said NBC President Robert Wright, who for
some time has been looking to get the company into cable.
   Tempo, which is based in Tulsa, Okla., and has about 12 million
subscribers, is being acquired by Tele-Communications Inc., the
Denver area-based company that is the nation's biggest cable
television operator.
   A statement issued by NBC said that in addition to giving up its
prospective interest in Tempo, Tele-Communications had agreed to
offer the new programming services on its own cable systems and on
affiliates that serve 8 million cable subscribers.
   John Malone, president of Tele-Communications, said, ``We feel
NBC's proposed services will be very appealing options for the
cable viewer and believe the rest of the cable industry will be
enthusiastic about this opportunity.''
   The announcement said NBC, Tempo and Tele-Communications hoped
to sign final agreements by the end of May. In the meantime, NBC
said, it would discuss affilation agreements for the new programs
with other cable operators.
   NBC's Wright frequently has expressed an interest in getting the
company into cable television since GE acquired NBC in 1986.
   NBC began talks last fall about buying a stake in Turner
Broadcasting System Inc. but those negotiations were suspended in
January. More recently, NBC said it had informally discussed with
Turner and other cable operators the possibility of selling
broadcast rights to some events in the Summer Olympics. NBC owns
the rights to broadcast the games.
   NBC also recently announced it had agreed to produce a new
comedy to be aired on the Disney cable channel.
   This would not be the first corporate link between an
over-the-air broadcast network and a cable service. Capital
Cities-ABC Inc., which owns the ABC Television network, also owns
80 percent of the ESPN cable network.
   Tempo Television provides programming aimed mainly at viewers
over age 45 in four categories _ entertainment, travel,
sports-outdoors and how-to information.
   NBC's plans call for it to replace that programming with
business and financial news on weekdays and sports programming in
the evening and on weekends, according to spokesman Joe Rutledge.
   The business news and financial information service would
present consumer-oriented features and information dealing with the
market, business trends and the economy, the announcement said.
   The sports-programming service would include live and taped
coverage of sports events, interviews with sports figures,
sports-oriented talk shows and magazine-format sports shows.
   Both services would rely on existing NBC operations, but would
be distinct from NBC Television network programming, Rutledge said.
   Wright said the venture ``promises to strengthen NBC, thereby
preserving our long-term ability to provide first-class programming
to our over-the-air broadcast audience.''
</TEXT>
