<1ST_LINE>u f PM-USG-DesertPartners Bjt   05-03 0676</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-USG-Desert Partners, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USG Offers Recap As Alternative to Desert Partners Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. would take on $2.2 billion in new debt
under a defensive recapitalization and business restructuring plan
it has proposed to counter an unwanted $2.32 billion buyout offer
by the investment group Desert Partners L.P.
   Under its plan, USG would borrow $2.2 billion to pay its
shareholders $37 in cash, debentures with a face value of $5 and a
share of stock in the recapitalized corporation for each of their
51.5 million common shares, company officials said Monday.
   USG, a Chicago-based manufacturer of building products, also
said it would raise money to pay off the debt by selling its
Masonite Corp. and Kinkead businesses and focusing operations on
its core building products businesses.
   The plan will be submitted June 24 to a vote of shareholders,
who also will be asked to rollover certain USG shares held in
company employee benefit plans into new shares of common stock, the
company said.
   As expected, Desert Partners' reaction was negative.
   ``From what we have seen, USG's proposal appears to be highly
conditional and does not have financing in place. We note that USG
proposes to move shares into an employee plan,'' said Desert
Partners' spokesman Tom Davies.
   ``It's not clear, however, what are the implications of that
move with respect to control of the company. We believe that the
USG shareholders might prefer contrary to USG's recap, our fully
financed $45 per share proposal,'' Davies said in a telephone
interview Monday night.
   Earlier Monday, Desert Partners had tried to lure USG to the
bargaining table by offering to increase its bid for the
Chicago-based manufacturer to $2.32 billion if the two sides can
reach a friendly deal.
   Desert Partners, a partnership headed by two Texas oilmen, said
in a statement that it was willing to pay $45 for each of 39
million USG shares if the USG's management agreed to support the
offer.
   The remaining 12.5 million shares would be acquired for
subordinated discount debentures carrying a market value of $45
each, giving the deal a total value of about $2.32 billion.
   The partnership, led by oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E.
Brown, previously offered $42 a share in a hostile tender offer.
That bid, including debt securities and warrants valued at $42
each, has a value of about $2.2 billion and remains in effect.
   Desert Partners owns about 9.9 percent of USG's shares and said
that as of Friday, about 19.3 million shares, or 37.5 percent, had
been tendered under its $42-a-share offer.
   Analysts said that Desert Partners' latest proposal was rather
conservative and that a bid of $50 a share would far more
attractive to USG, a manufacturer of paper, plaster and wood
products. In takeover overtures last year, Desert Partners
indicated it was willing to pay $50 a share for the company.
   On composite trading on the New York Stock Exchange, USG rose 50
cents to close at $41.50 a share Monday.
   In proposing a friendly resolution, Desert Partners' chief
financial officer, Joel L. Reed, said that ``all aspects of our
proposal, including price, are negotiable.''
   Among the big bargaining chips USG executives control is the
company's ``poison-pill'' defense, which is designed to hinder an
unwanted takeover. Last week a federal judge in Chicago denied a
request from Desert Partners to prevent USG from using the defense
measure. Desert Partners said it intended to appeal the ruling.
   ``The poison pill is a way for management to negotiate,'' said
Lawrence Horan, a vice president at the investment firm Smith
Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   ``What (Desert Partners) is trying to do is get USG management
to negotiate, not to sit there and say the company's not up for
sale,'' he added.
   The standoff appears headed for a showdown at USG's annual
meeting May 11. Desert Partners has nominated a slate of six
candidates to USG's 15-member board.
   ``We believe the stockholders will demonstrate their support of
good-faith negotiations by voting for the Desert Partners director
candidates,'' Reed said.
</TEXT>
