<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Benedictine-RemyMartin     05-03 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Benedictine-Remy Martin,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Remy Martin Drops Out Of Bidding For Benedictine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E. Remy Martin and Compagnie announced that it has
decided to drop its hostile bid for control of the liqueur and
luxury products group Benedictine SA in the face of a higher offer
from SAF Martini and Rossi.
   ``After studying the profitability aspects of a higher bid, we
have decided to drop out of the running,'' a Remy Martin
spokeswoman said Tuesday. ``That leaves Martini and Rossi as the
sole bidder, and we wish them luck.''
   Remy Martin's decision to give up the bidding came as little
surprise to Paris stock analysts, who had suggested that the French
cognac group's heavy debt burden was likely to prevent it from
winning a bidding war with the Swiss-based Martini and Rossi.
   Under French stock market rules, Remy Martin's wholly owned
subsidiary Remy and Associes unit would have had to offer at least
five percent more per share than Martini and Rossi's bid of 7,700
francs, or $1,350, to stay in the running.
   That would have worked out to 8,085 francs, or $1,418 dollars,
per share, and would have put the minimum cost of a sweetened Remy
Martin offer at 1.132 billion francs, or $199 million, on the basis
of Benedictine's current capital.
   And if Benedictine carried out a defensive capital boost it had
planned to make to friendly institutions, it would have worked out
to 1.199 billion francs, or $210 million.
   Benedictine's product range includes peppermint and
herbal-flavored liqueurs and anise-flavored apperitifs. The company
also has perfume and watch operations.
</TEXT>
