<HEAD>Gillete Shareholders Reject Effort to Replace Directors</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Coniston, Gillette comments</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. shareholders have rejected a New
York-based investor group's bid to replace four company directors
and seek to sell the personal care giant, the company reported
today.
   A preliminary count of about 87 million shares voting in the
proxy election indicate the four Gillette directors received 52
percent support to 48 percent backing the Coniston Group's slate
for the three-year terms, Gillette said.
   Coniston said it would request a recount.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Gillete fell $2.25 a
share to $39 after the announcement.
   Coniston launched a proxy battle in February, pledging that if
its candidates were elected to the board, it would try to convince
the other eight directors to sell Boston-based Gillette.
   The proxy ballots were submitted during Gillette's April 21
annual meeting and were counted by Delaware-based Corporation Trust
Co.
   Coniston, which controls 6.76 million shares, about 5.8 percent
of the 115.5 million shares outstanding, plans to call for an
immediate recount of the ballots, said Coniston principal Augustus
K. Oliver, one of the four Coniston candidates.
   Oliver said the group's projections were higher than 48 percent.
   ``We submitted a lot more votes than we seem to be getting
credit for,'' said Oliver. ``It puzzles us, and we'll try to figure
out exactly how many people were on our side.''
   In addition to Oliver, other Coniston candidates included
Coniston principals Paul E. Tierney Jr. and Keith R. Gollust and
former cable television executive David Strassler.
   In 1986, Gillette headed off several takeover attempts by Revlon
Group Inc. by signing a 10-year pact and buying back Revlon's
shares for nearly $580 million.
   ``We are very pleased that the results of the preliminary count
indicate majority support for the Gillette directors' platform to
maximize stockholder value by continuing the company's plan to
generate sustainable profitable growth above industry averages,''
said Gillette Chairman and Chief Executive Colman M. Mockler Jr. in
a prepared statement released today.
   Mockler was among the four challenged directors. The others are
Lawrence E. Fouraker, Herbert H. Jacobi and Joseph F. Turley.
   Gillette spokeswoman Joan Fitzgerald said the proxy ballot
announcement should have no affect on ongoing litigation filed by
Gillette and Coniston last month in U.S. District Court.
   A pre-trial hearing is scheduled Wednesday on the suits before
Judge Rya Zobel, who previously refused to issue a temporary
restraining order to block Coniston's proxy slate.
   Gillette claims Coniston failed to fully disclose all its
financial backers. In a countersuit, Coniston charged Gillette
issued false and misleading information about Coniston to
shareholders.
   Oliver said Coniston may request a new director election as part
of the ``equitable relief'' sought in the countersuit.
</TEXT>
