<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-Futures     05-03 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Futures,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China to Start Futures Markets This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China plans to open up to five futures markets in
the southern city of Canton later this year, becoming the first
socialist country to take such a step, according to a report
published Tuesday.
   The English-language China Daily quoted unnamed sources as
saying preparations were under way to set up three to five pilot
markets in Canton, one of China's most important business centers.
   Chinese leaders hope the markets will stabilize the economy and
prevent drastic price increases that have become a main complaint
of Chinese citizens, the newspaper said.
   A futures market allows traders and producers to negotiate a set
price for what they think a commodity will be worth at a future
date. The producer is guaranteed that price regardless of
subsequent fluctuations in the market.
   The report said officials from the cities of Beijing and Wuhan
and the provinces of Guangdong, Henan, Jilin and Hunan met in
mid-April to discuss plans for the futures markets, but did not say
what commodities would be traded.
   This is the latest development in China's decade-long economic
reform that has increasingly turned to capitalistic practices in
its attempt to strengthen and enliven the economy.
   The official Economic Daily earlier this year described how a
futures market would solve the problem of gluts and shortages,
which often are the result of farmers' inability to forecast the
market.
   Both papers acknowledged that China's backward communications
and transport systems will be a problem, but the China Daily said,
``... The country cannot wait until everything is ready before
carrying out the plans.''
   The paper said Chinese leaders want to learn from the experience
of foreign countries in futures markets and that experts from Hong
Kong will be consulted.
   It said no decision has been made yet on whether foreigners will
be allowed to trade in the markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
