<1ST_LINE>u f PM-URW-Goodyear     05-03 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-URW-Goodyear,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Goodyear Workers Reject Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Goodyear Tire & Rubber Co. is waiting for the
United Rubber Workers union to set the next course of action, now
that a proposed three-year contract for 15,000 union employees at
Goodyear plants in the United States has been defeated, a Goodyear
spokesman said today.
   ``Lacking a ratification, we agree with the union on working on
a day-to-day basis,'' John Perduyn said.
   URW spokesman Curt Brown said Monday night that the vote against
the agreement by the union's largest branch, Local 12 in Gadsden,
Ala., was pivotal. The local, which has 2,900 members, voted 1,764
to 348 Monday against ratification.
   Six of the URW's 11 Goodyear locals approved the proposed deal,
but a majority of the membership of all 11 locals was opposed to it.
   Local 2 in Akron approved the agreement Sunday by a 3-to-1 ratio.
   Brown did not reveal the final vote total among all 11 locals.
   The tentative agreement was reached in Cincinnati on April 21 at
2 a.m., two hours after the old contract had expired.
   Brown said he has heard that some locals were upset that the
agreement did not contain a wage increase, although it included
improved benefit and job security provisions.
   Brown said URW President Milan Stone will contact the Goodyear
section of the union's international policy committee and ask to
convene a meeting in Akron, probably on Friday, to determine the
URW's next step.
   ``We are not planning on a strike at this time,'' Brown said. He
said the policy committee may ``ask the company to come back in for
a meeting. ... We will work day-to-day while we chart a new
course.''
   In addition to the local in Gadsden, other locals voting against
the contract offer are in Union City, Tenn.; Danville, Md.;
Madisonville, Ky.; and Marysville, Ohio.
   Locals voting with Akron in favor of the contract are in
Lincoln, Neb.; Topeka, Kan.; Sun Prairie, Wis.; New Bedford, Mass.;
and St. Marys, Ohio.
</TEXT>
