<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1221EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-LatinDebtSwaps Adv07-08   05-03 0979</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Latin Debt Swaps, Adv 07-08,1003</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Equity Swaps Possible Way to Reduce Huge Latin Debt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto RIO1 of May 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It looked like the movie ``Wall
Street.'' Brokers wearing yellow ``yuppie'' ties, waving I.D. tags
and shouting into walkie-talkies, jostled one another to make bids
on the floor of the Rio Stock Exchange.
   But the object of the bidding was not stocks, bonds, commodities
or precious metals. It was part of Brazil's mountainous foreign
debt of $121 billion.
   Thoughout Latin America, which as a whole owes the rest of the
world $410 billion and has been unable to pay it back, so-called
``debt-for-equity swaps'' are being tried as a way to break the
impasse.
   Not everyone is enthusiastic about the idea, which involves
trading big debts for generally smaller amounts of equity in local
enterprises.
   Some countries say the swaps cause inflation and lead to
``foreign domination'' of their economies. Some major creditor
banks, mostly U.S. ones, which sank billions into Latin loans, say
the swaps force them to cancel their debt at too hefty a discount.
   On the other hand, many small banks _ in Europe, Japan, the
Middle East and American cities such as Cleveland, Pittsburgh and
Dallas _ see the swaps as a way to salvage at least some of the
money they sunk into the region in the 1970s.
   ``Swaps will never be a total solution to the debt crisis. But
they certainly are a step in the right direction,'' said Maarten L.
Pronk, the Rio representative of Holland's NMB Bank, currently the
world's No. 1 middleman in debt-for-equity trades. ``There are
pluses and minuses on both sides, but the overall result is very
interesting.''
   In Brazil, which has just begun monthly debt auctions, equity
trades could reduce the country's foreign debt by as much as $4
billion this year, officials estimate.
   In a typical transaction, a company hoping to start or expand a
Brazilian business purchases a certain amount of the country's debt
from a creditor bankat a steep discount and then brings that debt
to market to bid against other companies on a repayment plan from
the central bank of Brazil.
   Successful bidders _ the ones who accept the biggest discounts
from the central bank _ get repaid in local currency, which is to
be invested in their local enterprises. The benefit to the
companies comes in the difference between what they paid for the
debt and what the central bank agrees to repay them. For example, a
company might purchase debt at 50 cents on the dollar and then win
a bid of 70 cents on the dollar from the central bank in the
auction.
   The government regulates the auctions, screens the types of
projects to be funded and sets quotas on the amount of debt it will
repay. While the process helps ease the national debt burden, the
regulations are designed to control the inflationary effects of the
swaps, which infuse the economy with fresh capital and increase the
money in circulation.
   Brazil, like most other countries, also protects its end of the
deal by requiring investors to keep their assets in the country for
a period of years.
   ``The Rio debt auction was a complete success,'' Sergio
Barcellos, the president of the Rio stock exchange, said in an
interview.
   Another aggressive debt swapper is Chile, which still owes an
estimated $21.7 billion but has traded off $3 billion worth.
   Thanks to such deals, U.S., Australian, New Zealand and Middle
Eastern private interests have bought into Chilean mining
companies, private pension funds, fruit-growing firms and fishing
companies.
   Some critics complain that encouraging foreign interests to swap
debt for equity could lead to a ``denationalization'' of the Latin
American economy. But in Chile, the authoritarian regime of
President Gen. Augusto Pinochet says the swaps will continue,
especially since the country is writing off debt at the rate of 59
to 61 cents on the dollar.
   Mexico, the No. 2 Third World debtor owing $105 billion, swapped
some $2 billion of debt for local assets but stopped the program
last year when the inflation rate hit a record 159.2 percent.
   Under the Mexican swaps, made at a discount of around 30
percent, Nissan Motor Co., Ford Motor Co., Chrysler Corp.,
Volkswagen, American Express and Club Med acquired or increased
holdings in the country.
   Argentina, third among Latin debtors with $55 billion owed, this
year held two debt-for-equity auctions and authorized 15 specific
debt-swap deals. In these projects, $241 million worth of debt is
to be canceled in exchange for $139 million worth of ownership in
two breweries, a soft drink bottling plant, a beer bottling
company, an auto parts firm and a manufacturer of insulin.
   But Juan Ciminari, the secretary of industry and foreign trade,
echoed Mexico's worries about inflation. With Argentina's inflation
rate running over 200 percent a year, the swap program could get
tripped up, he said.
   Small, poor Bolivia has succeeded in reducing its $900 million
debt to foreign banks by swapping part of it for local assets _ at
the bargain-basement rate of 11 cents on the dollar. But there is
controversy, because of fear foreigners will gain control of
traditionally state-run companies.
   Venezuela has gone timidly into debt swaps. Uruguay says it
intends to start them. Colombia and Paraguay haven't shown much
interest in such operations, while Peru, which has openly refused
to repay most of its $16.7 billion debt, doesn't consider swaps at
all.
   Also generally in the anti-swap camp are the giant U.S. banks
that tied up billions of dollars in Latin American loans. Citibank,
Chase Manhattan, Morgan Guaranty Trust and Manufacturers Hanover
are, in principle, against huge discounts on the money owed to them.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1222EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-FarmEquipment Adv07-08   05-03 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Farm Equipment, Adv 07-08,0900</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 07</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions May 7-8 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Improved Farm Outlook Helps Revive Equipment Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BATES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers around the country are out kicking
the tires on new tractors again, and equipment sales are rebounding
from post-Depression lows so quickly many manufacturers are having
trouble keeping up.
   ``The situation has changed dramatically,'' said Dick
Unverferth, president of Unverferth Manufacturing, a Kalida, Ohio,
company that makes tillage and grain-handling equipment and special
farm vehicle wheels.
   ``It went from a pretty sick apple to one where we're on
overtime and have been on overtime for quite a while,'' said
Unverferth, who heads the Farm Equipment Manufacturers Association,
a 330-member trade group of small manufacturers.
   While manufacturers anticipated an upswing with an improved farm
economy, most misjudged its size and momentum.
   ``I never thought things would turn around to this magnitude
this quickly,'' said Bud Fleischer, who runs a Columbus, Neb.,
company that makes tillage and planting equipment.
   ``I thought it would be a gradual turnaround, something you
could adjust to,'' he said. ``We went from moderate production to
extremely heavy production.
   ``Unless something happens to change things drastically in the
next six weeks, this could be a record year in sales for this
company,'' Fleischer said.
   The sales spurt has left farmers waiting months for new tractors
and equipment as manufacturers attempt to fill an unexpected
backlog of orders.
   Steel has become a precious metal because of the manufacturing
push. Prices are up 20 percent to 45 percent for some tubing and
steel bars that are in short supply. Machinery makers also report
problems getting bearings.
   In addition to farmer income, factors propelling the surge
include a nearly depleted inventory of good used equipment, better
commodity prices, stronger export sales of grain and a continuing
moderation of interest expenses and costs for fuel, fertilizer and
other materials.
   Farm Equipment and Industrial Institute monthly sales surveys
show a strong recovery. In March, manufacturers sold 9,876 tractors
compared with 7,712 the same month a year earlier. For the first
quarter of this year, 22,986 tractors have been sold compared with
18,061 in the same period a year ago.
   Sales of combines and hay and forage equipment also are up
sharply in the first quarter.
   After record or near-record sales in the late 1970s as farmers
expanded their operations, equipment manufacturers and dealers were
hit hard when the farm recession began. During the early 1980s,
many farmers quit buying new equipment and either made used
equipment purchases or just tried to get by with additional
maintenance or repair.
   Dozens of little companies that made specialized machinery
folded or scrambled to get into other product areas.
   Even the big manufacturers were hard hit. A hallowed name in
agricultural equipment for decades, International Harvester Co.,
sold its farm machinery division to J.I. Case in 1984 so it could
concentrate on making more profitable heavy trucks.
   At Deere & Co., the No. 1 ag equipment maker in the United
States, farm machinery sales peaked in 1981. When they began
declining, company profits followed. In fiscal 1986, Deere lost
$229 million, its first loss since the Great Depression.
   As the slump bottomed out, sales and manufacturing capacity
dipped to around 50 percent of previous levels, said James
Ebbinghaus, vice president of the Farm and Industrial Equipment
Institute. The institute represents large manufacturers who provide
more than 90 percent of all the farm equipment and machinery made
nationwide.
   ``About a year ago things started to turn around,'' Ebbinghaus
said. ``Sales stopped their decline and leveled off or started back
up.''
   He said by the end of 1987, early-year losses had been recouped
and the industry stood about even with its position at the end of
1986.
   U.S. Department of Agriculture economists are predicting a
modest increase in sales during 1988.
   ``The big news is there isn't expected to be a decline for the
first time in several years,'' said Stan Daberkow, a USDA Economic
Research Service economist.
   Preliminary USDA statistics show 1987 was the eighth consecutive
year of declining farm equipment expenditures. But when final
figures are released in July, they are expected to show a less
severe decrease than in previous years, Daberkow said.
   He and other ag economists say the improvement in net farm cash
income _ the difference between gross income and expenses _ finally
is affecting equipment sales. For two years or more, farmers who
saw their incomes improve have used the money to pay off debts,
most economists agree.
   The outlook of many farmers began changing about eight months
ago, according to economists and other equipment industry analysts.
   ``It's as positive now as it's been in a long period of time,''
Ebbinghaus said.
   Deere & Co. broke a string of five straight quarterly losses in
the second quarter of fiscal 1987. The company hasn't had a losing
quarter since and it has been calling back laid-off workers.
   ``We expect the recovery to continue,'' said Deere spokesman
Brian Alm. ``We have what we call `cautious optimism.' We've been
through so much for so long we almost don't want to get too excited
too soon.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions May 7-8</NOTE>
</DOC>
