noon on Wall Street.
   Advancers outnumbered decliners by roughly 3 to 2 in the overall
tally of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 763 issues
higher, 529 lower and 523 unchanged.
   Big Board volume totaled 101.66 million shares at mid-day.
   Much of the session's early activity centered on heavy trading
in American Electric Power, which goes ex-dividend today. The stock
led the Big Board's most-active list, rising \ to 27].
   ``Without that, volume would be extraordinarily low,'' noted
Michael Metz, vice president and technical analyst at Oppenheimer &
Co.
   Trading volume also was sluggish because of a delay the opening
of the futures pits in Chicago, where the futures on the Standard &
Poor's 500 index are traded.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange halted activity for more than
two and a half hours after a water main flooded the basement and
disrupted telephone contact with the outside world.
   ``That's kept all the program trading out of the market,'' said
Peter Vandenberg, a trader at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. ``All the
people who read off the spread between index futures and the cash
market haven't been a factor.''
   Some analysts welcomed the respite. On Wall Street, ``it's a
refreshing case of a stock market rather than a casino,'' Metz said.
