graf pvs, The flood ...
^Broken Water Main Forces Halt to Merc Trading</NOTE>
<HEAD>ddfonesltddfonprlt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading halted for more than 2{ hours today on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange after a sprinkler system flooded
the exchange's telecommunications room, disabling its automated
price quotation system, officials said.
   Exchange officials called the halt at 8:05 a.m. CDT., 45 minutes
after the opening of trading in foreign currency and Treasury bill
futures. Trading resumed at 10:45 a.m. CDT.
   Trading in stock-index and agricultural futures had not yet
opened when the halt was called.
   Officials did not know the cause of sprinkler system's
malfunction. The telecommunications room is located on the second
floor of the exchange building, just below the trading floor.
   ``It's back in service,'' said Andrew Yemma, an exchange
spokesman. ``We don't know what caused it but it leaked a whole lot
of water.''
   The flood affected the exchange's high-speed telephone lines,
which carry price quotes to subscribers of market-information
services around the world.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange is the major market for Standard
& Poor's 500 stock-index futures, the most popular contract of its
type.
   The exchange is also the nation's biggest market for cattle and
pork futures.
</TEXT>
