<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting a variety of weather
information, analysts said.
   Beneficial rain fell overnight in Missouri, Nebraska and extreme
southwestern Iowa, and was headed today for central and southern
Illinois. The improvement in growing conditions lent a weaker tone
to corn futures.
   But longer-range forecasts predicted dryness and below-normal
temperatures in the east, and moisture and above-normal
temperatures in the west.
   ``It's indecisive at this point,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a
trader with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. ``Generally, rain is needed
in the east. They've been having some moisture in the west.''
   The long-term outlook for grain and soybean prices remained
bullish, however, Lespinasse said.
   ``I think we're going to gyrate back and forth and consolidate
the recent big gains before ultimately moving higher,'' he said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 4\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.02 a bushel; corn was \ cent to
} cent lower with May at $2.04} a bushel; oats were 1} cents to 2{
cents higher with May at $1.61 a bushel; soybeans were { cent lower
to 2 cents higher with May at $6.89 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange after opening about 2{ hours late due to
flooding in the exchange's telcommunications room.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .40 cent higher with June at 71.05
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .30 cent higher with
May at 79 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .20 cent
higher with June at 49.30 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.02 cent to .10 cent lower with May at 51.90 cents a pound.
   Feeder cattle settled mostly lower Monday. Other livestock and
meat futures settled mostly higher.
</TEXT>
