<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1258EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-NYSEProgramRule     05-03 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-NYSE Program Rule,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Exchange Requires Reports on Program Trades</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Stock Exchange on Tuesday began
requiring members to submit daily reports of their program trades,
a move designed to help the exchange analyze market volatility.
   Under the new rule, NYSE members and member firms must submit a
log of program trades made for customers or for their own accounts,
including trades executed in other markets, by the close of the
second business day following the trades, the exchange said in a
statement.
   Members are not required, however, to identify customers for
whom program trades were executed.
   Program trading has been blamed for much of the market
volatility at the time of the October stock market crash. The
submission of daily data will ``enable the NYSE to more routinely
monitor and analyze program trading activity.''
   Analysts were not surprised by the new rule, which had been
announced previously.
   ``It's going to require more forms, more paperwork, more time,
and it's going to cost money,'' noted Perrin Long, an analyst at
Lipper Analytical Services.
   But many said they support the move. ``It's a good idea because
a lot of movement in the market is attributed to program trading
that isn't,'' said Robert Gordon, president of Twenty First
Securities Corp. He hopes the rule will dispell some concern over
program trading activity.
   Analysts agree a separate possibility under consideration that
would require members to identify within 48 hours all customers for
whom any business was conducted has far more serious implications.
   ``That proposal will come up against a great deal of
resistance,'' Long said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880503-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Texas-OPEC     05-03 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas-OPEC,0599</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Oil Regulator Wants To Keep OPEC Contacts Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL HOLMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kent Hance, one of Texas' three oil
regulators, says the state benefited from his attendance at last
week's OPEC meeting, and he plans to keep those contacts open
despite the criticism the trip drew.
   ``We're not trying to join OPEC, and we're not always going to
agree with them,'' said Kent Hance, who sits on the three-member
Texas Railroad Commission. ``But when President Reagan tried to get
nuclear arms stability, he had to deal with the Russians, who are
our enemies.''
   Hance did not participate in meetings held by the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries, but rather visited with some
individual oil ministers during his stay in Vienna, Austria.
   ``The critical thing is _ we're living in a world where someone
else sets the price for our commodity. We have to have input,'' he
said in an interview Monday.
   Not everyone agreed. One group called Monday for Hance to be
prosecuted on charges of violating the Logan Act, which bans
private citizens from interfering with U.S. foreign policy.
   The Citizen Labor Energy Coalition, which says it has 12 million
members who favor low energy prices, wrote U.S. Attorney General
Edwin Meese urging that he prosecute Hance.
   ``It would appear that Commissioner Hance's efforts to assist
OPEC in fixing world oil prices are in direct opposition to U.S.
foreign and economic policy,'' the letter said. ``Commissioner
Hance is carrying on a blatant campaign to assist OPEC in raising
world oil prices and damaging U.S. economic interests.''
   The OPEC meeting ended Monday with no agreement on a proposed 2
percent cut in the group's oil production, a move aimed at
stabilizing prices that have undergone big fluctuations since late
1985.
   The proposal was made after six non-OPEC oil countries offered
to reduce their production if OPEC made a similar cut.
   ``I am disappointed that ... they did not reach an agreement.''
Hance said. ``I figured that if they didn't, prices would slide a
little temporarily and then they would come back.''
   Despite the meeting's breakdown, however, Hance said he agreed
with predictions that world oil prices would stabilize near recent
levels.
   In fact, prices did take a hard fall amid market disappointment
at the meeting's failure _ but not low enough to match levels that
existed before the OPEC session was called early last month.
   At the New York Mercantile Exchange, for example, West Texas
Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude, fell 85 cents a barrel to
$17.14 Monday. In early April, it had traded in high $16 range.
   For 40 years, the Texas Railroad Commission helped set world oil
prices. The commission has monitored oil output since an oil price
crash in the 1930s, and under state law the agency has authority to
restrict production to avoid waste and to protect reserves.
   Hance made no apologies for his trip, which also drew criticism
from the Reagan administration. He said Texas officials should
attend the next OPEC session in June because ``what happens in
Vienna at the OPEC meetings will have more impact on our economy
than anything that will happen in Austin or in Washington.''
   Hance invited OPEC's president, plus oil officials from several
other nations, to visit Texas and learn more about the Railroad
Commission's production monitoring system.
   ``Indonesia is coming Wednesday,'' he said, adding that OPEC's
president or his representative likely would visit the state this
summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
