<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1509EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-DalkonClaimants     05-03 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dalkon Claimants,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Opposition to Dalkon Shield Payoff Plan Is Challenged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition that has urged Dalkon Shield
claimants to vote against A.H. Robins Co.'s reorganization plan is
ignoring the advice of their own lawyers, a Robins spokesman said
Tuesday.
   ``They overlook the fact that the very committee that has
represented them for over two years is urging that the plan and the
system for settling claims be adopted,'' said spokesman Roscoe E.
Puckett Jr.
   At a Washington news conference Monday, Karen Hicks, president
of the Dalkon Shield Information Network, called Robins' proposed
plan of reorganization ``inadequate, unfair and contrary to law.''
   Ms. Hicks, representatives of consumer groups and some plaintiff
lawyers linked to Dalkon Shield lawsuits and Robins' reorganization
called for rejection of the plan, which was mailed to claimants
last week.
   The proposal includes Robins' merger with New York-based
American Home Products Corp. and a Dalkon Shield trust fund of at
least $2.475 billion.
   Puckett expressed puzzlement at the opposition.
   ``Our view is that we have a consensus of all the groups
involved in the case,'' he said. ``The reason for that is this plan
is fair.''
   U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. of Richmond, who is
overseeing Robins' Chapter 11 reorganization in U.S. Bankruptcy
Court, in December placed the $2.475 billion value on an estimated
195,000 Dalkon Shield claims before the court.
   ``It is important to remember that Judge Merhige has said that
the Dalkon Shield trust fund represents more money than anyone ever
thought would be available,'' Puckett said.
   A letter mailed by the claimants' committee to women who contend
they were injured by the birth control device said that ``as a
result of interest earnings, the funds available under the plan to
pay Dalkon Shield claims and expenses will exceed $2.475 billion.
... We recommend that you vote to accept the plan of
reorganization.''
   ``The plan is not perfect,'' the letter said. ``However, on
balance, the plan offers claimants the most money and the best
terms that could be achieved without a long and uncertain legal
fight.
   ``This is an opportunity to receive compensation for your claim
sooner and with greater certainty than if we were to continue the
litigation,'' the committee's letter said.
   Robins, a pharmaceutical manufacturer based in Richmond, sold
the intrauterine device in the the early 1970s. Robins filed for
reorganization under federal bankruptcy law in August 1985 as
lawsuits mounted against the Dalkon Shield.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
