<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed mostly lower
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in an see-saw session
influenced by conflicting interpretations of long-range weather
forecasts.
   ``If we had closed 15 minutes earlier, we would have closed
higher,'' said Victor Lespinasse, a trader for Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc. ``It's just been back and forth all day long.''
   Forecasts called for beneficial rains Tuesday in Missouri,
Nebraska and extreme southwestern Iowa, and a good chance for rain
Wednesday in central and southern Illinois. Those forecasts gave
the markets their negative tone.
   But six-to-10 day forecasts called for dryness and below-normal
temperatures in the east with wetter weather and above-normal
temperatures in the west.
   Traders had a hard time deciding whether the long-range
forecasts implied better or worse growing conditions, Lespinasse
said.
   ``The weather is ambiguous and the market reflected that
ambiguity today,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was { cent to 3{ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $2.97{ a bushel; corn was unchanged
to } cent lower with May at $2.04} a bushel; oats were 1\ cents to
1} cents lower with May at $1.57\ a bushel; soybeans were { cent to
3{ cents lower with May at $6.89 a bushel.
</TEXT>
