<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Gillette-Coniston Bjt   05-03 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gillette-Coniston, Bjt,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gillette Announces Narrow Victory In Proxy Fight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gillette Co. said Tuesday that its shareholders
narrowly rejected a bid by a group of New York investors to replace
four company directors and seek a buyer for Gillette's global
personal care empire.
   Analysts said most of the support for Gillette came from
individual shareholders interested in retaining a stable investment
and confused by the lack of definite sale plan by Coniston.
   A preliminary count of about 87 million shares voting in the
proxy election indicate that the four Gillette directors received
52 percent support, Gillette said. It said that tally exceeded the
48 percent of shareholder votes backing Coniston Group's slate of
directors for the three-year terms.
   The announcement culminates a proxy battle launched in February
by New York-based Coniston, which pledged to convince the other
eight directors to sell Gillette if its candidates were elected to
the board. Possible suitors included Revlon Group Inc., which ended
a series of takeover attempts in 1986 after Gillette paid about
$580 million to repurchase its shares.
   The proxy ballots were submitted during Gillette's April 21
annual meeting in Andover, Mass.
   After the ballots were cast both sides had claimed victory, with
Coniston noting support from many large institutional shareholders.
   Coniston principal Augustus K. Oliver vowed Tuesday to
immediately file a recount request, saying their ballot projections
were higher.
   ``We submitted a lot more votes than we seem to be getting
credit for,'' said Oliver. ``It puzzles us, and we'll try to figure
out exactly how many people were on our side.''
   Oliver also said Coniston attorneys may request a new election
as part of the ``equitable relief'' sought in a countersuit filed
last month in U.S. District Court claiming Gillette issued false
and misleading statements about Coniston during the three-month
proxy battle.
   A pre-trial hearing is scheduled Wednesday before Judge Rya
Zobel, who previously refused to issue a temporary restraining
order to block Coniston's proxy slate.
   In a suit filed last month, Gillette claims Coniston failed to
fully disclose all its financial backers in documents submitted to
the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
   In a prepared statement Tuesday, Gillette Chairman Colman M.
Mockler Jr. said the outcome shows shareholder support for
Gillette's performance since a 1986 restructuring, which included
2,400 layoffs and sale of several unprofitable divisions.
   At the annual meeting, several shareholders lauded Gillette
management's long-term plans and questioned Coniston's ultimate
intentions.
   ``Coniston never really had any definite plan on the table,''
said Pavlos Alexandrakis, an analyst at Argus Research in New York.
``There were no real buyers and no tender offer made. All they were
saying is that we'll have four people on a 12-member board and
we'll have some clout.''
   Mary Ann Winter, an analyst at Brown Brothers Harriman in New
York, said most shareholders are reluctant to give up their
investment in Gillette, which produces steady stock dividends.
   ``Here's a company with an annual growth rate of about 10
percent and stockholders do not want to give that up for a one-time
cash payment,'' said Winter. ``Institutional investors, on the
other hand, are looking for a profit each quarter ...''
   Coniston, a diversified investment firm, controls 6.76 million
Gillette shares, or about 5.8 percent of the company's 115.5
million shares outstanding.
   Last year, Coniston forced a major restructuring of Allegis
Corp. following a takeover attempt.
   Gillette spokeswoman Joan Fitzgerald said the company has no
comment on reports that officials had conducted negotiations with
several potential buyers.
   As a way to dilute the influence of Coniston's slate, Gillette
on April 20 amended its bylaws to increase the number of directors
needed to call a special meeting from two to seven.
</TEXT>
