<2ND_LINE>AM-Moore McCormack Sale,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Southdown, Moore McCormack to Sell Energy Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southdown Inc. and Moore McCormack Resources Inc.
announced Tuesday that they will sell a Moore McCormack energy
subsidiary for about $148.7 million to CanadianOxy Offshore
Production Co.
   The two resource companies said the proceeds from the sale of
Moore McCormack Energy Inc. will be used to help pay off loans made
to Southdown for its recent $512 million acquisition of Moore
McCormack Resources.
   CanadianOxy Offshore Production is a subsidiary of Occidental
Petroleum Corp., a major oil company based in Los Angeles.
   The sale of Dallas-based Moore McCormack Energy, which is
subject to regulatory approval, is expected to be completed by the
end of May following the impending merger of Southdown subsidiary
SDW Inc. with Moore McCormack Resources.
   Houston-based Southdown and Moore McCormack Resources, based in
Stamford, Conn., are both engaged in the production of cement and
concrete and in oil and gas operations. Moore McCormack Energy
explores for and produces oil and gas mainly in the Gulf Coast area
of Louisiana and Texas.
