<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 1620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MercTradingHalt Bjt   05-03 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Merc Trading Halt, Bjt,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sprinkler System Mishap Forces Trading Halt At Merc</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trading halted for more than 2{ hours Tuesday on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange after water from a burst pipe
flooded the exchange's telecommunications room, disabling its
automated price quotation system.
   The Chicago Mercantile Exchange is the leading U.S. market for
stock-index and livestock futures, and the trading shutdown had a
quieting effect on the nation's other financial markets, analysts
said.
   ``We don't know what caused it but it leaked a whole lot of
water,'' exchange spokesman Andrew Yemma said after trading resumed
at 10:45 a.m. CDT.
   Exchange officials called the trading halt at 8:05 a.m. CDT., 45
minutes after the opening of trading in foreign currency and
Treasury bill futures. Trading in stock-index and agricultural
futures had not yet opened when the halt was called, Yemma said.
   A large water pipe in the sprinkler system burst and flooded the
second-floor telecommunications room, located just below the
exchange's trading floor, he said.
   The water disabled the exchange's high-speed telephone lines,
which carry price quotes to subscribers of market-information
services around the world.
   The exchange's computers were not damaged, so trading could have
continued but ``the customers and users of the market wouldn't have
known what the prices were,'' Yemma said.
   During the trading halt, stock market players were unable to
hedge their equity investments via the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange's popular Standard & Poor's 500 futures contract. That may
have limited trading activity on the New York Stock Exchange,
analysts said.
   ``You're definitely not going to see anybody make a big play
without the futures open,'' said Arthur Liming, an analyst with LNS
Financial Group in Chicago.
   While the Merc was down, he said, ``There was one or two things
less to watch on what was a quiet day to begin with.''
   Yemma said it was impossible to calculate the dollar value of
the loss of volume at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Chicago's MidAmerica Commodity Exchange, which trades smaller
versions of the most popular futures contracts offered by other
exchanges, may have benefited from the Merc's problems, however.
   Spokesman William Murschel said the MidAm halted trading in its
stock-index, livestock, foreign currency and Treasury bill futures
at the same time as the Mercantile Exchange, then resumed trading
in those contracts at 10 a.m. CDT when it appeared the Merc might
be closed for a day or more.
   ``When the MidAm reopened, it really became the marketplace for
those contracts that were affected by the CME, so there was an
alternative marketplace available,'' Murschel said. ``It was the
MidAm's day in the sun.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
