<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-US     05-03 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-US,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Presses For South Korea To Remove Import Barriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States Tuesday asked South
Korea to protect American intellectual property rights and lift
sales restrictions on foreign cigarettes, government officials said.
   In the second day of a scheduled three-day trade meeting which
opened in Seoul on Monday, the United States also asked South Korea
to open its advertising and insurance markets, the officials said.
   ``The meeting was very useful. There were detailed discussions
on almost all pending issues,'' a South Korean official said after
Tuesday's talks.
   The 19-member U.S. delegation, headed by Peter Allgier,
assistant chief of the U.S. Trade Representative Office, demanded
that South Korea protect 911 U.S. chemical products which are
patented but not marketed, retroactive to Jan. 1, 1987, the
officials said.
   South Korea promised to reply to the U.S. request before the
Seoul meeting ends on Wednesday, they said.
   U.S. officials also called for the South Korean government to
tighten control on pirated books under a 1985 agreement, in which
Seoul officials promised to protect the U.S. copyrights, the
officials said.
   The United States took a critical stand on South Korea's
cigarette sales system and demanded that the prices of imported
foreign cigarettes be lowered to the level of domestic brands, they
said.
   Imported American cigarettes sell for $1.76 a pack compared with
81 cents a pack for the most expensive local brand.
   The United States also asked South Korea to permit cigarette
advertisements through all news media, but South Korea said the
advertisements would be limited to magazines, the officials said.
</TEXT>
