<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market advanced today, but most of its
gains were concentrated in blue-chip takeover targets and in
dividend-related trading.
   Analysts said that aside from pockets of activity, trading was a
bit lackluster. But they noted the market's improvement was more
apparent than in previous weeks.
   Much of the session's activity centered on heavy trading in
American Electric Power, which goes ex-dividend today.
   Takeover stocks also helped drive the market higher. Analysts
said these issues heated up in anticipation that cash will soon be
freed up as a handful of other takeover deals come to a close.
   Program traders were shut out of the market in the early going
because of a water main break at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the futures on the Standard & Poor's 500 index are traded.
Activity was halted for more than two and a half hours.
   Some analysts welcomed the respite. On Wall Street, ``it's a
refreshing case of a stock market rather than a casino,'' Metz said.
   Arbitragers remained mostly on the sidelines once futures
activity resumed, analysts said.
