<2ND_LINE>AM-Staley-Tate, Bjt,0441</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Staley Rejects British Firm's Sweetened Buyout Offer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROLLING MEADOWS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Staley Continental Inc. announced
Tuesday its board rejected a sweetened $1.42 billion takeover bid
from British sugar producer Tate & Lyle PLC and may consider other
offers.
   Staley Chairman Donald E. Nordlund said several unidentified
``third parties'' are interested in acquiring the company, based in
this northwest Chicago suburb.
   ``The company is continuing discussions with certain third
parties and expects to enter into negotiations,'' Nordlund said in
a statement issued by the company.
   In New York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday, Staley shares
advanced 50 cents to $38.375.
   Staley's board recommended that the company's stockholders
reject the $35-a-share bid, which was made last week and approved
Tuesday by Tate & Lyle shareholders meeting in London.
   When it first moved to take over Staley last month, the British
company offered $32 per share of common stock.
   Staley, the United States' second-larged refiner of corn
sweeteners behind Decatur-based Archer Daniels Midland Co., urged
its stockholders April 21 to reject the first offer.
   In its statement Tuesday, Staley said its financial advisers _
First Boston Corp. and Merrill Lynch Capital Markets _ had
concluded the revised Tate offer was ``inadequate.''
   Staley's board did not make a recommendation on Tate's offers of
$53.15 a share for depositary preferred stock or $105 a share for
cumulative preference stock.
   But the company's statement noted the British company's takeover
bid was conditioned on receiving a minimum number of common-stock
shares and that Staley's board has recommended rejecting the common
stock bid.
   In a related matter, Staley's board extended its ``poison pill''
anti-takeover defense until May 10 at 5 p.m. Tate's revised bid
expires at midnight (EDT) on that date.
   Spokesmen for the companies did not return telephone messages
Tuesday seeking comment. But industry analysts have said Staley has
a fair market value of about $40 a share.
   After Tate's first offer, Clinton Mayer III, an analyst in New
York with Bear Stearns Inc., said that if he were a Staley
stockholder, he probably wouldn't sell for less than $40.
   Tate & Lyle owns about 5 percent of Staley's stock and wants to
acquire the entire company for its A.E. Staley Manufacturing Co.
subsidiary, which produces corn sweeteners.
   Staley was based in Decatur, Ill., until about three years ago
when it moved its headquarters to Rolling Meadows. The British
company has promised to move Staley's headquarters back to the
central Illinois city if its takeover succeeds.
   Staley Continental also owns CFS Continental Inc., a leading
food-service supplier.
</TEXT>
