<FILEID>AP-NR-05-03-88 2114EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Koppers     05-03 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Attorneys Accuse Shearson Of Using Inside Information</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. accused Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. on Tuesday of improperly trading Koppers stock on the basis of
inside information about the $1.7 billion hostile takeover attempt
by Shearson and British industrialist Brian Beazer.
   A court document filed by Koppers attorneys said Shearson
brokers accumulated Koppers stock from January through early March
for managed discretionary customer accounts.
   During the same period, which ended the day before the Beazer
group announced a buyout offer, large amounts of Koppers stock were
sold for Shearson discretionary accounts and for discretionary and
managed discretionary accounts of Shearson's E.F. Hutton unit.
   ``Based on information disclosed, Shearson's managed accounts
performed as if they had a pipeline directly into the tender
offer,'' the attorneys said in court documents filed in U.S.
District Court in Pittsburgh.
   ``It is factually obvious that Shearson's preferential customers
were enriched at the expense of all other discretionary accounts,''
the documents stated.
   The allegations were included in a motion filed in connection
with Koppers' federal suit to block the Beazer group's takeover
attempt.
   BNS Inc., formed by Beazer, Shearson and National Westminster
Bank, has offered $60 a share to acquire the Pittsburgh-based
chemical and construction company.
   The investor group owns or has been tendered about 66 percent of
Koppers outstanding common shares, but is barred from purchasing
the tendered stock by two injunctions issued by federal judges in
Pittsburgh and Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
